<HEAD>
<TITLE>Tyna1028.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
October 28, 1996<BR>
<BR>
I was so excited about today.  I really had a chance to explore some techniques Iwould like to use in my own class.  I performed the experiment "Deadly Skies", and Mrs. French was a supreme help in the very first part of this experiment.  She planted paper towels soaked with vinegar all over the room.  Unfortunately the vinegar dissipated 
very quickly and only a few of the kids noticed the smell.  We talked about air pollution and how easy it was to clean our environment of the vinegar towels, but it is not so easy to clean a habitat being destroyed by acid rain.  <BR>
The kids helped me design a concept map about acid precipitation.  We discussed the activity (planting seeds so we could water one tin with water, and one with vinegar) and came up with three hypotheses about what would happen to the tin watered with vinegar.  They helped me design a chart we could use to record our observations.  We will actually be viewing the effect of an acid on a habitat over a period of time.<BR>
I practiced more of a lecture procedure but incorporated quite a bit of student participation through the concept map and development of the hypotheses.  I felt very good about the activity.  After we finished talking, I had the students record the concept map in their notebooks as well as copy the chart we had all designed.  I am not sure if I handled that correctly.  I probably should have had them copying as we 
went along, but I was a bit afraid of losing their train of thought.  I think I could have done it while they were recording and not worried so much about it.<BR>
We planted the seeds and then went up to the library and finished the research they need for Wednesdays lesson.  Today was definitely a good day with quite a bit of thought provoking results.  I would like to incorporate more of this type of teaching in my class.  I used the chalkboard, but I would prefer an overhead.  I wasn't real comfortable 
having to turn my back on them even for the seconds it took me to record a statement on the board.<P>

