<HEAD>
<TITLE>Tyna114.html</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
November 4, 1996<BR>
<BR>
I missed Friday, the kids were at the Canton farm and I couldn't make it.  Today was a good day.  Last Monday we focused on acid rain and air pollution.  This week we wanted to focus a bit more on water pollution itself.  The kids helped me design another concept map, this one for water pollution.  The concept map listed all four major types and I had them help give me as much detail as possible.  I notice even more today how much I dislike using the chalkboard.  I intensely dislike having my back to the kids.  I do like using overheads.  Perhaps next time I have a lesson which involves designing a concept map or a brainstorming session in which I want the kids to record 
information I will use an overhead!<BR>
After we finished with that, I had them split into two groups depending on their interests.  One group would draw pictures which described things that could be done to keep the water clean - aid against pollution, and the other group had to come up with a contract which they will sign that clearly states their intentions to fight against pollution.  The kids got off to a slow start with this one but eventually got into it.  I am wondering if we are not bogging them down with all these pollution concepts. They remarked to me that they could do nothing - basically they were powerless.  I attempted to convince them otherwise and I think I achieved that goal somewhat, 
but it is from this that my worries stem.<P>

