<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DT><!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DT><DT><HTML>
<DT><DT><HEAD>
<DT><DT><TITLE>lespfve</TITLE>
<DT><DT></HEAD>
<DT><DT><!-- Body Tag --><BODY BACKGROUND="back2.gif">
<DT><DT></BODY>
<DT><DT><BR>
<DT><DT>
<DD>     <DD>     <H3><EM><CENTER><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#AFCEFF">Lesson #4:  Classification of Plants</FONT></FONT></B></CENTER></EM></H3>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <B><I><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#AFCEFF">Pedagogy:</FONT></FONT></I></B>  This lesson is to develop an appreciation of plants for the students.  
<DD>     <DD>     They will learn that plants serve many important functions within the ecosystem. 
<DD>     <DD>      Also, the students will learn to discern between various aspects of plant structure- 
<DD>     <DD>     leaf texture, leaf arrangement, stem type and presence of certain "other" structures (pistil, stamen, etc..). <BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#AFCEFF">Phase 1:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Either at the site, or on school grounds, the students will choose ten <STRONG>different </STRONG>
<DD>     <DD>     leaves.  This activity is adapted from the activity "Leaf Impressions" found on the 
<DD>     <DD>     World Wide Web at the URL address:       http://207.22.231.50:80/nsta_scripts/List_SSC_byGrade.idc 
<DD>     <DD>      <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     In their journals, they will draw a picture of the leaf, depicting it as accurately 
<DD>     <DD>     as possible.  Along with the drawing, a short description of the plant it came from 
<DD>     <DD>     must be given.  The students will then put the leaves between wax paper, iron them, and keep them in their journal.  This will provide them with a comparison of a variety of leaf types.  After this is finished, the field guide classification will begin. 
The student must identify, correctly, the type of plant the leaf came from.  The information used will be taken from the journal descriptions and leaf characteristics (one or two 45 minute periods).<BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#AFCEFF">Phase 2:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Journal Entry- What purpose or purposes do(es) a plant serve to the ecosystem?<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     The classification will continue.  When every student has found a classification for 
<DD>     <DD>     each leaf, a class discussion will ensue.  This talk will contain such information 
<DD>     <DD>     as to why they classified the plant where they did, and what certain characteristics 
<DD>     <DD>     were used to lead them to their conclusion (30 minutes).<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     A brainstorming session will follow, and the students must say what they think the 
<DD>     <DD>     plants are used for and how important they believe them to be.  The purpose of this 
<DD>     <DD>     is to allow the students to generate ideas on their own, and give them the opportunity to express their own thinking and beliefs (10-15 minutes).<BR><P>


<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#AFCEFF">Phase 3:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Journal Entry- Do plants provide a lot of energy to the nutrient cycles?<BR>
<DD>     <DD>      Cranial creation #42, from <CITE>Cranial Creations in Life Science</CITE> by Downing and Miller, p.170 will be performed .  This activity is designed to bring all that has been studied on this topic before into one experience.  It is a good way for the teacher to actually measure the amount of learned material for each student.  They will work in groups of two, and create a cartoon which relates the importance of plants to the ecosystem.  Four words are chosen from the free association conducted on day two and incorporated into the cartoon.  Again, the students should be encouraged to derive their own ideas.  Therefore, a vague idea or description is acceptable (45 minutes).
<DD>     <DD>     </BODY>
<DD>     <DD>     </HTML>
<DD>     </DL>
</DL>
