<center>
<strong>XI.  COLLEGE SERVICES</strong></center>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A"><b>A</a>.	COLLEGE FACILITIES AND SERVICES</b>

	<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A1"><i>1</a>.	ATHLETIC FACILITIES</I>

		<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A1a">a</a>)	Maxcy Hall
<dt><br>
			<dt>Maxcy Hall, the College's modern sports complex, contains a field house with a 1/10 mile indoor track, an ice arena, an Olympic-size swimming pool, six racquetball and three squash courts, three basketball courts, a large exercise/weight training room, a free exercise room, a wrestling room, a dance studio, a study lounge, three classrooms, and a therapy/training room, as well as locker and shower rooms.  Surrounding Maxcy Hall are 50 acres of playing fields, tennis courts, and a 1/4 mile track.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A1b">b</a>)	Use Of Facilities

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A1bi">i</a>)	Privileges
<dt><br>
				<dt>Faculty and staff members have the same privileges in the building as do students.  Added to that, faculty and staff have the privilege of reserving racquetball courts by telephone (students must appear in person) and have exclusive use of the courts during the weekday noon hour.
<dt><br>
<dt>Children of faculty, staff or students, fourteen years of age or older, have the same privileges in the building as do students (except they cannot participate in intramurals or informal hockey).  Children, ages thirteen and under, can only use the facilities when they are directly supervised by their parent(s).
<dt><br>
<dt>The Friday, Saturday and Sunday family swim hours are set aside as a special time for faculty and staff families to swim together.  Faculty, staff and students may bring their children to this program provided they can either swim or touch bottom (the shallow end is four feet).

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A1bii">ii</a>)	Lockers
<dt><br>
				<dt>Lockers in either faculty locker rooms are only available when someone vacates their current locker.  Children of faculty are not privileged to use the faculty locker room.  Lockers are available in the main locker rooms and may be obtained from the Programs and Operations Office.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A1biii">iii</a>)	Access To Building
<dt><br>
				<dt>Access to the facilities is via the doors on the front (west side) of Maxcy Hall.  All other doors serve as emergency exits or service entrances.      

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A1biv">iv</a>)	I.D.
<dt><br>
				<dt>Everyone using the facility must have a college identification card to participate.  Each individual must have their own card.  Cards may be obtained by contacting Human Resources.  Children, 13 and under, will be admitted only when accompanied by their parent(s).  

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A1bv">v</a>)	Building Hours
<dt><br>
				<dt>Regular activity hours within the building are  8 a.m. to 10 p.m. weekdays and noon to 6 p.m. weekends.
<dt><br>
<dt>Naturally some areas periodically will be unavailable for general use because classes or games are scheduled and/or special repair or maintenance projects occur.
<dt><br>
<dt>Hours for the activity areas (exercise/fitness center, racquetball, free swim, open skating, field house track, gymnasium) are posted throughout the building.
</dl>
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A2"><i>2</a>.	AUDIO-VISUAL EQUIPMENT</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Audio-visual equipment is normally available in each College building through the Office of the Building Administrator.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A3"><i>3</a>.	CAMPUS MAP</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Campus maps are available from the Public Safety Office.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A4"><i>4</a>.	CHECK CASHING SERVICES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>All SUNY Potsdam faculty, staff and students are offered check cashing services  at the College Store, located in the Student Union, between the hours of 12 noon and 3 p.m., Monday through Friday during the academic year when classes are in session.  In addition, an automated teller machine (ATM) supplied by Marine Midland Bank is located in the lobby of the Student Union.  Please contact the bank directly with any questions.
<dt><br>
		<dt>There is a check cashing limit on personal checks of $25.00 per person, per day.  Guaranteed fund instruments such as payroll checks, cashier's checks, money orders and travelers checks are cashed subject to the availability of funds.  There is a service charge of 25 cents per check.


	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A5"><i>5</a>.	COLLEGE FOUNDATION</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Potsdam College Foundation, a non-profit corporation, was formed to solicit, receive, and distribute funds from private sources in support of the College's mission.  Governed by an independent Board of Trustees, the Foundation is responsible for all external fundraising activities associated with SUNY Potsdam.
<dt><br>
<dt>Income from the Foundation's endowment and the proceeds of its Annual Fund Drive have been used to support student aid, for purchase of equipment, for support of Admission's activities and in support of Alumni activities.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A6"><i>6</a>.	CUSTODIAL SERVICES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Special custodial services should be requested through the Department Chair, Director or Building Administrator as appropriate using a Work Order Request Form and submitting it to the Office of Physical Plant.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A7"><i>7</a>.	DESK AND DOOR SIGNS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Small engraved signs for desks and doors may be ordered from the Office of Physical Plant using a Work Order Request Form.  Departments ordering signs will be recharged for materials.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A8"><i>8</a>.	DUPLICATING AND PRINTING SERVICES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>SUNY Potsdam and Canton College have combined in a centralized printing service for both colleges.
<dt><br>
<dt>All departments should bring their work to the Potsdam Duplicating Services Center.  Departments are asked to refrain from sending duplicating or printing to the Canton College Print Shop on their own.
<dt><br>
<dt>When preparing a duplicating job, departments are asked to allow sufficient time to get the job done.
      <dt><br>   
<dt>Prices for work done by the two operations--(1)  the Duplicating Services Center and the Canton College Print Shop are listed in <A HREF =" ../Appendices/Appen15.html">Appendix XV.</a>

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A9">9</a>.	<I>EMPLOYEE ASSISTANCE PROGRAM (EAP)</I></a>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A9a">a</a>)	Purpose
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Employee Assistance Program (EAP) is a confidential referral program which offers assistance to employees to cope with personal problems which negatively affect their lives and which might intrude upon their jobs.  Emotional stress, family disintegration, financial and legal difficulties, alcoholism, drug abuse and marital disruption impair not only an employee's personal life, but workplace productivity.  EAP was formed with the knowledge that such problems can be addressed and treated with appropriate help.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A9b">b</a>)	Service Provided
<dt><br>
<dt>EAP is a confidential information, support and referral service.  It is not a counseling service, nor does it provide treatment.  Using the referral services of EAP is not a condition of employment.  Depending upon the nature of the problem, employees seeking assistance are referred to a program, service or agency within the community for appropriate counseling or assistance.
<dt><br>
<Dt>Involvement in this program is entirely voluntary and services of EAP are free of charge.  Employee benefits may cover the expenses of other referral agencies.
<dt><br>
<dt>The SUNY Potsdam EAP office is located in Morey Hall, Room 105.  Employees calling EAP are not restricted to Potsdam coordinators.  Any EAP coordinator from any state agency can be contacted.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A9c">c</a>)	Eligibility And Referral
<dt><br>
			<dt>The EAP is open to all College and PACES employees, retirees and their families.  An employee may enter EAP through self- referral, supervisor referral, or a third party (family member, union representative, friend, co-worker, clergy, etc.)
<dt><br>
<dt>It is important to remember that the final decision to contact the Employee Assistance Program lies with the employee.  EAP is a voluntary option.
</dl>
	</dl>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A11"><i>10</a>.	I.D. CARD</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>All employees are expected to have an identification card.  Sometime prior to the beginning of employment, you should visit the I.D. Office, Thatcher Hall, for the purpose of having an I.D. card made.
<dt><br>
<dt>In addition to providing identification for security of buildings and facilities purposes, an I.D. card provides access to the use of College facilities, such as Maxcy Hall and Crumb Library.
<dt><br>
		<dt>The I.D. Office is open Monday through Friday from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m. and no appointment is necessary.  There is no cost for the initial I.D. card, however, if the card is lost, a fee will be charged for the replacement.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A12"><i>11</a>.	MAIL</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The College's central mail room is located on the first floor of Carson Hall and is under the supervision of the Office of Physical Plant.  The following procedures are followed in the operation of the College's mail service:

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>a)	All mailboxes are assigned by the Office of Physical Plant.  

</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>b)	All outgoing, 1st class mail requires an account number on it to accurately account for postage used.  Mail stamps with account numbers will be provided by the above office.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
		<dt>c)	Official college mail on which the College pays the postage should be left unsealed to facilitate the use of the stamping machine.  All other mail must have the proper postage affixed and sealed.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
		<dt>d)	All requests for use of a mail IFR account are to be submitted to the above office.  An account number and mail stamp will be assigned, as required.  Complete billing information must be provided by the user department.               
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
		<dt>e)	All outgoing mail deposited after 3:00 p.m. will be processed for next day delivery to the Post Office.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
		<dt>f)	All mail with like account number shall be rubber banded together.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
		<dt>g)	All on campus mail for faculty and staff shall be sorted and rubber banded together by department.  Student mail for on campus shall be sorted by dormitory and rubber banded together.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
		<dt>h)	Third class bulk mailings must comply with USPS regulations which are available from our mail personnel.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
		<dt>i)	Faculty and staff are encouraged to make use of messenger envelopes for on-campus mail.  These envelopes receive special handling and are not mixed with U.S. mail and they are afforded faster handling.  They provide for multiple re-use and are therefore very economical.  
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A13"><i>12</a>.	NOTARY PUBLIC</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The services of a Notary Public free of charge to all faculty, staff, and students may be obtained from a number of employees at various locations on campus including the Office of Human Resources.  

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A14"><i>13</a>.	POTSDAM AUXILIARY AND COLLEGE EDUCATIONAL SERVICES, INC. (PACES)</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A14a">a</a>)	General Information
<dt><br>
			<dt>PACES is a Type B, Not-For-Profit Corporation organized under the laws of the State of New York; this means that there are no stockholders and that income cannot accrue to the benefit of any member of the corporation, but must be used to benefit the College directly.  In the event of dissolution of PACES, its assets must be transferred to the State University of New York for the benefit of the State University of New York College at Potsdam.    
<dt><br>
<dt>PACES is authorized to function on the College campus by virtue of a contractual agreement with the State University of New York.  This contract mandates conformance with broad guidelines which have been prepared for all campuses of State University.  Within the framework of such broad guidelines, policy decisions and budgetary decisions are the responsibility of the Board of Directors of PACES.  It should be noted, however, that the budget recommended by the Board of Directors must receive final approval from the President of the College and the Central Office of State University of New York.  The fiscal year runs from June 1 to May 31.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A14b">b</a>)	Purpose
<dt><br>
			<dt>PACES was incorporated in 1950 for the following purposes:
<dt><br>
			<dd>* To operate a college dining program.
<dt><br>
			<dd>* To operate a college store.
<dt><br>
			<dd>* To operate a college loan fund.
<dt><br>
			<dd>* To provide banking services for student activity accounts and   other accounts not included in the regular College budget.
<dt><br>
			<dd>* To generate income for the purpose of improving the   total program of the College.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A14c">c</a>)	The College Store
<dt><br>
			<dt>The College Store is located in the Barrington Student Union.  Its prime function is to provide the student with the textbooks and supplies required for the pursuit of his or her academic goals.  In addition, The College Store strives to serve the needs of the total student by stocking a variety of merchandise which includes a large selection of books for leisure reading, personal items, greeting cards, magazines and SUNY Potsdam memorabilia.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A14d">d</a>)	Star Lake Campus
<dt><br>
			<dt>The College's conference, outdoor education, and recreation center owned and operated by PACES is located on the western slope of the Adirondack Mountains on Star Lake, adjacent to over a half million acres of State Forest Wilderness Area.  Star Lake Campus facilities include a rustic lodge with full dining services, classrooms, recreation room, sauna, glass-enclosed pavilion, several types of housing accommodations, cross-country skiing and hiking trails, beach and dock area.  Recreational equipment available includes canoes, sailboats, paddleboats, rowboats, fishing tackle, camping gear and cross-country skiing equipment.
<dt><br>
<dt>The campus is available for educational, recreational and social programs for both SUNY Potsdam groups and the general public.
  <dt><br>
			<dt>Star Lake Camp Board, an SGA-funded student organization, supervises student activities and provides social programs for College groups that come to Star Lake Campus.  Students, faculty, and staff utilize the facilities as a retreat center for study weekends, workshops, relaxation and a change of environment.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A14e">e</a>)	Dining Services
<dt><br>
			<dt>Dining Services locations include the Student Union Snack Bar, Lehman & Thatcher Dining Halls, The Greenery in Carson Hall, Crane Snack Bar and the Bakery and Commissary located in Bowman Dining Hall.  It also provides catering services for both on-campus and off-campus groups.  Meal plans are available for faculty and staff members.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A14f">f</a>)	Administrative and Vending Services
<dt><br>
			<dt>PACES provides accounting and banking services for College groups and organizations.  All on-campus organizations are entitled to maintain their accounts with PACES.  PACES also manages all vending on campus, both washers and dryers and food and amusement vending.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A14g">g</a>)	Loan Fund
<dt><br>
			<dt>PACES operates a modest loan fund for full-time students during the regular academic year.  These loans are for emergency purposes and are usually for a short time.  Information is available in the Office of Financial Aid.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A14h">h</a>)	Miscellaneous
<dt><br>
			<dt>PACES not only provides service to the academic community, but it also serves as an employer to more than 100 full-time employees and approximately 400 students.  The majority of these staff members work in Dining Services.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A15"><i>14</a>.	POTSDAM REPORTER</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>THE POTSDAM REPORTER a weekly publication of the Office of College Relations, serves as a campus bulletin board.  College policy, faculty governance issues, vacancies, the calendar of events and workshops, and research opportunities are included to help assure the campus community of accurate, timely information.  Copy should be submitted in writing by 4 p.m. each Monday to College Relations, Room 602, Raymond Hall.  Items may also be submitted via e-mail to the address "REPORTER" or via the Macintosh Reporter drop box.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A16"><i>15</a>.	PUBLIC SAFETY</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Public Safety at SUNY Potsdam consists of a team of people working with the campus community to create a safe environment in which to live, work, and learn.  The department is primarily service-oriented, created to meet the specialized needs of a College campus.  The work of the department includes crime prevention and control, criminal investigations, traffic and parking supervision, physical plant security, emergency first aid treatment, the maintenance of public order and other related activities.
<dt><br>
<dt>The officers of the department are responsible for the enforcement of all state and local laws as well as rules and regulations of the College.  The department's ability to function as an independent law enforcement agency enables it to provide a sensitive, measured approach to all situations requiring police assistance while still maintaining the autonomy of the University.
<dt><br>
<dt>Public Safety officers are peace officers as designated in Section 2.20 of the Criminal Procedure Law.  This section basically gives Public Safety Officers the authority to make arrests, conduct criminal investigations, issue Uniform Traffic Tickets, execute warrants and issue summonses for parking, as well as enforce any general, special or local law or charter, rule, regulation, judgment or order.
<dt><br>
<dt>As Peace Officers, Public Safety Officers receive 16 weeks of training at the Public Safety Basic Training Academy in Albany.  This training is mandated by the Bureau for Municipal Police and is in compliance with that established by the Municipal Police Training Council. 
<dt><br>
		<dd>Some of the services provided the College campus are:
<dt><br>
			<dd>- render emergency first aid when necessary
<dt><br>
			<dd>- assist motorists with minor problems or call for service if   necessary
<dt><br>
			<dd>- open doors in emergency situations and within College policy guidelines
<dt><br>
			<dd>- conduct fire drills and safety inspections
<dt><br>
			<dd>- notify of emergencies (death, serious illness)
<dt><br>
			<dd>- lecture on various law enforcement and safety topics
<dt><br>
			<dd>- conduct rape prevention programs
<dt><br>
			<dd>- conduct operation I.D. program
<dt><br>
			<dd>- patrol dorms on foot
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Department of Public Safety is located in Dunn Hall.  Officers are on duty 24 hours a day, seven days a week.
<dt><br>
<dt>For emergencies on campus, dial 267-2222.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A17"><i>16</a>.	FACULTY SCHOLARSHIP AND GRANTS OFFICE</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Faculty Scholarship and Grants is that branch of the College which is responsible for all pre and post award activity involving grants and contracts from federal, state and private agencies.  The Faculty Scholarship and Grants Office is here to help faculty and staff in the preparation of proposals and must process all proposals committing institutional resources, i.e. faculty and/or facilities. 
<dt><br>
<dt>Employees wishing assistance in the preparation of proposals should contact the Faculty Scholarship and Grants Office at least four weeks prior to the sponsor deadline.  Initial drafts should be prepared by departmental personnel.  Subsequent revisions and final proposals can be produced by the Faculty Scholarship and Grants Office if time allows.  Faculty Scholarship and Grants will review the proposal to insure compliance with sponsor and state guidelines and regulations and prepare it for institutional approval.
<dt><br?
<dt>The Faculty and Scholarship and Grants Office is available to assist you with the following:
<dt><br>
			<dd>- assistance in identifying potential sponsors using a variety   of directories and the SPIN computer database;
<dt><br>
			<dd>- interpretation of guidelines, outlining proposals, typing assistance, budget advice and preparation, editing and critiquing of institutional and individual proposals;
<dt><br>
			<dd>- responsible for securing Provost and other institutional signatures as required;
<dt><br>
			<dd>- photocopying, packaging and mailing of final proposals
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Faculty Scholarship and Grants Office publishes a bi-monthly newsletter on or about the fifteenth of the month.  Issues include topics such as funding opportunities targeted for the arts, humanities, sciences, education and miscellaneous; institutional policies regarding the seeking of external funds; announcements of campus funding sources; proposal activity and funds awarded; and a listing of future deadlines.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A18"><i>17</a>.	SUPPLIES - OFFICE AND CLASSROOM</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Examination paper, stationery, chalk, pencils, and other routine office and classroom supplies are stocked in the College Storehouse.  They may be obtained on requisition from the Purchasing Office.  Supplies will be delivered to the ordering department.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A19"><i>18</a>.	TELEPHONE</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>It is the policy of the College to provide the most efficient and economical telecommunications system possible to support the operations of the College.  Telephone service is provided to the College community by an AT&T Definity G3R telephone switch.  Voice Mail is provided by an AT&T AUDIX System.
<dt><br>
<dt>The College presently utilizes AT&T as our long distance carrier.  This carrier requires the use of a seven digit authorization code to complete long distance, international and information calls.  Authorization codes are available from the office of Distributed Computing/Telemedia.    Personal authorization codes are available upon request, but require a supervisor's approval.  A supervisor may, at his/her discretion, restrict certain phones to campus or campus and local calls, only.
<dt><br>
<dt>Faculty and staff may request personal authorization codes by completing a Telephone/Network Services Request form.  This code will allow the individual to make personal calles from work and be charged for these calls.
<dt><br>
<dt>Our local calling area consists of the following exchanges:  262; 265; 267; 268; 322; 328; 353; 379 and 386.
<dt><br>
<dt>The telephone system is coordinated through the Office of Distributed Computing/Telemedia.  Please direct any questions regarding phone service to Brenda Bennett at extension 3000. 
<dt><br>
<dt>The following is a brief description of our most commonly used dialing patterns:
<dt><br>
		<dd>Local Calls:		Dial 9 followed by the complete seven digits of the number you are dialing.
<dt><br>
		<dd>On-Campus Calls:	Dial the last four digits.<br>
		<dd>(Includes Students)      
<dt><br>
		<dd>800 Calls:			Dial 9, then 1-800 and the last seven digits of the 800 number you are dialing. Authorization codes are not required to place 800 calls.
<dt><br>
		<dd>Long Distance Calls:	Dial 9-1, the area code (only if outside 315) and then the seven digits of the number you are calling, followed by your seven digit authorization code.
<dt><br>
		<dd>Information Calls:	Dial 9-1-Area Code-555-1212 and your seven digit authorization code.
<dt><br>
		<dd>International Calls:	Dial 9-011, the country code, city code, and the number you are calling, wait for 3 beeps, then enter your seven digit authorization code.
<dt><br>
		<dd>Card Calls:	Dial 9-0, then the area code and the complete seven digits of the number you are calling.  You will then get the AT&T Network and may place your call by entering your credit card number.
<dt><br>
		<dd>If you wish to use an alternate carrier for credit card calls, please contact your carrier for instructions.
<BR>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="11A20"><i>19</a>.	FACSIMILE MACHINE</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Throughout the campus facsimile machines are located for use by other campus offices/ departments.  The machine transmits and receives printed material via telephone lines within seconds.  Facsimile can be an economical (and reliable) alternative to mail service.
</dl></dl>
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
<dt><br>
<br>
