Content-length: 4581
</DOCHDR>
<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>lespfor</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<!-- Body Tag --><BODY BACKGROUND="back2.gif">
</BODY>
<BR>

<H3><EM><CENTER><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF6B20"><!-- List Tag --><DL>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>     Lesson #3:  Structural Relationships
<DD>     </DL>
</DL></FONT></FONT></B></CENTER></EM></H3>
<BR>
<BR>
<B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><I><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF6B20"><!-- List Tag --><DL>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>     Pedagogy:
<DD>     </DL>
</DL></FONT></I></FONT></B> <!-- List Tag --><DL>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>     Since the students can now recognize an ecosystem and the individual patterns and cycles within it, they are ready to learn the scientific classification for the organisms found there too.
<DD>     </DL>
</DL><BR><BR>

<EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF6B20"><!-- List Tag --><DL>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>     Phase 1:
<DD>     </DL>
</DL></FONT></FONT></B> </EM>
 <!-- List Tag --><DL>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>     Journal Entry- To group something under a specific category, what characteristics would you look for?<BR>
<DD>     <DD>       One microscope will be set up at a station in the classroom.  Under the microscope is a specific organism, but there will be twenty five to thirty living and non-living objects/organisms the students will be required to observe.  The students go from one station to the next, studying and observing the physical properties of the organism/object located there.  When they have visited each station, and returned to their seat, they must organize and classify the organism in their own way (30 minutes).  A reason(s) must be given to support their choices.  There will be a class discussion relating to the type of classification used.  For example, the students may classify them shape, size, color, alive, or not alive, etc...  Following this, the students will create a concept map which shows their method of thinking, and how they got to the classification scheme.  As a group, the students must agree on which method used, was the most advantageous (15 minutes).
<DD>     </DL>
</DL><BR><BR>

<EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF6B20"><!-- List Tag --><DL>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>     Phase 2:
<DD>     </DL>
</DL></FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>       This days lesson serves as a continuation of the previous day.  The students are now using live specimens which they will collect / observe at the site.  The observed characteristics of the specimens will be recorded in their journals.  Type of specimens collected will include insects, fish, plants, small animals, and rocks.  The fish will be collected by using kick-nets provided by the Gouverneur school district.  All of the specimens will be kept alive and released after the information is obtained (30 minutes).  Upon completion, the students will discuss and give reasons describing specific characteristics of their organism.  A hypothesis pertaining to the correct classification of that organism must also be given by the student.  The five Kingdom approach will be touched on at the very end, and compared to the previously used approach (15 minutes).  They will all be handed a card with one organism on it, and they will be given a five Kingdom map.  As homework, they must classify that organism according to the five Kingdom classification system.  At some time on this day, the students will have to take a soil sample form this site for future experiments. 
<DD>     </DL>
</DL><BR>
   <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF6B20"><!-- List Tag --><DL>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>     Phase 3:
<DD>     </DL>
</DL></FONT></FONT></B></EM>
 <!-- List Tag --><DL>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>      Journal Entry- Do you think the five Kingdoms approach is more accurate and reliable than the methods used by yourselves at first?  <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     On this day, students will go to the library and research the organisms found at the site.  This search will serve to provide them with the correct classifications for that organism (30 minutes).  When all the organisms have been designated a classification, the students will devise a flow chart which demonstrates the student's understanding of hierarchical classification (10-15 minutes).  The more branches there are is indicative of a greater understanding.
<DD>     </DL>
</DL>
</BODY>
</HTML>
