<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chapter 12 10-17</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#ff00ff">

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=87  SRC="../FACBOOK.GIF"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<center>
<strong>XII.  CAMPUS POLICIES</strong>
</center>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="12A"><b>A</a>.	CAMPUS POLICIES AND PROCEDURES</b>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="12A10"><i>10</a>.	BOMB THREAT</i>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>THE MOST important concern in any threat to campus property or people is to provide quick and orderly safety to all concerned.  Secondary but also important is the clarity with which campus functions will proceed while under the emergency procedures.  Guidelines for bomb threats are as follows.
<dt><br>
<dt>1.	The Director of Public Safety will determine the need for closing one or more buildings or events.
<dt><br>
		<dt>2.	At the point a building is closed or event is terminated an attempt will be made to suggest the duration, i.e. "closed for the day," or "postponed until ________."
<dt><br>
		<dt>3.	The Director of Public Safety will, in conjunction with the Assistant Vice President for Facilities, post notices on the building and, if appropriate, identify where continued information and services can be forwarded. "Class information will be available in the Barrington Union" or "____________ services will be provided in _________________ ."
<dt><br>
		<dt>4.	The Director of Public Safety will notify the Provost, Vice President for Student Life, the Office of Human Resources, and the Director of College Relations who will in turn notify appropriate services and teaching units.		
<dt><br>
	<dt>5.	All personnel not instructed by the above will report to the Office of Human Resources.
<dt><br>
		<dt>6.	In the event Dunn Hall and main switchboard cannot be the communication center, emergency phones will be established in Barrington Student Union.
<dt><br>
		<dt>7.	Director of College relations will serve as primary media contact. 
<dt><br>
		<dt>*** Any employee receiving a threatening call should immediately call Public Safety at *2222..  Special attention to such as the following are crucial:  Sex of caller, background noise, type of "bomb" and any location specifics.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl><!-- 1 -->
</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl><!-- 0 -->
	<dt><A NAME="12A11"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>11</a>.	BUILDING ADMINISTRATOR:  POLICIES AND RESPONSIBILITIES</i>
 <dt><br>
		<dt>Each academic building on the SUNY Potsdam campus shall have a building administrator, preferably a person already residing in that building.  The building administrator shall be appointed by the President of the College after appropriate consultation.  He/she shall be willing and able to assume the position and all associated responsibilities.  The appointee shall be a full-time member of the faculty, professional or administrative staff of the College.  He/she shall serve for a period of one year, the appointment to be made at the beginning of the Fall semester and be renewable each year thereafter.  The building administrator is the chief administrator in charge of his/her building at the direction of the President of the College and is ultimately responsible for the well-being of the facility.  The building administrator will have the authority to make decisions and carry out those duties which affect comfort, convenience, safety and energy conservation.  In this regard, the building administrator will work closely with the Offices of Physical Plant, Public Safety and his/her building custodians.  The building administrator's name, office and telephone numbers and official building hours shall be prominently posted in the main lobby of his/her building.
<dt><br>
<dt>Specifically, the building administrator shall:
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
<dt>a)	Perform his/her responsibilities in a competent, positive and timely fashion.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>b)	Be authorized to delegate selected responsibilities associated with the position to one or more individuals in that building with the understanding that the building administrator is ultimately responsible for decisions or policies made regarding use of the facility.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>c)	Make regular tours of his/her building making sure that all equipment and facilities essential to good work/study practices are in proper working order.  All irregularities that cannot be taken care of by the regular building custodians shall be referred to the  building administrator.  He/she shall then prepare a work order and send it to the Office of Physical Plant for action.  (A written record of such findings will be kept by the building administrator.)

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>d)	Shall be notified of and act on all requests to use facilities after normal working hours or on weekends making sure that such utilization does not violate College policies.  All approved requests must have written authorization from the building administrator. All requests for keys must also have his/her written authorization.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>e)	Accompany Public Safety, Physical Plant representatives and state inspectors on all scheduled safety and fire prevention tours.  The building administrator shall make certain that all potentially dangerous situations and particularly those conditions that affect the handicapped are immediately referred to the appropriate administrative office.  He/she shall also make certain that necessary information recorded during fire drills is submitted to the Office of Public Safety.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>f)	Be notified of all accidental occurrences in his/her building and keep a record of such.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>g)	Be apprised in advance of all activities regarding structural modification, scheduling pesticide spraying or changes in College policies which might affect building usage.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>h)	Act on requests to use audio-visual hardware and other equipment already under the supervision of the building administrator.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>i)	When requested, meet with the Environment Advisory Committee for the purpose of providing input on matters of safety, comfort and energy conservation.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>j)	Serve as a member of a group of all building administrators, this group to constitute the Council of Building Administrators to be convened by the President of the College or designee at the beginning of the Fall semester.  At this time, the President will officially appoint building administrators and discuss responsibilities and policies.
          <dt><br>
<dt>The names of Building Administrators are listed in <A HREF="../appendices/APPEN12.html">Appendix XII.</a></BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl><!-- 1 -->
</dl><!-- 0 -->
<dt>
<dd><dl>
	<dt><A NAME="12A12"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>12</a>.	BUILDING USE</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Building use by any individual or organization must be recognized by the campus as educationally oriented and non profit in nature.  Student organizations must be recognized by the Student Government Association; Faculty and Staff organizations recognized by the College administration, and non-College affiliated users approved by the President or his/her designee.  (Director of Continuing Education.)

<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A12a">a</A>)	Use by College Affiliated Group - Building use by any College affiliated group or individual is approved by the individual building administrator and related directly to the scheduling of the spaces within the facility involved.  General instructional space on campus such as classrooms, lecture halls, etc. are scheduled by the Office of the College Registrar.  Specific dedicated instructional spaces are normally scheduled either by the academic unit involved and/or the building administrator.  In each case, the building administrator is aware of the scheduled use of all such direct instructional spaces within the building over which he/she has jurisdiction.  Therefore, the single contact with the building administrator provides the necessary input as to the availability of the space for which the use is requested.  It is the building administrator's responsibility to check with any academic unit to ascertain whether they have scheduled prior use of any such space, in addition to that shown on the class schedule.  Forms for building use are sent to building administrators

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A12b">b)	Use By Non-College Affiliated Groups -  All use of facilities by any non-College affiliated group or individual is channeled through the President's designee, Director of Continuing Education. That person bears the responsibility to insure that the requested use meets the required criteria, then contacts the building administrator involved to ascertain whether the space is available for the intended purpose.  A standard form exists for all such requests for use of space by non-College affiliated groups or individuals.  Any prolonged use in excess of thirty days requires prior approval of the Central Office of the State University and State Comptrollers Office.  Use of space for less than 30 days requires approval of the President of the College or his/her designee.  Long term use requires the completion of a revocable permit.  The short term use is handled locally and approved by the President, while the long term use requires formal presentation through Central Administration of State University and the Comptrollers Office and becomes a comprehensive and complex document. Use of all space on campus is based on a priority system.  
<dt><br>
			<dt>The direct needs of the academic program take the highest priority followed closely by student and staff activities.  Other scheduled activities that relate to the total College program receive the next priority.  Other requested uses by College or non-College affiliated individuals or organizations are then considered.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl><!-- 1 -->
</dl><!-- 0 -->
<dt>
<dd><dl><!-- 0 -->
	<dt><A NAME="12A13"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>13</a>.	NAMING OF BUILDINGS AND GROUPS AND ROOMS WITHIN A BUILDING</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The College President, Executive Director of the  Potsdam College Foundation, nominator and/or donor will initiate the confidential process of naming.  The President may inform and involve the Executive Staff and other college administration as appropriate.  The College President will appoint a screening committee as needed to review any naming requests.
<dt><br>
<dt>The screening committee will review the nominee's contributions and qualifications relative to the mission and spirit of the college and the SUNY guidelines.  The committee is authorized to consult with appropriate campus offices and constituencies in this process.  Upon completion of the review, the committee will make a recommendation to the President.
<dt><br>
<dt>The President, after review and consideration, may forward the recommendation to the College Council or may terminate the recommendation.
<dt><br>
<dt>The College Council will forward its recommendation to the Chancellor for the SUNY Trustees, or may terminate the recommendation.
<dt><br>
<dt>Upon approval from the SUNY Board of Trustees, the President may release information and/or initiate ceremonies as deemed appropriate.
<dt><br>
<dt>DESIRED RESULTS
<dt><br>
			<dt>The naming should result in enhancement and increased understanding of the mission of SUNY Potsdam.
<dt><br>
The naming should honor an individual, group, organization or political subdivision that has definable and significant connections with the College's history, academic programs, student life, research, public service or advancement efforts.
<dt><br>
<dt>The naming should enhance a visitor's ability to identify, locate and use an area of the campus.
<dt><br>
<dt>An additional name for a building shall incorporate a functionally-related name whenever possible - i.e., Crumb Library, Crane School of Music.
<dt><br>
		<dt>GENERAL UNDERSTANDINGS
<dt><br>
			<dt>Buildings or grounds may be named for individuals (living or deceased) and/or organizations, with the primary criteria of dedicated support of and commitment to the enhancement of SUNY Potsdam, its mission and its efforts.  Each situation is judged on its own merit, taking into account significant contributions of personal service as well as monetary or in-kind gifts.
<dt><br>
<dt>Naming for gifts (cash or in-kind): consideration should be given to previous contributions, the purpose of the gift and the proportional relationship of the gift to the project for which it is intended.
<dt><br>
<dt>Naming an existing building:  this implies a significant contribution of the donor both in terms of size and relationship to the original or renovated cost and purpose of the building or facility as well as significance for the future.
<dt><br>
	<dt>DEFINITION OF TERMS
<dt><br>
			<dt>Outstanding service (above and beyond the call of duty) to the college includes excellence as an employee or an individual serving in a voluntary capacity; scholarly contributions; college service.
<dt><br>
<dt>Prominence refers to the overall reputation in the local area or elsewhere with a record of substantial contributions to society - for example, in education, environment, public service.
<dt><br>
<dt>Substantial gift includes the nominee's ongoing affiliation with and financial support for the college combined with a reputation for quality and caring on campus and in the community.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl><!-- 0 -->
<dt>
<dd><dl><!-- 0 -->
	<dt><A NAME="12A14"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>14</a>.	CHANGE OF ADDRESS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>If you move to a new address, you are asked to notify the Office of Human Resources immediately.  A new withholding form will be completed in Human Resources which will change the address on your payroll and personnel records.    
</BLOCKQUOTE>
	</dl><!-- 0 -->
<dt>
<dd><dl><!-- 0 -->
	<dt><A NAME="12A15"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>15</a>.	COMPUTING CODE OF ETHICS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Every user of SUNY Potsdam's computing facility has the fundamental right to privacy and is entitled to a fair share of resources.  It is unethical for any user to violate these principles
<dt><br>
<dt>Each usercode and associated password belong to an individual.  All use should be in accordance with SUNY Potsdam policy on computer use set forth in this document.  Owners accept the burden for the responsible use of their usercode.
<dt><br>
<dt>Electronically-stored files are presumed to be private and confidential unless the owner has explicitly made them available to the public.
<dt><br>
<dt>Use of the network or electronic mail facilities for transmitting anonymous, rude, abusive, harassing or malicious messages is unethical.
<dt><br>
<dt>The unauthorized copying of any software that is licensed or protected by copyright is theft and thus unethical.
<dt><br>
<dt>Although SUNY Potsdam's computing systems and network are not invulnerable to deliberate abuse, knowledge of a special password or any weaknesses in the established security systems should not be used to deliberately degrade SUNY Potsdam's computing systems, its network, personal computers, nor deprive other users of the resources of any SUNY Potsdam or individually-owned computer.
<dt><br>
<dt>When necessary for the maintenance of a system network, SUNY Potsdam Information Services Personnel may restrict availability of shared resources.  It may also be necessary to look at a user's file to follow up on reported problems.
<dt><br>
<dt>Use of computer resources is a privilege, not a right, and is granted with restrictions and responsibilities for their use.  Misuse of College computer resources can result in their revocation.      
<dt><br>
<dt>Use of resources associated with college computer accounts for direct financial gain (e.g., commercial consulting) is unethical.    
<dt><br>
<dt>Violation of the Computing Code of Ethics may subject a user to disciplinary action.
<dt><br>
<dt><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="e-mail">ELECTRONIC MAIL</A> (EMAIL)
<dt><br>
<dt>Obtaining an Email Account (usercode)
<dt><br>
			<dt>In order to use electronic mail at SUNY Potsdam it is necessary to have an email "account" or usercode for each user.  This prevents anonymous mail and establishes the electronic address for each email user to which electronic mail can be received from other email users on or off campus.  Each email account is protected, in part, from unauthorized access by requiring the use of a unique password to identify the legitimate user.
          <dt><br>
<dt>Any student, faculty or staff member of SUNY Potsdam identification may request an email account.  While SUNY Potsdam does not prohibit the use of email for personal           reasons, users should be informed that the primary intention
of providing email service is to support the educational mission of the college and the conduct of its daily business.
<dt><BR>

<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt>Postmaster Responsibilities for Email
<dt><br>
		<dt>It may be necessary at times for the local SUNY Potsdam email postmaster to read an electronic mail message which has failed to reach its destination in order to determine, if possible, the intended addressee and redirect the message to the correct address.  However, it is otherwise not the practice of the postmaster to read or to discuss the content of any message.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>Privacy of Email
<dt><br>
		<dt>It is impossible to ensure the confidentiality of any electronic messages stored or communicated through our computing facilities.  As pointed out by other universities, "The privacy of electronic mail is somewhere between that of a letter and a postcard."  While confidentiality cannot be ensured, all email is considered private and confidential. Except as noted under Postmaster Responsibilities for Email above, email is not to be read by computing center staff or any others with sufficient computer system privileges to do so.
         </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>Hierarchy of Communication with Email
<dt><br>
		<dt>Email is a person-to-person form of electronic communication, addressed to a specific individual and does not adhere to any chain of command in its delivery.  Anyone may write to anyone.
<dt><br>
<dt>Ethics of Email
<dt><br>
		<dt>The SUNY Potsdam Computing Code of Ethics applies to email.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<BLOCKQUOTE><I>1<A NAME="12A16">6.  CONFINED </A>SPACE</I><BR>
<BR>
SUNY Potsdam has established guidelines and operational instructions to be taken by campus personnel in order to provide a safe work environment for its employees when entering confined spaces.  "Permit required confined spaces" have been identified on campus and posted in accordance with Federal regulations.  Confined spaces on the campus of SUNY Potsdam are as follows:  manholes (steam, signal, sewage, storm, electrical and condensate stations), boilers, distrubtion tanks (domestic hot water, water treatment, condensate recovery tanks and oil tanks), HVAC handling units, steam tunnels, crawl spaces.</BLOCKQUOTE>


<BLOCKQUOTE><I><A NAME="12A17">17.</A>	CONTRACTUAL AGREEMENTS</I><BR>
<BR>
Authority to enter into contractual agreements on behalf of the College is vested in the President of the College(ordesignee, the Director of Finance and Management). It may be delegated in specific instances.  No individual except as above, shall purport him/herself to represent the College and any agreement entered into without proper authority is notbinding on the College.  The legal status of the individual will be determined by the separate circumstances.</BLOCKQUOTE>


</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
<BR>
<BR>
