<BR>
<BR>
<center><strong>V. HEALTH, DEPENDENT CARE AND MEDICAL RELATED BENEFITS</CENTER></STRONG><BR>
<BR>

<dt><blockquote><A NAME="5A9"><i>9.	CONTINUATION IN RETIREMENT</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>If you meet the minimum employment requirements set forth below at the time of your retirement from State service, you will be eligible to continue your coverage, and that of your enrolled dependents, into retirement.  As an enrolled retiree, your coverage will be continued under the option in which you were enrolled at time of retirement, although you may elect to change options.  However, if you were formerly a member of a bargaining unit and eligible to receive benefits from a union's Employee Benefit Fund or special benefits negotiated for members of your unit, there may be some change in benefits and/or the method of obtaining them after retirement.
<dt><br>
		<dt>The requirements for continuation of coverage in retirement are as follows:                    

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>a)	An employee whose most recent date of employment in State service is prior to April 1, 1975, may continue health insurance coverage in retirement provided that at the time of retirement the employee:

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>i)	has had a least five years of State service, not necessarily continuous, or has had at least five years of combined service with the State and one or more Participating Agencies; and
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>ii)	has retired as a member of a retirement system administered by the State of New York or any of its political subdivisions; or be enrolled in the optional retirement plan offered by TIAA-CREF,

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>(1) is at least 55 years of age, or

				</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>(2) has qualified for Social Security disability payments and has had at least ten years of State service in the case of an ordinary disability retirement and
</dl>
			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>iii)	is enrolled in a New York State Health Insurance Plan at the time of retirement.
</dl>
		</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt>b)	An employee whose most recent date of employment in State service is on or after April 1, 1975, may continue health  insurance coverage in retirement provided the employee:

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>i)	has had at least 10 years of State service, not necessarily continuous, or has had at least ten years of combined service with the State and one or more Participating Agencies; and

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>ii)	has retired as a member of a retirement system administered by the State of New York or one of its political subdivisions; or be enrolled in the optional retirement plan offered by TIAA-CREF
<dt><br>
				<dd>(1) is at least 55 years of age if employment began with     NYS prior to 9/1/83,
				<dd>(2) is at least age 62 if employment began with NYS                              on or after 9/1/83;
				<dd>(3) has qualified for Social Security disability                              payments and

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>iii)	is enrolled in a New York State Health Insurance Plan at the time of retirement.
<dt><br>
				<dt>NOTE:  The five and ten-year minimum service requirements do not apply in the case of a disability retirement resulting from a work-incurred illness or injury.  In such cases, no minimum period of service is required.
<dt><br>
			<dt>An employee who is eligible to continue health insurance coverage into retirement is entitled to use their accumulated unused sick leave, up to a maximum of 165 days to offset all or part of the cost of their health insurance coverage during retirement.  An employee's sick leave is converted into a dollar amount by dividing the total dollar value of sick leave by the employee's actuarial life expectancy in months.  The result is a lifetime monthly credit which is applied to the employee's health insurance premium for as long as he/she remains enrolled in a New York State Health Insurance Plan.  Although the cost of health insurance coverage may change, the amount of monthly credit remains the same throughout the retirees lifetime, thereby resulting in an increase in premium that the retiree will have to pay.
<dt><br>
			<dt>Credit for unused sick leave may be provided only if the employee meets both of the following provisions:
<dt><br>
				<dt><blockquote>the employee's compensation is paid directly by the State; and
<dt><br>
				<dt>the employee is subject to a plan administered by law, rule, regulation, written order or written policy which provides for the regular earning and accumulation of sick leave.</blockquote>
</dl>
		</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="5A9c">c)</A>	Dual Annuitant Sick Leave Credit
<dt><br>
			<dd>Effective 1/1/89 for M/C Employees<br>
			<dd>Effective 9/1/91 for Employees represented by UUP
<dt><br>
			<dt>At the time of retirement, an employee may specify that they would like their dependent survivors to be able to use their monthly sick leave credit towards the cost of their health insurance premium if they should die.  If an employee wishes to choose this option, it must be done before the last day on the payroll.
<dt><br>
<dt>This benefit allows an employee to select 70% of their sick leave credits towards the cost of the health insurance premium for as long as they live.  If the enrollee should die, his/her dependents may continue to use the 70% of the monthly credit for their health insurance premium.  The opportunity to elect Dual Annuitant Sick Leave is available only once, at the time of retirement.  Once this is elected it may not be discontinued.  If an enrollee's dependents should predecease him/her, the enrollee will maintain the 70% sick leave credit.

		</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="5A9d">d)</A>	Deferred Health Insurance Coverage for Retirees
<dt><br>
			<dt>Employees that retire may elect to delay the start of their health insurance coverage in retirement.  During this deferment period, enrollees who have health insurance coverage through their spouse's employer and through post-retirement employment, do not pay anything to the State Health Insurance Program.  Deferring coverage also means that the retiree's sick leave credit, calculated when the retiree is older, will be higher than it would otherwise be at the time of retirement.
<dt><br>
<dt>If the retiree dies while coverage is deferred, the spouse and/or eligible dependents may transfer back to the State Health Insurance Program.  To elect Deferred Health Insurance Coverage, the enrollee must complete the appropriate form (available through the Office of Human Resources) and furnish proof of continued coverage through a spouse's health care plan or through post-retirement employment.
<dt><br>
<dt>*M/C employees may elect to defer the start of their health insurance coverage indefinitely.  <BR>
** Employees represented by UUP may elect to defer the start of their health insurance coverage for up to 5 years.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><blockquote><A NAME="5A10"><i>10</A>.	DEPENDENT ELIGIBILITY</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The following types of dependents are eligible to be enrolled in the program.  

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>a)	Your spouse, including a legally separated spouse.  If you are divorced, or your marriage has been annulled, your former spouse is not eligible for coverage even if the court orders the coverage to be maintained.  

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>b)	Your unmarried children under 19 years of age. This includes your natural children, legally adopted children, including children in a waiting period prior to the finalization of an adoption, and your dependent step-children.  Other children who reside permanently with you in your household who are chiefly dependent on you, are also eligible.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>c)	Your unmarried children 19 years of age or older but under 25 who receive more than half of their support from you and who are full-time students at an accredited secondary or preparatory school, college or other accredited educational institution, and are otherwise not eligible for employer group coverage.  They continue to be eligible through the month in which they complete course requirements for graduation.  Time spent in US military service, not to exceed four years, may be deducted from the dependent's age for the purpose of establishing eligibility for coverage.
<dt><br>
<dt>Unmarried dependent children over age 19, but under age 25, are also eligible when less than full-time course work is needed to satisfy the requirements for graduation as long as i) the child was a full-time student in the term immediately preceding the semester or trisemester in which course requirements will be completed, and ii) be able to provide a statement from the school or college administrator which certifies the student's status. If the above criteria are met, the child will be eligible for dependent student status through the end of the month in which he/she completes course requirements for graduation.  Coverage will not be extended beyond this semester or trimester unless full-time student status is resumed.
<dt><br>
<dt>An enrolled dependent child whose 19th birthday occurs during school vacation period will continue to be covered under the program, provided the child is enrolled in a school and it is anticipated the child will resume full-time student status at the end of the vacation period.
<dt><br>
<dt>In the event a dependent student is disabled and is granted a medical leave by the school he or she is attending, health insurance coverage will be continued for a maximum of one year from the month in which the student withdraws from school plus  any time before the start of the next regular semester.  Written documentation must be provided from the school and physician.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>d)	Your unmarried child 19 years of age or older who is incapable of self-support by reason of mental or physical disability and who became so incapable before reaching age 19.
<dt><br>
<dt>The eligibility of such a dependent should be established as early as possible.  This should be done at the time of your initial enrollment if the child is age 19 or older at that time. If the child has not attained age 19 at the time you first enroll in the program, eligibility for continued coverage should be established at the time of his, or her, 19th birthday.

</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>e)	Your domestic partner.  A domestic partner is defined as one in which the partners must be 18 years of age or older, unmarried and not related by marriage or blood in a way that would bar marriage, reside together, involved in a committed (lifetime) rather than casual relationship and mutually interdependent financially.  The partners must be each other's sole domestic partner and must have been involved in the domestic partnership for a period of not less than six (6) months.
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Office of Human Resources can provide the forms and instructions necessary to establish eligibility.
</dl>
	</dl>


<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>11.	<A NAME="11">DOMESTIC PARTNER BENEFIT</A><BR>
<BR>


			Pursuant to language in the agreements between New York State and the unions, a domestic partnership is one in which both partners are:  18 years of age or older; unmarried and not related by marriage or blood in a way that would bar marriage; residing together; involved in a committed (lifetime) rather than casual relationship, and mutually interdependent financially.  The partners must be each other's sole domestic partner and must have been involved in the domestic partnership for a period of not less than six (6) months.  The partners must be able to document all of these criteria for the enrollment in a health insurance plan to be permitted.

			<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>a)	Enrolling a Domestic Partner<BR>
<BR>

	
					To begin the enrollment process, please contact Human Resources to obtain the domestic partner enrollment package.  This includes the Affidavit of Domestic partnership, Afficavit of Financial Interdependence, Dependent Tax Affidavit, Termination of Domestic Partnership Form and a Health Insurance Transaction Form (PS-404).  Completed documents are to be returned to Human Resources along with two items to proof of financial interdependence and proof of six month residency.  The Affidavit of Financial Interdependence includes a list of acceptable proofs.</dl>

			
		<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>	b)	Effective Date of Coverage<BR>
<BR>


					For applications received after March 1, 1995, the date of coverage will be six months after the latest date on the documents of proof that are submitted with the application.</dl>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>			c)	Dental and Vision Coverage<BR>
<BR>


					If an employee enrolls a domestic partner for health insurance and is eligible for the State administered dental and vision programs, the partner will automatically be eligible for dental and vision coverage.  If the employee receives prescription drug, dental and vision benefits from the CSEA Employee Benefit Fund or the UUP Benefit Trust Fund, the partner will also be eligible for those benefits based on the same eligibility criteria and application process used for health insurance enrollment.  The Funds will take the necessary action to provide applicable fund benefits to the partner.  They will contact the enrollee for any additional information they may need to complete enrollment of the partner for Fund-provided benefits.</dl>

		<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>	d)	Imputed Income<BR>
<BR>


					Covering a Domestic partner will almost always result in additional taxable income.  Internal Revenue Service (IRS) rules require the fair market value of the coverage provided to the domestic partner to be considered imputed income to the employee.  This means that the amount of taxable income reported on the employee's W-2 form will be increased by the fair market value of that coverage.  The fair market value of State-administered benefits equals the "gross" (before application of interest and dividend) individual premium less the employee's contribution for dependent coverage.  An employee who enrolls a domestic partner for health insurance and who has State-administered dental/vision benefits will also have the value of those benefits included as income.  This is required by the IRS because those benefits are automatically available to all eligible dependents.  There is no "opt-out", so the employee is in "constructive receipt" of State-administered dental/vision benefits for the partner as soon as (s)he demonstrates the partner's eligibility for coverage.

					For example, if the employee is an M/C employee, the imputed income for each pay period for 1995 will be approximately $74.40 (gross bi-weekly cost of health, dental and vision coverage, less premium paid by employee).  This means that if an M/C employee covers a domestic partner for 20 pay periods in 1995, (s)he will have to pay taxes on an additional $1,488.00 of income reported on his/her W-2.  This figure includes the value of health (including prescription drug benefits), dental and vision coverage.  Paycheck deductions for income tax and FICA contributions will also be adjusted to reflect this higher income level.</dl>

			<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt></dl>e)	Imputed Income Exception<BR>
<BR>


					If a domestic partner qualifies as a dependent under IRS Code Section 152 (copy enclosed with application package), there is no imputed income for the employee and none will be reported to the IRS if the dependent tax affidavit in the enrollment package is submitted by the employee at the time of application.  Employees will be required to review the IRS dependent status of the partner annually.  Mid-year adjustments will not be made to imputed income, payroll tax withholding and FICA contributions based on gain or loss of IRS dependent status.  If the partner's IRS dependent status changes mid-year, the employee will be responsible for reporting and paying taxes on the value of coverage provided to the partner for the entire year with that year's income tax return.<dl>

			<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt></blockquote></dl>f)	Pre/Post-Tax Deductions<BR>
<BR>


					IRS rules mandate that an employee who enrolls a domestic partner must pay the additional employee contribution for dependent coverage on a post-tax basis although the individual premium can remain pre-tax.  The Office of the State Comptroller will shortly be able to split health insurance deductions into pre- and post-tax components.  Employees who currently have pre-tax individual coverage, will have a post-tax deduction for the additional premium for dependent coverage.  Employees who already have family coverage on a pre-tax basis, will have their deductions split into pre-and post-tax components to meet IRS requirements.</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><blockquote>g)	Terminating Domestic Partner Coverage<BR>
<BR>


					When a domestic partner relationship ends, the employee must fill out and sign the Termination of Domestic Partnership Form within 14 days of the termination.  This form is part of the enrollment package.  The employee will not be eligible to enroll another domestic partner or re-enroll the same partner until six months after the Termination of Domestic Partnership Form is submitted to the Office of Human Resources.</dl>

		<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>	h)	Other Information<BR>
<BR>


					Eligibility for coverage of children of domestic partners will continue to be based on the New York State Health Insurance Program's eligibility criteria for "other children."  Note that these criteria assess the child's dependent status with respect to the enrollee and should be separate from the eligibility of the domestic partner.

					Domestic partners who survive a deceased employee will be eligible for dependent survivor coverage under the same circumstances as surviving spouses.

					Domestic partners who lose coverage eligibility will have 60 days following their loss of coverage in which to elect COBRA continuation.  The 60 day application period begins on the day eligibility is lost, not the day the termination form is filed, so termination notices must be filed promptly.

					Retirees may enroll domestic partners and must contact the New York State Department of Civil Services' Employee Benefits Division Program Service Unit directly to apply<BR>
<BR>
</dl>

<dt><A NAME="5A12"><i>12</A>.	COVERAGE WHILE ON LEAVE OF ABSENCE WITHOUT PAY</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>If an employee is granted a leave of absence without pay, or otherwise leaves the State payroll temporarily, he/she may be eligible to continue health insurance coverage while off the payroll. In order to do so, the employee must pay both the employee and employer shares of the premium.  The NYS Department of Civil Service Division of Employee Benefits will notify the employee as to the cost of the bi-weekly payment and due date of the first payment.  Failure to make payments on time will cause a cancellation of health insurance coverage.  Conversion privileges will not be offered.  In order to reinstate coverage while on leave, there will be a break in coverage and the enrollee will be subject to late enrollment provisions.
<dt><br>
<dt>If an employee is on leave-without-pay for 28 days or less and has not canceled his/her coverage, the employee and employer shares of the health insurance premium for that period will be automatically deducted from his/her paycheck once he/she has returned to work.
<dt><br>
<dt>If an employee does not want to continue health insurance coverage while off the payroll, coverage must be canceled prior to the last day on the payroll.  All employees should contact the Office of Human Resources concerning their insurance coverage while on leave prior to the beginning of a leave of absence without pay in order to complete the necessary paperwork and review the available options.	

</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5A13"><i>13</A>.	LOSS OF ELIGIBILITY - CONTINUATION OF COVERAGE THROUGH COBRA AND CONVERSION PRIVILEGES</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>a)	Continuation Of Coverage - Managerial/Confidential Employees (M/C) and Academic and Professional Employees (UUP)
<dt><br>
<dt>The Consolidated Omnibus Reconciliations Act (COBRA) provides for a temporary extension of health care coverage under the New York State Health Insurance Plan to an employee and covered dependents who are otherwise no longer eligible to continue this benefit.  COBRA provisions are available to Managerial/Confidential employees and employees represented by UUP.

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>i)	Eligibility

<dt><br>
<dd>(a) Employees and dependents who lose coverage because     the employee has been terminated for any reason     (other than gross misconduct), or has a reduction in     hours of employment whereby coverage would     terminate.
<dt><br>
    <dd>If an employee is terminated for gross misconduct,     he/she may be able to continue coverage under the     NYS Continuation of Coverage Law.

<dt><br>
<dd>(b) The spouse and dependent children of an active     employee has the right to continue coverage under     COBRA for any of the following reasons:
<dt><br>
<dd>1. the death of the employee,<br>
				    <dd>2. the divorce or legal separation of the employee<br>
				    <dd>3. the dependent child of the employee no longer meets the eligibility requirements

</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>ii)	Length of Coverage
<dt><br>
<dd>(a) Continuation of coverage for an employee's spouse and/or dependent children may be continued for up to 3 years unless coverage was lost due to termination of employment or a reduction of work hours.  If this is the case, the required continuation coverage period is 18 months. 
<dt><br>
				<dd>(b) Continued coverage through COBRA will cease for any person if:
<dt><br>
				   <dd>(1) New York State no longer provides group             health care coverage to any of its employees, or the union Employee Benefit             Fund no longer provides the type of coverage to State employees;
<dt><br>
				 <dd>(2) the premium for continued coverage is not paid on time;
<dt><br>
				  <dd>(3) the person becomes eligible for Medicare;
<dt><br>
				  <dd>(4) the person becomes covered under another health care plan; or
<dt><br>
				  <dd>(5) the continuation period ends.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>iii)	Available Benefits
<dt><br>
				<dt>All Medical, Hospital, Drug, Dental, Vision, and Hearing Care insurance coverages available as an active employee (or the dependent of an active employee) are available under COBRA.  Employees represented by UUP are also eligible to continue benefits provided by the UUP Benefit Trust Fund through COBRA.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>iv)	Cost of Continued Coverage
<dt><br>
				<dt>Any person who elects to continue coverage under the Plan must pay the gross premium (employee cost plus employer cost) plus a two percent (2%) administrative fee.  Payments for continued coverage must be made in advance on the first day of each month for which coverage will be provided.  Employees represented by UUP must also make payment directly to the UUP Benefit Trust Fund to continue dental, vision and prescription benefits.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>v)	Notices
<dt><br>
				<dt>The Division of Employee Benefits will notify eligible enrollees of their continuation rights.  Eligible enrollees and dependents have sixty (60) days from the date the coverage ends or the date of the notice, whichever is later, to elect coverage and submit one month's payment.  However, the employee or covered spouse or covered dependent child must notify the Division of Employee Benefits in writing in the event of a divorce, legal separation, or when the dependent child no longer qualifies as a covered dependent under the plan.  *The written notification must be made within sixty (60) days of such event to qualify the dependent for continuation of coverage.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>vi)	When COBRA Will Not Be Offered
<dt><br>
				<dt>COBRA coverage will not be offered when an employee/dependent is able to continue coverage in the State Health Insurance Plan.  Examples of this would be when an employee dies and a dependent continues coverage as a dependent survivor or when the employment terminates and the employee continues coverage in vested status.
</dl>
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>b)	Continuation of Coverage - Direct-Pay Conversion Contracts 
<dt><br>
			<dt>Under certain conditions, New York State Health Insurance Plan (NYSHIP) enrollees and their dependents are entitled to direct- pay conversion contracts after NYSHIP coverage ends or after continuation of coverage in NYSHIP under COBRA ends.  The benefit package and the premium costs for direct-pay conversion contracts may differ from those under NYSHIP.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>c)	Conversion Privileges
<dt><br>
			<dt>An employee will be given the opportunity to convert to direct-pay conversion contract(s) with the carrier(s) of their former coverage, if the enrollee and eligible dependents lose eligibility to continue coverage under NYSHIP for any of the following reasons:
<dt><br>
			<dd>1.	Termination of employment,<br>
			<dd>2.	Resignation,<br>
			<dd>3.	Loss of status as an eligible employee or dependent,<br>
			<dd>4.	Death of the employee or retiree (when the dependent is not eligible for a survivor coverage) or <br>
			<dd>5.	COBRA continuation period ends.
<dt><br>
			<dd>* In order to enroll in a Direct-Pay Conversion Plan, application must be made within 45 days from the date coverage terminates.
<dt><br>
<dt>Direct-pay conversion contracts are not available to:
<dt><br>
			<dd>1.	enrollees who voluntarily cancel their coverage;<br>
			<dd>2.	enrollees who fail to remit required payments during periods of temporary removal from the payroll or enrollees who fail to remit the required cost for coverage continuation under COBRA; or<br>
			<dd>3.	vestees who have failed to remit payments
<dt><br>
			<dd>* There is no conversion right under the Metropolitan Life Insurance Plan for Empire Plan enrollees who have existing coverage which would duplicate the conversion coverage or who are eligible for Medicare.
<dt><br>
<dt>Once continued coverage ends for any person, that person may obtain a personal health care (conversion) policy without evidence of insurability, as provided under the terms of the Plan.  Such a conversion right is not available for prescription drug coverage. Contact the Office of Human Resources for Conversion Policy addresses and telephone numbers. 
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5A14"><i>14</A>.	TERMINATION OF COVERAGE</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>When the employee loses eligibility to continue coverage, the health insurance plan terminates twenty-eight (28) days after the last day  of the payroll period from which the employee is separated.
</dl>
</dl>
<BR>
<BR>
