<BR>
<BR>
 <center><strong>V. HEALTH, DEPENDENT CARE AND MEDICAL RELATED BENEFITS</center></strong>
<BR>
<BR>
<dt><A NAME="5B"><b>B</A>.	MEDICARE </b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>The Omnibus Budget Reconciliation Act of 1986 (COBRA) requires the New York State Health Insurance Program to provide primary coverage for active employees under age 65 or their dependents under age 65 who are enrolled in Medicare due to a disability.  Medicare then becomes the secondary insurance carrier.
<dt><br>
<dt>An individual who reaches age 65 and meets Medicare requirements  must apply for Medicare coverage parts A & B, at a local Social Security Office, in order to receive full health insurance benefits.  To avoid the loss of Medicare benefits, the individual should enroll him/herself and dependents during the three month period preceding his or her 65th birthdate.  Detailed information is available at the local Social Security Office.
<dt><br>
<dt>For active employees age 65 and over who are enrolled in Medicare, the Empire Plan remains the primary insurance carrier and Medicare is the secondary carrier until the employee retires.
<dt><br>
<dt>When an employee becomes eligible for Medicare it is strongly advised that enrollment in Medicare Parts A & B be effected.

</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5C"><b>C</A>.	PRESCRIPTION DRUG PROGRAMS</b>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5C1"><i>1</A>.	PROGRAM FOR MANAGERIAL/CONFIDENTIAL EMPLOYEES AND EMPLOYEES REPRESENTED BY COUNCIL 82</b>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Empire Health Insurance Plan has an associated co-pay prescription drug program through the State of New York (Value Rx) for eligible managerial/confidential employees that allows employees, dependents, and domestic partners to purchase prescription drugs from participating pharmacies at minimal cost.
<dt><br>
<dt>An employee obtaining prescription drugs from a participating pharmacy is responsible for the co-pay charge.  If such drugs are obtained from a non-participating pharmacy the employee must pay the full cost of the prescription.  Upon filing a claim form with the receipt of purchase the employee will be reimbursed, in general, an amount based upon standard prescription drug pricing guides minus the co-pay charge.  The difference between the non-participating pharmacy's charge and the amount reimbursed, in most cases, will be greater than the co-pay charge.  It is therefore to the employee's advantage to use a participating pharmacy.  The plan also has a Mandatory Generic Substitution Requirement.
<dt><br>
<dt>Eligibility, effective date of coverage, dependent eligibility, domestic partner eligibility, continuation in retirement, coverage while on leave of absence  without pay, loss of eligibility and termination of coverage is identical to the health insurance plan rules and regulations. 

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5C2"><i>2</A>.	PROGRAM FOR ACADEMIC AND PROFESSIONAL EMPLOYEES (UUP)</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Employees under the Professional Services Negotiating Unit who are eligible for enrollment in the Empire Health Insurance Plan have an associated co-pay prescription drug program through the UUP Benefit Trust Fund that allows employees and dependents to purchase prescription drugs from participating pharmacies with an associated co-payment.  The plan also has a Mandatory Generic Substitution Requirement.
<dt><br>
<dt>An employee obtaining prescription drugs from a participating pharmacy is responsible for the co-pay charge.  If such drugs are obtained from a non-participating pharmacy (or you do not have an ID card), the employee must pay the full cost and be reimbursed an amount no greater than the amount which would be paid to a participating pharmacy upon submission of a completed direct pay claim form.
<dt><br>
<dt>The effective date of coverage, dependent eligibility (except a legally separated spouse is not covered), domestic partner eligiblity, continuation in retirement, coverage while on leave of absence without pay and loss of eligibility is identical to the health insurance plan rules and regulations.
<dt><br>
<dt>Eligibility for benefits will terminate at the end of the           month following the month in which the employee last appears           on the payroll as an active state employee.
</dl>
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5D"><b>D</A>.	HOME CARE ADVOCACY PROGRAM (HCAP)</b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>The Empire Plan's Home Care Advocacy Program (HCAP) started October 1, 1994.  HCAP is administered by Metropolitan.  When you call HCAP at 1-800-638-9918 and use an HCAP provider for medically necessary home care services and/or durable medical equipment/supplies prescribed by your doctor, you have a paid-in-full benefit for:
<dt><br>
	<dd>(a)	durable medical equipment/supplies
<dt><br>
	<dd>(b)	home nursing
<dt><br>
	<dd>(c)	home infusion therapy
<dt><br>
	<dd>(d)	certain home health care services when they take the place of hospitalization or care in a skilled nursing facility; home health aides; physical, occupational and speech therapy; prescription drugs; laboratory services.
<dt><br>
<dt>Call HCAP as soon as your doctor prescribes home care services and/or durable medical equipment/supplies.  Metropolitan will pre-certify medical necessity and then make or help you make the arrangements.  They will work with participating providers in your area.  If there are none, they will arrange for you to receive the pre-certified home care and/or equipment/supplies from a non-participating provider.
<dt><br>
<dt>After you call HCAP and your home care services and/or durable medical equipment/supplies are pre-certified as medically necessary, you may choose a non-participating provider that HCAP has not approved.  You will have out-of-pocket expenses.  The Empire Plan Basic Medical benefits will apply.  You must pay for the first 48 hours of private duty nursing per calendar year and meet your annual deductible.  You must submit a claim to Metropolitan.  You will be reimbursed 80% of the reasonable and customary charge for covered services.  You are responsible for the remaining 20% (until you meet your coinsurance maximum) and any charges above the reasonable and customary charge.

</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E"><b>E</A>.	DENTAL INSURANCE</b>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E1"><i>1</A>.	PLAN FOR MANAGERIAL/CONFIDENTIAL EMPLOYEES (M/C)</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E1a">a</A>)	The Plan
<dt><br>
			<dt>New York State provides M/C employees with a group dental insurance plan, the Preferred Dental Plan, administered by Group Health Incorporated.  The entire cost of the coverage is paid by the State for eligible employees and dependents.  The plan covers a broad range of dental work.  If an employee chooses to use a participating dentist, all covered fees are paid by the plan.  If the employee chooses to use a non-participating dentist, reimbursement is made in accordance with a fee schedule based on a Statewide average.  The employee is responsible for any difference between the dentists' fees and the plan's payment schedule.  Coverage under this plan is automatic and is subject to certain deductibles.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E1b">b</A>)	Eligibility
<dt><br>
			<dt>The eligibility requirements for an employee, dependents, and domestic partners are the same as that for the health insurance program.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E1c">c</A>)	Effective Date of Coverage
<dt><br>
			<dt>Coverage under this Plan is effective on the first day of the month after an employee has completed six full calendar months of continuous employment.  The employee may have satisfied the six month period of employment in a non-eligible position.  In this event, the effective date is the first day of the month following the date of transfer to an eligible position.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E1d">d</A>)	The Deductible
<dt><br>
			<dt>There is an annual deductible, for all services except Preventative Care, Diagnostic Care and Orthodontics.  The deductible is $25.00 per person per calendar year.  The total family deductible will not exceed $75.00 per year for all covered family members.  The amount of the deductible is based on GHI's schedule, not on the amount charged by the dentist.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E1e">e</A>)	Expiration of Coverage and Leave Without Pay Status
<dt><br>
			<dt>Coverage in the Plan ends the last day of the month in which an employee is separated from active service with  his/her employer or is transferred from a unit or group eligible to participate in the Program.  In the event of death, your dependents' coverage terminates on the last day of the month in which your death occurs.  
<dt><br>
<dt>If you are placed in leave without pay status you may continue your coverage.  Payments of the full cost of coverage for this period must be made directly to the Office of Human Resources.
<dt><br>
<dt>If you do not make these payments, your coverage will cease on the last day of the month in which you were placed on leave without pay.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E1f">f</A>)	Cost
<dt><br>
			<dt>If you are employed by the State of New York, the State will pay the full cost of coverage for you and your eligible dependents. 
<dt><br>
<dt>If you are temporarily removed from the payroll, you may continue coverage while off the payroll by paying the full cost yourself.  Details are available from the Office Human Resources.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E1g">g</A>)	If You Leave State Service
<dt><br>
			<dt>If you leave State service, you may be eligible to continue your coverage through COBRA.  You must request continuation of coverage in writing within 60 days of the later of (1) the date coverage would otherwise end or (2) the date notice of your right to continue coverage is sent to you. (Please refer to the book "Preferred Dental Plan for You and Your Dependents" for more information.)
<dt><br>
			<dt>If you choose to continue your coverage through COBRA, NYS is required to offer you coverage which, as of the time coverage is being provided, is identical to the coverage provided under the plan to similarly situated employees or family members.  The law requires that you have the opportunity to maintain continuation of coverage for 3 years, unless you lost your group health coverage because of termination of employment or reduction in hours.  In that case, the required continuation coverage period is 18 months.  The law also provides that your continuation coverage may be cut short for either of the following reasons:
<dt><br>
			<dd>(1)	if NYS no longer provides dental insurance coverage to 	its employees<br>
			<dd>(2)	if the premium for your coverage is not paid on time.
<dt><br>
			<dt>You will have to pay all of the premium for your continuation coverage plus a 2% administrative fee.  You will have an initial grace period of 45 days starting with the date you choose continuation coverage to pay any premium; after the  initial 45 day grace period, you will have a grace period of at least 30 days to pay subsequent premiums.  COBRA also requires that at the end of the 18 month, 29 month or 3 year period, you are eligible to convert to a direct pay dental conversion contract.  If you choose COBRA, you must exhaust those benefits before converting to a direct-pay conversion plan.  If you choose COBRA and fail to make the payments or cancel coverage, you will not be eligible to convert to an individual policy.  Please contact the Office of Human Resources for additional information on COBRA.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E2"><i>2</A>.	PLAN FOR ACADEMIC AND PROFESSIONAL EMPLOYEES (UUP)</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E2a">a</A>)	The Plan
<dt><br>
			<dt>The United University Professions (UUP) provides employees under the Professional Services Negotiating Unit a dental program administered by the UUP Benefit Trust Fund.  The schedule of allowances provides payments according to a schedule of covered dental procedures which relate directly to the dentist's actual charges.  There are no deductibles which means eligible enrollee's receive first dollar coverage for their dental work and the cost of coverage is paid by the Benefit Trust Fund.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E2b">b</A>)	Eligibility
<dt><br>
			<dt>An employee eligible for enrollment in the State Health Insurance Program is eligible for dental benefits.
<dt><br>
<dt>Dependent and domestic partner eligibility is identical to the eligibility requirements for the UUP Prescription Drug Program.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E2c">c</A>)	Effective Date of Coverage
<dt><br>
			<dt>If you are a new employee in the PSNU, and you transferred directly from other State employment, you will become eligible for benefits on the day after the coverage under your previous plan terminates.  In all instances, you will not suffer a break in coverage.
<dt><br>
<dt>If you are a new employee in the PSNU, and you were not employed by the New York State Government immediately prior to your employment in the PSNU, you will become eligible for benefits following the completion of forty-two days of continuous service in covered employment.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E2d">d</A>)	Expiration of Coverage
<dt><br>
			<dt>Eligibility for benefits will terminate at the end of the month following the month in which you were last employed.
<dt><br>
<dt>However, if you are on authorized sick or disability leave without pay, your eligibility for benefits will terminate at the end of the fourth month following the month in which you were last employed.  A copy of your agency's sick or disability leave of absence without pay notice must be filed with the Fund Office before claims can be paid.  This will serve as certification of eligibility.
<dt><br>
<dt>Your enrolled dependents will lose eligibility at the same time that you do.
<dt><br>
<dt>You will again become eligible for benefits as soon as you have completed one full day of work, if you are re-employed within twelve months as an active employee in the PSNU and are eligible for State Health Insurance.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5E2e">e</A>)	Continuity of Benefits
<dt><br>
			<dt>The dental benefits described above cease when you leave the UUP/PEBF group.  However, arrangements can be made to continue coverage on a Direct Payment basis or through COBRA for yourself or a dependent when he or she is no longer eligible.  The benefits provided will differ somewhat from Fund coverage.
<dt><br>
<dt>Upon request to the Fund, you will be furnished with the appropriate conversion applications and full instructions concerning continuation of dental coverage on a Direct Payment basis or through COBRA.
<dt><br>
<dt>Applications for continuation of coverage must be received within 30 days after your removal from the group.
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F"><b>F</A>.	VISION CARE </b>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F1"><i>1</A>.	PLAN FOR MANAGERIAL/CONFIDENTIAL EMPLOYEES (M/C)</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F1a">a</A>)	The Plan
<dt><br>
			<dt>Eligible M/C employees, their dependents, and their domestic partners are eligible for vision care coverage under the M/C Vision Care Plan.  If an employee chooses to use a participating provider for vision care needs, the employee will be issued a voucher, which is valid for 45 days, for the entire cost of an examination and eye glasses  or standard allowance for contact lenses.  If the employee chooses a non-participating provider, payment will be made directly to the employee according to a fixed schedule.  Plan benefits are available to each covered person once in each 24 month period.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F1b">b</A>)	Eligibility
<dt><br>
			<dt>All full-time and half-time salaried M/C employees are eligible for coverage.  Dependent and domestic partner eligibility is identical to that of the State Health Insurance Program.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F1c">c</A>)	Enrollment
<dt><br>
			<dt>An eligible M/C employee must enroll in the M/C VISION CARE PLAN in order to take advantage of the services provided under the plan.  Newly eligible employees will automatically receive an enrollment form and plan information at their residence after they have been on the payroll for 25 days.  

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F1d">d</A>)	Expiration Of Coverage
<dt><br>
			<dt>A vision care voucher may be requested up to and including  twenty-eight (28) days after an employee's last day on the payroll.          
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F2"><i>2</A>.	PLAN FOR ACADEMIC AND PROFESSIONAL EMPLOYEES (UUP)</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F2a">a</A>)	The Plan
<dt><br>
			<dt>Eligible employees, their dependents, and their domestic partners may elect vision care coverage under the UUP Benefit Trust Fund Vision Care Plan.  If an employee chooses to use a participating provider for vision care needs, the employee will be issued a voucher valid for 45 days for the entire cost of an examination and eye glasses or standard allowance for contact lenses.  If the employee chooses a non-participating provider, payment will be made directly to the employee according to a fixed schedule.  Plan benefits are available to each covered persons once in each 24 month period.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F2b">b</A>)	Eligibility
<dt><br>
			<dt>All full-time and most part-time employees are eligible for coverage.  Dependent, and domestic partner eligibility is identical to that of the State Health Insurance Program.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F2c">c</A>)	Enrollment
<dt><br>
			<dt>An eligible employee must enroll with UUP Benefit Trust Fund in order to take advantage of the services provided under the plan.  This is done by completing an enrollment form and submitting it to the Office of Human Resources for forwarding.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5F2d">d</A>)	Expiration Of Coverage
<dt><br>
			<dt>A vision care voucher may be requested up to and including twenty-eight (28) days after an employee's last paycheck.
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5G"><b>G</A>.	HEARING CARE (FOR M/C EMPLOYEES ONLY)</b>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5G1"><i>1</A>.	THE PLAN</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Eligible M/C employees, their dependents, and their domestic partners are eligible for hearing care coverage under the M/C Hearing Care Plan.  The eligible enrollee must obtain medical clearance from an otolaryngologist prior to seeking any covered services.  The medical exam is required, but not covered under this plan. It may, however, be covered under the employee's health insurance plan.
<dt><br>
<dt>If recommended by the otolaryngologist, the employee next obtains an audiological evaluation (hearing test) from an audiologist.  The Plan reimburses up to $60 for this exam. If a hearing aid is recommended the employee proceeds to an audiologist for a hearing aid consultation to determine which aid is most suitable.  The Plan reimburses up to $70 for the consultation.
<dt><br>
<dt>The employee then purchases the aid or aids from an otolaryngologist, audiologist, or hearing aid dealer.  The plan provides up to $350 for one aid or $600 for two aids, if one aid is required for each ear.
<dt><br>
<dt>Plan benefits are available to each covered person once in each 45 month period and all covered expenses must be claimed on a single form.  The benefit enhancement for children under 12 years of age allows benefits to repeat after 24 months with prior written approval.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5G2"><i>2</A>.	ELIGIBILITY</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>All annual salaried M/C employees who work at least half-time are eligible for coverage.  Dependent and domestic partner eligibility is identical to that of the State Health Insurance Program.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5G3"><i>3</A>.	ENROLLMENT</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Eligible employees who are enrolled in the M/C Vision Care Plan are automatically enrolled in the M/C Hearing Care Plan.  Eligible employees who are not enrolled in the M/C Vision Care Plan or Hearing Care may enroll in both plans simultaneously by filling out an M/C Vision Care/Hearing Care Plan enrollment form available from the Human Resources Office.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5G4"><i>4</A>.	COVERAGE</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Coverage under this plan commences after you have been on payroll as an eligible employee for 28 calendar days.  Claim forms may be submitted up to six months following the expiration of coverage as  long as the expenses were incurred prior to the date coverage expired.  Coverage expires (28) days after an employee's last day on the payroll.
</dl>
</dl>
<br><br>


<CENTER><!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=400 HEIGHT=4  SRC="http://www.potsdam.edu/hr/faculty_handbook/line.blue.GIFF"></CENTER><BR>

