<html><head>
<title>Section 5 A 1-8</title>
</head>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF1FFF" BACKGROUND="
">


<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=87  SRC="../FACBOOK.GIF"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>

          <center><strong>V.  HEALTH, DEPENDENT CARE AND MEDICAL RELATED BENEFITS </strong></center>    

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="5A"><b>A</A>.	HEALTH INSURANCE</b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>The College provides the opportunity to join one of two health insurance plans:  THE EMPIRE PLAN or The Mohawk Valley Health Maintenance Organization (MVP-HMO).

	<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5A1"><i>1</A>.	THE EMPIRE PLAN</i>

		<dt><br>
<dd></dl>
The Empire Plan offers hospitalization coverage provided through Blue Cross, and medical/surgical for Major Medical benefits provided through the Metropolitan Life Insurance Company.
<dt><br>
		<dl>	The Empire Plan, although offering few preventive services, is designed to provide a comprehensive program of protection against most medical expenses, with an emphasis on insurance against the often catastrophic costs that result from major illness.  The plan also provides flexibility in the selection of participating providers (physicians) or other providers of services.  In recognition of the broad protection available, and to provide an incentive for the prudent utilization of benefits, the Empire Plan has both an annual deductible as well as a coinsurance feature for most charges covered under the major medical portion of the plan.  However, some hospital charges covered by Blue Cross are subject to a coinsurance payment for out-patient treatment.
</dl>
</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><blockquote><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="5A2">2</A>.	THE MVP HEALTH PLAN (HMO)</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The MVP Health Plan is an innovative plan which combines the comprehensive benefits of an HMO with the ability to continue seeing local doctors in their private offices.  Participating physicians must be used except in exceptional cases.  There are no deductibles, no claim forms and no lifetime maximums.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Employees can pay their share of the health insurance premium on a pre-tax basis.  Contact the Office of Human Resources for details.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>3.	<A NAME="5A3">ELIGIBILITY</A></i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>a)	all employees with full-time appointments anticipated to last at least 12 weeks;
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>b)	part-time managerial/confidential (M/C) employees who are at least half-time or more, who have appointments that are anticipated to last at least twelve (12) weeks and who work on a regular schedule;

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>c)	part-time academic employees who teach two or more courses in any one semester (excluding casual employees);

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>d)	part-time professional employees if they are employed at a salary rate which would yield a total compensation of $9,000 or more per year, (excluding casual employees) are eligible to elect a plan.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5A4"><i>4</A>.	EFFECTIVE DATE OF COVERAGE</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Coverage is effective on the 43rd day of employment if election is made before that date.  The cost of coverage is dependent upon whether individual or family coverage is elected.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5A5"><i>5</A>.	PRE-TAX CONTRIBUTION PROGRAM</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>At the time an employee enrolls in a health insurance plan, he/she must also decide whether they would like to enroll in the Pre-Tax Contribution Program (PTCP).  Under the PTCP an employee may have their share of the health insurance bi-weekly premium deducted from their gross wages before taxes are withheld.  This program may lower taxes.  (Employees on Leave-Without-Pay making direct payments for health insurance are not eligible to participate in this program).  The amount of money saved in taxes will be dependent upon the employees' income, health insurance premium and the number of withholding allowances claimed on their taxes.
<dt><br>
		<dt>If an employee enrolls in the PTCP, the Internal Revenue Service places restrictions on changes that an employee can make to their health insurance.  Under the Internal Revenue Service rules, employees can change their pre-tax health insurance deduction if certain qualifying events exist or during the annual health insurance Option Transfer Period. (See the Office of Human Resources for more information on this plan.)

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="5A6"><i>6</A>.	THE EMPIRE PLAN'S MENTAL HEALTH AND SUBSTANCE ABUSE PROGRAM</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>a)	The Plan
<dt><br>
			<dt>Effective February 1, 1992 (for employees represented by UUP and M/C employees and retirees), benefits for mental health and substance abuse became administered by American Psych Management (APM) and insured by Metropolitan Life.  APM changed it's name to Value Behavioral Health in March, 1994.
<dt><br>
			<dt>The program has two levels of benefits, Network and Non-Network. By calling Value Behavioral Health (VBH) and obtaining care for a mental health and/or substance abuse problem from a provider VBH recommends, the patient's out-of-pocket expense is significantly reduced.  Modest copayments are required for outpatient care and inpatient care is paid in full under the Network benefits.  There are no maximum benefit levels for medically necessary care.
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><blockquote><A NAME="5A7">7</A>.	 MANAGED PHYSICAL MEDICINE PROGRAM<br><BR>


		The Empire Plan's Managed Physical Medicine Program began August 1, 1995.  This program replaces current Metropolitan coverage for chiropractic treatment and physical therapy.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<blockquote>a)	Network Benefits
<dt><br>
	<dt>		There is an $8 copayment per visit when you use a network provider for chiropractic treatment or physical therapy.  The MPN provider will be responsible for certifying the medical necessity of care.  All certified services will be paid in full except for an $8 copayment.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>b)	How to find a Network Provider<BR>
<BR>
	

			The MPN network includes most current Empire Plan participating providers who provide chiropractic treatment or physical therapy.  It also includes many additional providers who meet MPN's high credentialing standards.<BR>
<BR>
Contact a provider directly and ask if the provider is in the MPN network, or call Metropolitan at 1-800-942-4640 and select the Managed Physical Medicine Program from the automated telephone system menu.  What if there are no MPN providers in the area?  Beginning August 1, 1995, you are guaranteed that network benefits will be available to you under the Managed Physical Medicine Program.<BR>
<BR>
Call Metropolitan at 1-800-942-4640.  MPN will make arrangements for you to receive medically necessary chiropractic treatment or physical therapy, and you will pay only your $8 copayment for each visit.<BR>
<BR>
But, you must call first and you must use the provider MPN recommends.  Remember, the Empire Plan covers only medically necessary treatment.<br>
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>c)	Non-Network Benefits (Deductible, Coinsurance, Annual Maximum Apply)<BR>
<BR>
If you receive chiropractic treatment or physical therapy from a non-network provider when MPN has not made arrangements for you, you will pay a much higher share of the cost.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><dl>1)	Deductible Applies<BR>
<BR>
You must meet the Managed Physical Medicine Program annual deductible of $250.  Your spouse/domestic partner must meet the $250 annual deductible, and all your enrolled children, combined, must meet the $250 annual deductible.  This deductible is separate from other Plan deductibles.<BR>
<BR>
</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt>2)	Coinsurance and $1,500 Annual Maximum Apply<BR>
<BR>
After you meet your deductible, submit a claim to Metropolitan.  You will be reimbursed up to 50 percent of the network allowance for medically necessary services, subject to a maximum annual benefit of $1,500 per covered person.<BR>
<BR>
	Your out-of-pocket expenses under the Managed Physical Medicine Program do not count toward your  Basic Medical annual deductible and coinsurance maximum or toward your Mental Health and Substance Abuse deductibles.<BR>
<BR>	
If Metropolitan determines that the non-network care you received was not medically necessary, you will not receive any Empire Plan benefits, and you will be responsible for the full cost of care.</blockquote></dl>

</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl><dt><A NAME="5A8"><i>8</A>.	THE DEPENDENT CARE ADVANTAGE ACCOUNT</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>a)	The Plan
<dt><br>
			<dt>This program is a New York State employee benefit that allows employees to pay for certain child care, elder care or disabled dependent care expenses on a pre-tax basis.  Employees may set aside up to $5,000 of pre-tax salary annually to be reimbursed for these costs.  These expenses must be incurred to allow you and your spouse, if married, to work.  Employees with dependent children under the age of 13, handicapped children of any age, or adult relatives needing care, may be interested in participating in this program.
<dt><br>
<dt>When an employee enrolls in the DCA Account, a regular pattern of the annual amount will be deducted from his/her bi-weekly paychecks throughout the year.  The deductions are made before State, Federal or Social Security taxes are calculated on an employee's gross pay, thereby reducing taxes and increasing spendable income.
<dt><br>
<dt>Due to the tax-advantage, there are several strict guidelines issued by the Internal Revenue Service.  One of them is the "use it or lose it rule".  This means that if an employee deposits pre-tax dollars into a reimbursement account and does not incur expenses equal to all of the money in the account, the employee will lose any remaining money in the account.  IRS guidelines will not permit any remaining dollars to be returned to the employee or carried over for the next year.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>b)	Eligibility
<dt><br>
			<dt>Any employee of the NYS Executive, Legislative, or Judicial Branches and Employees of Participating Employers who receive a regular bi-weekly paycheck as an employee of New York State is eligible to enroll in this program.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt>c)	Enrollment
 <dt><br>    
			<dt>New employees are eligible to enroll in the DCA Account and must enroll within 30 days of their initial employment date.  Active employees and new employees who choose not to initially enroll in the program may do so during the Annual Open Enrollment Period, which occurs during the Fall of each year.
<dt><br>
<dt>For more information on this program, contact the Office of Human Resources.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>

<A HREF="S5A9-14"><B>Continue to next section</B></a>
</blockquote>
</blockquote>
<br>
<br>


