<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=87  SRC="../FACBOOK.GIF"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<center><strong>XIII.  AFFIRMATIVE ACTION</strong></center>
<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="13F">F.</A>	<b>RACIAL AND ETHNIC HARASSMENT</b>

	<blockquote><dt>
<dt><A NAME="13F1">1</A>.	<i>INTRODUCTION</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>An atmosphere of mutual respect among members of the academic community is necessary for SUNY Potsdam to function as a center of academic freedom and intellectual advancement.  Any violation of mutual trust, any form of intimidation or exploitation, damages the institution's educational process by undermining the essential freedoms of inquiry and expression.  Students, teachers, and staff must feel personally secure for real learning to take place.
<dt><br>
		<dt>As a place of work and study, SUNY Potsdam must be free of racial and ethnic harassment and all forms of racial and ethnic intimidation and exploitation.  All students, staff, and faculty must be assured that the Collage will take action to prevent such misconduct and that anyone who engages in such behavior is subject to disciplinary procedures.

	<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13F2">2</A>.	<i>DEFINITION</i>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt>a)	Intimidating verbal, written or symbolic communications or physical conduct of a racial or ethnic nature that is abusive toward another individual based on direct or implied discrimination. 
<dt><br>
		<dt>b)	Verbal, written or symbolic communications that have the purpose or effect of unreasonably interfering with an individual's performance, or of creating an intimidating, hostile or offensive University environment.
</dl>
	<dt>
<dt><A NAME="13F3">3</A>.	<i>POLICY</i>
        <dt><br>
		<dt>SUNY Potsdam is committed to maintaining an academic residential and working environment which is free of inappropriate and disrespectful conduct of a racial or ethnic nature, especially when such conduct adversely affects a student's or an employee's work environment or creates an intimidating, hostile or offensive campus environment.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Racial and ethnic harassment is a prohibited personnel practice when it has the effect or purpose of abusing others based or implied discrimination.  It is also a prohibited personnel practice when it interferes with an individual's academic, social or work performance.  The effect may include, but is not limited to:  immobilizing anguish, withdrawal from a course, a major, a school, a residence, a department or a career.
<dt><br>
		<dt>This policy applies only to employee-employee or employee-student cases of racial or ethnic harassment.  (Student-student racial or ethnic harassment cases must be reported to the Assistant to President for Affirmative Action or the Assistant Vice President for Student Development and heard in the Student Judicial System.)

	<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13F4">4</A>.	<i>GRIEVANCE PROCEDURES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Any student or employee who feels she/he may have been racially or ethnically harassed by another employee is strongly encouraged to report any episode(s) to the Assistant to President for Affirmative Action.
        <dt><br>
		<dt>There are three established procedures for processing a racial or ethnic harassment complaint:<br>
		<dt>--	Informal Grievance Procedures;<br>
		<dt>--	Formal Procedures;<br>
		<dt>--	External Administrative or Judicial Proceedings (bypassing SUNY Potsdam's internal procedures).
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt>a)	Informal Grievance Procedure
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	The primary objective of all informal procedures is to discover and identify whether racial or ethnic harassment has in fact occurred.  To that end, a student or employee who feels she or he has been harassed by an employee is encouraged to consult with the Assistant to President for Affirmative Action.  Careful consideration of the definition of racial or ethnic harassment and a detailed review of the student's or employee's experience will take place.  Discussions at this informal level are treated as confidential.  No formal records are maintained, and the student or employee will be assured as much anonymity as possible.
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	A second goal is to explore with the student or employee the various alternatives available to her or him in response to the situation.  The ultimate goal is to support and assist the student or employee in implementing the approach chosen in order to reach a satisfactory resolution.
                    <dt><br>
			<dt>iii)	Both parties -- the complainant and respondent (alleged harasser) -- have the right to appear with an advisor during any stage of the proceedings.  Advisors may accompany the parties for support and consultation but may not actively participate, i.e. speak in the proceedings. 
<dt><br>
			<dt>iv)	Recommended actions include, but are not tied to: a) a direct conversation between the student or employee and the alleged harasser, b) a letter written by the student or employee to the alleged harasser, and c) a conversation between the Affirmative Action Officer and the alleged harasser on behalf of the student or employee.
</dl><!-- 3 -->
<dt><br>
		<dt>b)	Formal Grievance Procedure
            <dt><br>                  
			<dt>The SUNY Grievance procedure for Reviewing Allegations of Illegal Discrimination, revised by SUNY Potsdam, will be employed in cases of racial or ethnic harassment.  The statement may be prepared by the complainant as a record of the complaint. 
                    <dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	Written Statement
   <dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
				<dt>(a)	A formal complaint of racial or ethnic harassment must include a written statement signed by the complainant specifying the incident(s) of racial or ethnic harassment.  The statement may be prepared by the complainant as a record of the complaint.
<dt><br>
				<dt>(b)	Grievances must be filed with the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action.  The College will prevent retaliation against the complainant for filing a complaint.                            
</dl><!-- 4 -->
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	Time frame for Filing a Formal Grievance          
            <dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
				<dt>(a)	Employees must file a grievance within 45 calendar days following an alleged case of racial or ethnic harassment.
<dt><br>
				<dt>(b)	Students must file a grievance within 45 calendar days following an alleged case of racial or ethnic harassment; or, if accused is an instructor, 45 calendar days after a final grade is received if that date is later.
</dl><!-- 4 -->
<dt><br>
			<dt>iii)	Procedural Options
            <dt><br>
				<dt>Complainant may choose to process his/her formal complaint through one of the following options:
                         <dt><br>
				<dt>Employees:<br>
				<dt>--	Tri-Partite Committee<br>
				<dt>--	Outside Hearing Officer
<dt><br>
				<dt>Students:<br>
				<dt>--	Tri-Partite Committee<br>
				<dt>--	Outside Hearing Officer<br>
				<dt>--	Students Judicial Process if accused is another student
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
				<dt>(a)	Ad Hoc Tri-Partite Committee
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 5 -->
					<dt>(1)	The Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action will request the convening of this board if the complainant chooses.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(2)	The board consists of a standing panel of six members, formally trained on issues of discrimination, appointed by the President.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(3)	Complainant chooses one member from this standing panel, respondent chooses one member and president chooses third member.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(4)	This ad hoc board must be in place within seven calendar days after receipt of request.  The written request shall include a copy of the original grievance statement.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(5)	The Ad Hoc Tri-Partite Committee shall conduct a fact finding review and shall submit an opinion to the President within 21 calendar days from the date of appointment.  The Board shall have the right to all relevant information and to interview witnesses, including the right to bring together complainant and respondent, if desirable.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(6)	Both parties -- the complainant and the respondent -- have the right to appear with an advisor during any stage of the proceedings.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(7)	The College President or designee shall communicate the opinion of the Tri-Partite Committee verbatim and in writing to the grievance and to the campus Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action within 7 calendar days together with a statement indicating acceptance or rejection of the Hearing Officers' recommendation.  The College President will indicate his/her decision either to dismiss the charge for lack of evidence that unlawful discrimination has occurred or, serve the respondent with a Notice of Discipline.  This is followed by disciplinary grievance procedures under the applicable union contract.
</dl><!-- 5 -->
<dt><br>
				<dt>(b)	Outside Hearing Officer
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 5 -->
					<dt>(1)	The Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action will (if the alleged victim chooses) request an outside Hearing Officer from other SUNY campuses or, from the Associated Colleges:  one of the Assistant V.P. for Diversity & Affirmative Action Officers or their trained alternate to hear the case.  The written request shall include a copy of the original grievance statement.  An outside hearing officer must be in place within 7 calendar days after receipt of request.  The Vice Chancellor for Affirmative Action at SUNY shall receive a copy of the request.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(2)	The Hearing Officer shall conduct a review and shall submit an opinion to the president within 21 calendar days from the date of appointment.  The Hearing Officer shall have the right to all relevant information and to interview witnesses, including the right to bring together complainant and respondent, if desirable.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(3)	Both parties -- the complainant and the respondent -- have the right to appear with an advisor during any stage of the proceedings.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(4)	The College President or designee shall communicate the opinion of the Hearing Officer verbatim and in writing to the Grievance and to the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action within 7 calendar days together with  a statement indicating acceptance or rejection of the Hearing Officer's recommendation.  The College President will indicate his/her decision either to dismiss the charge for lack of evidence that unlawful discrimination has occurred or, serve the respondent with a Notice of Discipline.  This will be followed by the Union disciplinary grievance procedures.
</dl><!-- 5 -->
<dt><br>
				<dt>(c)	Student Judicial Process:  (see student conduct code).                                           
</dl><!-- 4 -->
			<dt><br>
	<dt>4)	Off-campus Resolution of Grievances:  (External Administrative or Judicial Proceedings).
<dt><br>
				<dt>If the Grievance is dissatisfied with the President's response, the Grievance may file a formal complaint with:  a) New York State Division of Human Rights, b) the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, c) the Office for Civil Rights of the U.S. or N.Y. State Department of Education and Office of Federal Contract Compliance of the Department of Labor.
<dt><br>
			<dt>5)	Procedure for Processing Grievances:
<dt.<br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
				<dt>a)	The Assistant to President for Affirmative Action shall receive any complaint of alleged harassment, shall assist the complainant with information about the various internal and external mechanisms through which the complaint may be filed, including applicable time limits for filing with each agency.
<dt><br>
				<dt>b)	If the complainant chooses to use the Potsdam Grievance Procedure for the Review of Allegations of Illegal Discrimination, the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action shall assist the complainant in filling out the appropriate form, signing and dating a copy of the completed form for the complainant.
<dt><br>
				<dt>c)	Once a form has been filled, the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action will notify respondent as soon as possible that a complaint has been filed against him/her.
<dt><br>
				<dt>d)	The Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action shall seek to resolve the complaint informally and shall have the right to all relevant information and to interview witnesses, including the right to bring together complainant and respondent, if desirable.  If a resolution satisfactory to both complainant and respondent is reached within 14 calendar days through the efforts of the Assistant to President for Affirmative Action, the officer shall close the case, sending a written notice to that effect to the complainant and respondent.  The written notice, a copy of which shall be attached to the original complaint form in the officer's file, shall indicate the agreement reached by complaint form in the officer's file, shall indicate the agreement reached by complainant and respondent and shall be signed and dated by the complainant, the respondent and the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action.
<dt><br>
				<dt>e)	If the Assistant to President for Affirmative Action is unable to resolve the complaint to the mutual satisfaction of the Grievance and respondent within 14 calendar days, the officer shall notify the Grievance, advising Grievance of his or her right to proceed to the next step internally or to file with appropriate enforcement agencies immediately.
<dt><br>
				<dt>f)	If a formal complaint with a state or federal agency or a court action is filed by a Grievance, any internal investigation or review underway on the same complaint will terminate without conclusion, except that if internal investigation is prolonged to the point that the statute (180 days for EEOC and OCR complaints; 365 days for Division of Human Rights complaints), a charge may be filed with the appropriate agency without interruption of the internal procedure.
<dt><br>
				<dt>g)	If the Grievance chooses to proceed through the formal internal grievance procedure, the Grievance shall notify the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action and respondent in writing within 10 calendar days from the time of notification by the Assistant to President for Affirmative Action that the issue cannot by resolved informally.
</dl><!-- 4 -->
</dl><!-- 3 -->
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt>
<dt><A NAME="13F5">5</A>.	<i>RECOMMENDED CORRECTIVE ACTION </i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The purpose of any action to resolve a complaint will be to correct or to remedy the injury, if any, to the complainant and to prevent further harassment.  Recommended action may include written or verbal reprimand of the harasser; suspension, dismissal, or transfer of the harasser; a change of grade or other academic record for a student who has been the victim of harassment; a change in personnel action (such as a promotion) for an employee who has been victimized; or other appropriate action with the understanding that the imposition of sanctions against an employee can occur only after completion of contractual disciplinary procedures.

	<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13F6">6</A>.	<i>FALSE CHARGE</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>If it has been determined that a complaint was made by a student with knowledge that the facts were false, the President or designee shall so notify the Vice President for Enrollment and Student Services.  In the case of a false complaint made knowingly by an employee, this finding shall be stated in the recommendation to the President for possible disciplinary action.       
</dl><!-- 1 -->
</dl><!-- 0 -->
<br><br></blockquote>
