<A NAME="VI.  RETIREMENT, DISABILITY AND DEATH BENEFITS"><CENTER><B>VI.  RETIREMENT, DISABILITY AND DEATH BENEFITS</B></CENTER></A>
<br><br>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C6"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>6</A>.   RETIREMENT PLAN FOR TIER III MEMBERS AND TIER IV MEMBERS - GENERAL STATEMENT</i>
<dt><br>
          <Dt>Tier III members are entitled to receive either the benefits under the Coordinated Escalator Plan (CO-ESC) or the benefits under the Coordinated Retirement Plan.  Members may not mix the provisions of  the two laws to change the eligibility requirements for a benefit under either plan.  Once a Tier III member selects and begins to receive a retirement benefit, whether it be under CO-ESC or the Coordinated Retirement Plan, (s)he cannot change plans.  For example, if a Tier III member retires at age 55 under the provisions of the CO-ESC Plan with its 30% reduction and its offset of Social Security beginning at age 62, the member is "locked in" to that benefit--(s)he cannot change to Coordinated Retirement Plan benefits at a later date.  (See below for further discussion of these benefits.
<dt><br>
          <dt>Tier IV members are only entitled to the benefits of the Coordinated Retirement Plan.</BLOCKQUOTE>

     </dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>7</A>.   RETIREMENT PLAN FOR TIER III MEMBERS (7/27/76 - 8/31/83) - THE COORDINATED ESCALATOR PLAN (CO-ESC)</BLOCKQUOTE></i>

<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7a"><BLOCKQUOTE>a</A>)  Final Average Salary
<dt><br>
              <dt>Your final average salary is the average of the wages you earned during the 36 consecutive months which will provide the highest average wage.  If the wages earned during any year included in the 3-year period exceed the average wages of the previous 2 years by more than 10%, the amount over 10% will be excluded from the calculation.  If the 3-year period used immediately precedes retirement, any month or months (up to 12), during which you are on authorized leave of absence at partial or no pay, shall be excluded and an equal number of months immediately preceding the period shall be substituted.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7b">b</A>)  Service Credit
<dt><br>
              <dt>Service credit is based on time worked including paid vacation and sick leave.  Your annual statement shows the credit you have earned in a year.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7c">c)  Service Retirement Eligibility
<dt><br>
              <dt>You are eligible for a normal service retirement benefit when you are 62 years of age or older, and have 10 or more years of creditable service after July 1, 1973.  If you are age 70 or older when you cease public service, the minimum service requirement is reduced to 5 years.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7d">d</A>)  Early Service Retirement Benefits
<dt><br>
              <dt>As a Tier III member, your normal retirement allowance is based on age 62.  Should you choose to retire between the ages of 55 and 62, your retirement benefit will be calculated as follows:
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you retire with 20 or more years of service credit, your normal service retirement benefit will equal 1/50th (2%) of your final average salary multiplied by your years of credited service (not to exceed 30 years). 
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you retire with fewer than 20 years of service, your normal service retirement benefit will equal 1/60th (1.66%) of your final average salary multiplied by your total years of service credit.
<dt><br>
              <dt>Your retirement benefit will be calculated without the CO-ESC Social Security deduction.  It will, however, be reduced by 1/15th (6.66%) for each of the first two years by which your retirement precedes age 62 and 1/30th (3.33%) for each year by which your retirement precedes age 60.  At age 62, your benefit will be further reduced by 50% of the CO-ESC Social Security retirement benefit.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7e">e)  Options
<Dt><br>
              <dt>In addition to a maximum retirement benefit, with no provision for a beneficiary, there are several options available which provide protection for a beneficiary.  The decision of an option must be made no later than the day before the effective date of retirement.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7f">f</A>)  Vesting
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you have 10 or more years of credited service and leave public employment, you have the right to a vested benefit.  This will entitle you to a retirement benefit when you attain age 62,  regardless of the fact that you have left public employment.
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you wish, you may elect to receive a reduced benefit at any time between age 55 and age 62.
<dt><br>
              <Dt>The vested retirement allowance is calculated in the same way as the service retirement benefit.  There is a guarantee, however, that the benefit cannot be less than the actuarial equivalent of your contributions with interest.
<Dt><br>
              <dt>Remember, vested benefits are not paid automatically.  It is up to you to notify the system when you become eligible for and ready to receive your benefit.
<Dt><br>
              <dt>In order to receive vested benefits at the earliest possible time, you should submit an application between 30 and 90 days before you reach age 62.  Similarly, to apply for the reduced vested benefit, an application can be filed as early as 30 to 90 days before you become age 55.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7g">g</A>)  Disability Benefits</BLOCKQUOTE>

<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7gi"><BLOCKQUOTE>i</A>)   Ordinary Disability Benefits
<dt><br>
                   <dt>If you are credited with a least five years of service and are not eligible for a normal retirement benefit but are eligible for a primary Social Security disability benefit, you may be eligible for an ordinary disability benefit from the Retirement System.
<Dt><br>
                   <Dt>Disability retirement benefits qualify for the annual increases/decreases as of the month in which your disability retirement becomes effective.  The adjustment is in the amount of 3% or the change in the cost of living index, whichever is lesser.
<Dt><br>
                   <Dt>Your ordinary disability retirement benefit is equal to the greater of:
<dt><br>
                  <dd>- 33 1/3% of your final average salary; or
<dt><br>
                   <dd>- 2% of your final average salary for each year of  service credit up to 30 years.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>In either case, this benefit is reduced by 50% of the Social Security disability benefit.  If a Workers' Compensation benefit is payable, the Ordinary Disability benefit is reduced by the amount of such benefits for as long as they are paid.

             </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7gii">ii</A>)   Accidental Disability Benefits
<dt><br>
                   <dt>If you become disabled as the natural and proximate result of an accident on the job, not caused by your own willful negligence, and you are not eligible for a normal service retirement benefit but are eligible for primary Social Security disability benefits, you may be eligible for an accidental disability benefit from the Retirement System.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>If approved, your accidental disability retirement benefit will be equal to 2% of your final average salary for each year of service credit you would have earned if you had been able to work until you reached 65 (not to exceed 30 years).  This benefit is then reduced by 50% of the Social Security disability benefit.  If a Workers' Compensation benefit is payable, the disability benefit is reduced by the amount of such benefits as long as they are paid.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl>
          </dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>

<dt><A NAME="6C7h"<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>h</A>)   Contributions
<dt><br>
              <dt>CO-ESC members must contribute 3% of their annual salary toward their retirement benefits during the period for which they accrue service credit.  Employers also contribute to the Retirement System on behalf of members.  These two sources together with investment income provide the money to pay retirement benefits.  

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7i">i</A>)  Refunds
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you leave public employment and are neither vested nor  eligible for a benefit, you may withdraw all your accumulated contributions plus interest.  If you later return to public employment, after having withdrawn your contributions, you will not receive credit for  your earlier service unless you apply for that credit, repay the withdrawn contributions and interest and complete five years of creditable service.


          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C7j">j</A>)  Loans
<dt><br>
              <Dt>A Tier III member is permitted to borrow any portion of his/her  contributions.

          </dl>
</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl>
     </dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C8"><i<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE><I>8</A>.   RETIREMENT PLAN FOR TIER III (7/27/76 - 8/31/83) AND TIER IV (ON OR AFTER 9/1/83) MEMBERS - THE COORDINATED RETIREMENT PLAN</I></BLOCKQUOTE></i>

<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C8a"><BLOCKQUOTE>a</A>)  Service Retirement Eligibility
<dt><br>
              <dt>Coordinated Retirement Plan members may retire:
<dt><br>
              <dd>at age 62, if credited with 10 years of service, or
<dt><br>
              <dd>at age 70, if credited with 5 years of service.
<Dt><br>
          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C8b">b</A>)  Service Retirement Benefits</BLOCKQUOTE>
<dt>
              <dt><BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>i)   If you retire with 25 or more years of service credit, your    
                   service retirement benefit will equal 1/50th (2%) of your 
                   final average salary multiplied by your years of credited 
                   service (not to exceed 30 years), plus 3/200ths (1.5%) of 
                   your final average salary for each year of credited service 
                   beyond 30 years.
<dt><br>
             <dt>ii)   If you retire at normal retirement age but with fewer than 
                   25 years of credited service your retirement allowance will 
                   be 1/60th (1.66%) of your final average salary times your
                   years of credited service.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE> 

          </dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C8c"><BLOCKQUOTE>c</A>)  Final Average Salary (FAS)
<Dt><br>
              <dt>This is the salary for the three years (any 36 consecutive months) when your salary was the highest divided by three.
<dt><br>
              <dt>If the salary in any of the three years is more than 10% higher  than the average wage for the previous two years, the amount over 10% is not included in your final average salary.  If the three-year period used comes right before retirement, any month or months (up to twelve) during which you are on authorized leave of absence at partial pay, or without pay, will be dropped and an equal number of months immediately before that period will be substituted.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C8d">d</A>)  Options
<dt><br>
              <dt>In addition to a maximum retirement benefit, with no provisions for a beneficiary, there are several options available which provide protection for a beneficiary.  The decision on an option must be made no later than the day before the effective date of retirement.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C8e">e)  Vesting
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you have 10 or more years of credited service and leave public employment, you have the right to a vested benefit.  This will entitle you to a retirement allowance when you attain age 62, regardless of the fact that you have left public employment.
<Dt><br>
              <dt>The vested retirement allowance is calculated in the same way as the service retirement benefit.  There is a guarantee, however, that the benefit cannot be less than the actuarial equivalent of  your contributions with interest.
<dt><br>
              <dt>Remember, you must notify us when you become eligible for and ready to receive your benefit.
<dt><br>
              <dt>In order to receive vested benefits at the earliest possible time, you should submit an application between 30 and 90 days before the first of the month following your reaching age 62.  Otherwise your retirement becomes effective on the date your  application is received by the System.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C8f">f</A>)  Disability Benefits
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you are unable to perform your duties because of physical or mental incapacity, you may be eligible for one of the following  disability benefits whichever is greater.
<dt><br>
              <dd>- 1/60th of your final average salary for each year of  credited service or
<dt><br>
              <dd>- 1/60th of your final average salary for each year of service you would have earned if you had worked until you were 60.   The benefit in this case is limited to 1/3 of Final Average Salary.
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you think you are eligible, you or the Office of Human Resources may file an application for a disability benefit.  The application must be filed within three months of the last date you were paid on the payroll.  In the case of a medical leave of absence without pay, the application may be submitted within 12 months of your last paid service, provided you were disabled when the leave began and are on the leave when the application is filed.
<dt><br>
              <dt>Ten years of credited service are required in order to qualify for a disability benefit.  If your disability results from an on-the-job accident, not due to your own negligence, there is no minimum service requirement.  In order to qualify for your disability benefit, written notice of your accident must be filed with the Retirement System within 90 days of the accident, detailing the time and place of the incident, the particulars thereof, the nature and extent of your injuries, and your alleged incapacity.  The notice must be signed by your or someone acting on your behalf.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C8g">g)  Contributions
<Dt><br>
              <dt>Coordinated Retirement Plan members must contribute 3% of their annual salary toward their retirement benefits.  Employers also contribute to the Retirement System on behalf of members.  These two sources together with investment income provide the money to pay retirement benefits.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C8h">h</A>)  Refunds
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you terminate your public employment before vesting and before retirement, your contributions must remain on deposit with the System until you reach age 62 at which time you may  collect your contributions with 5% interest.  In the event of death before age 62, however, your contributions (plus interest at the rate of 5% per year, compounded annually) will be paid to your beneficiary unless a greater death benefit is payable.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C8i">i</A>)  Loans
<dt><br>
              <dt>A Tier IV member may borrow any portion of his/her contribution.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl>
  </dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C9"><i><BLOCKQUOTE>9</A>.   GENERAL INFORMATION - ERS</i>
<dt><br>
          <dt>The ERS program is designed to help you and your dependents maintain financial stability at the time of retirement or in the event of disability or death.  It is important that you keep yourself fully informed about your Retirement System, your plan, and the benefits that they offer.
<dt><br>
          <dt>Each year, you will receive a statement, outlining your status within the Retirement System, and an Investment Report, outlining the status of the Systems' investments.
<Dt><br>
          <Dt>You will also receive a semi-annual newsletter, containing current information about your plan and its benefits, as well as general information about retirement and the Law.
<dt><br>
          <dt>If you have a specific question, you can telephone the Albany office at (518) 474-7736 or write to:
<dt><br>

                   <dd>N.Y.S. Employees' Retirement System<br>
                   <dd>Gov. Smith State Office Building<br>
                   <dd>Albany, NY 12244<br>
</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl>
</dl>
<br><br>
