<BR>
<BR>
<A NAME="VI.  RETIREMENT, DISABILITY AND DEATH BENEFITS"><CENTER><B>VI.  RETIREMENT, DISABILITY AND DEATH BENEFITS</B></CENTER></A>
<br><br>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C"><b>C</A>.	NEW YORK STATE EMPLOYEES' RETIREMENT SYSTEM (ERS)</b>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C1"><i>1</A>.	THE SYSTEM</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>A State retirement system which permits retirement at age 55 or thereafter.  Members who join after July 26, 1976 must complete ten years of creditable service after that date.  Credit is given only for time actually worked, i.e., faculty with an academic year obligation, even if paid on a 12-month basis, receive ten months of credited service.  Benefits are based on final average salary and years of full-time service.  A death benefit is provided as well as ordinary and accidental disability within minimum lengths of service.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C2"><i>2</A>.   MEMBERSHIP</i>
<dt><br>
          <dt>Membership includes employees of the State of New York and employees of those political subdivisions and public agencies of the State that have elected to become participating employers.
<Dt><br>
          <Dt>All permanent full-time employees (except those who are  members of the Teachers' Insurance Annuity Association-College Retirement Equities Fund, State Policemen's and Firemen's  Retirement system, or State Teachers' Retirement System) must  join the New York State Employees' Retirement System.  Temporary, part-time, and seasonal employees may elect to  join the system, but any employee who wishes to be covered  by Social Security must join. 
<dt><br>
          <dt>The system is divided into four tiers.  Membership in each tier is generally determined by the date on which an employee was first           appointed to a permanent position in State service or last applied for membership.  Benefits are based on final average salary and years of service.

     </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3"><i>3</A>.   DEFINITIONS</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3a">a</A>)  Tier I members - members who last joined the System prior to July 1, 1973.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3b">b</A>)  Tier II Members - members who last joined the System during the period July 1, 1973 through July 26, 1976.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3c">c</A>)  Tier III Members - members who last joined the system during the period July 27, 1976 through August 31, 1983.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3d">d</A>)  Tier IV Members - members who last joined ERS on or after September 1, 1983.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3e">e</A>)  Member Service
<dt><br>
              <dt>Credited service as an employee of the State of New York or with any of the political sub-divisions or public agencies of the State of New York after they elected to participate in this Retirement System.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3f">f</A>)  Prior Service
<dt><br>
              <dt>Service with the State prior to 1921 or with a participating employer before that employer provided for membership in the System.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3g">g</A>)  Total Service
<Dt><br>
              <dt>All member service for which a member is credited, all credited prior service and all credited military service.  

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3h">h</A>)  Final Average Salary
<dt><br>
              <dt>The average annual salary earned during any three consecutive years of member service when earnings were highest; usually the last three years.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3i">i</A>)  Pension
<dt><br>
              <dt>The annual allowance for life, payable monthly, derived wholly from employer contributions.  The pension amount is related directly to final average salary and total service, in accordance with the terms of the plan the member is covered by when he/she retires.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3j">j</A>)  Annuity
<dt><br>
              <dt>The annual allowance for life, payable monthly, derived from the member's accumulated contributions, including interest earnings.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C3k">k</A>)  Retirement Allowance
<dt><br>
              <dt>The pension plus the annuity, if any, and the pension-for-increased-take-home-pay, if any.  This is an annual sum, payable in monthly installments to the retiree for his/her lifetime.  The sum may, of course, be modified to provide for payment to a beneficiary.
 </dl>
     </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C4"><i>4</A>.   RETIREMENT PLAN FOR TIER I MEMBERS (PRE 7/1/73) - NEW CAREER PLAN</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C4a">a</A>)  Service Retirement Eligibility
<dt><br>
              <dt>As a Tier I member of the New Career plan, you are eligible for retirement at age 55.  If you have recently changed employers, you may be required to complete 5 years of service with your new employer before you can retire under this plan.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C4b">b)  Service Retirement Benefits
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you retire with 20 or more years of total service, your guaranteed service retirement benefit is 1/50th (2%) of your final average salary for each year of service.
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you retire with less than 20 years of total service, your guaranteed service retirement benefit is 1/60th (1.66%) of your final average salary for each year of service.
<dt><br>
              <dt>If your service began prior to April 1, 1960, your benefit will include an annuity purchased by the contributions you were required to make before that date, plus their interest earnings.
<dt><br>
              <dt>The portion of your service retirement benefit attributable to employer contributions may not exceed 75% of your final average salary.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C4c">c</A>)  Options
<dt><br>
              <dt>Your retirement plan provides many options for the payment of your retirement benefits.  You may wish to receive the maximum retirement allowance with no beneficiary payment.  There are also other options which provide reduced monthly payments in return for protection for a beneficiary.   For more information, read the Retirement System booklet entitled "YOUR OPTIONS AT RETIREMENT"  available from the Office of Human Resources.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C4d">d</A>)  Vesting
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you have 10 or more years of service credit upon leaving public employment (including 5 years as a Retirement System member), you have the right to a vested benefit.  This will entitle you to a retirement allowance when you retire, related to your previous years of government employment.
<dt><br>
              <dt>You can begin to receive a full vested benefit when you reach age 55. The amount of your vested benefit is frozen when you leave public employment and will not be increased by a delay in filing to receive it.
<dt><br>
              <dt>It is up to you to notify ERS when you become eligible for and ready to receive your benefit.  In order to receive your vested benefits at the earliest possible time, a retirement application must be completed and submitted before the first of the month following your 55th birthday.  Otherwise, your retirement will become effective on the date your application is received by the Retirement System.
<dt><br>
              <dt>Vested benefits are payable throughout your retirement and you can select an optional method of payment to provide for possible income to your beneficiary.
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you were a member of the Retirement System before April 1,1960 and you withdraw your required contributions made before April 1, 1960, your vested rights may be terminated.  However, the withdrawal of contributions made for service rendered after April 1, 1960 will not affect your vested status.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C4e">e</A>)  Disability Benefits
<dt><br>
              <dt>You, the College, or anyone authorized by you, may file your application for disability benefits.  Application forms are available from the Retirement System or the Office of Human Resources.
<dt><br>
              <Dt>If you think you are eligible, you may submit applications for both ordinary and accidental disability retirement benefits.  However, both must be submitted before your effective retirement date.
<dt><br>
              <dt>You are also eligible to select an option for the payment of your disability benefits.  More information is found in the  Retirement System booklet entitled "YOUR OPTIONS AT RETIREMENT."

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C4i">i)   Ordinary Disability Benefits
<dt><br>
                   <dt>If you become physically or mentally disabled on a permanent basis, you may be eligible for an ordinary disability retirement benefit.  In order to qualify, you must have at least 10 years of service credit.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>If you entered government service before age 40, your ordinary disability retirement benefit is 1/60th (1.66%) of your final average salary for each year of service credit.  Various factors (withdrawn contributions, periods out of service, and loans, among others) may reduce your benefits but, generally, the minimum allowance is one-third of your final average salary.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>If you entered government service after attaining age 40, your benefit is equal to 1/60th (1.66%) of your final average salary multiplied by the number of years of possible service before you reach age 60.  Remember that your retirement allowance may be reduced, due to withdrawn contributions, loans, and other factors.  However, the minimum allowance is generally one-third of your final average salary.
<dt><br>
                   <Dt>An application for this benefit may be submitted either while you are actually in the service upon which your membership is based or while on a medical leave of absence.  Should you be separated from service, you must file your application with the Retirement System within 90 days after termination of service.

             </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C4eii">ii</A>)   Accidental Disability Benefits
<dt><br>
                   <dt>Regardless of your time in service, if you become physically or mentally unable to perform your job as the direct result of an on-the-job accident which was not due to your willful negligence, you may be eligible for an accidental disability retirement benefit.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>In order to qualify, written notice of your accident must be filed with the Retirement System within 90 days of the accident, detailing the time and place of the incident, the    particulars thereof, the nature and extent of your injuries, and your alleged incapacity.  The notice must be signed by you or someone acting on your behalf.  Your application for benefits must be filed before you reach age 60.  Should you be separated from service, either voluntarily or involuntarily, your application may be submitted within 2 years of your date of separation.
<dt><br>
                   <Dt>If approved, your accidental disability retirement benefit will be a pension equal to three-quarters (75%) of your final average salary, reduced by the total amount of Workers' Compensation benefits that you are or may become entitled to receive.  Members who are eligible for Workers' Compensation must apply for these benefits.  In addition to your pension, you will receive an annuity provided by any contributions you may have made during your working years.
</dl>
<dt><br>

<dt><A NAME="6C4g">f</A>)  Contributions
<dt><br>
              <dt>As a Tier I member of the New Career Plan, you are not required to contribute towards your retirement benefits.  However, you may elect to make voluntary contributions to the Retirement System.  These contributions, plus interest, will provide additional annuity income for you when you retire.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C4h">g</A>)  Loans
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you have contributed towards your retirement benefits, have at least one year of credited service, and are still on payroll, you may apply for a loan against your contributions.  Eligible members may obtain an application form from the Retirement System or Office of Human Resources.
</dl>
     </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C5"><i>5.   RETIREMENT PLAN FOR TIER II MEMBERS (7/1/73 - (7/26/76) - NEW CAREER PLAN</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C5a">a</A>)  Service Retirement Eligibility
<dt><br>
              <Dt>As a Tier II New Career Plan member, you will be eligible to retire with full benefits at age 62.  Retirement with reduced benefits is possible between ages 55 and 62.  In either case, you must have earned at least 5 years of service credit after July 1, 1973.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C5b">b</A>)  Service Retirement Benefits
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you retire with 20 or more years of service credit, your  retirement allowance will be 1/50th (2%) of your final average salary for each year of service credit plus an annuity purchased by your required contributions for any service prior to April 1, 1960.
<dt><br>
              <Dt>If you retire with less than 20 years of service credit, your benefit will be 1/60th (1.66%) of your final average salary for each year of service credit plus an annuity purchased by your required contributions for any service prior to April 1, 1960.
<dt><br>
              <Dt>Should you choose early retirement between the ages of 60 and 62, your benefit will be reduced by one-half of 1% for each of the 24 months by which your retirement precedes age 62.  Should you choose early retirement between the ages of 55 and 60, your benefit will be further reduced by one-quarter of 1% per month for each month by which your retirement preceding age 60.
<dt><br>
              <dt>Your retirement benefits (excluding any annuity purchased by contributions you may have made) may not exceed:
<dt><br>
               <dd>*   60% of the first $15,300 of your final average salary,
<dt><br>
               <dd>*   50% of your final average salary over $15,300, and
<dt><br>
               <dd>*   40% of any final average salary over $27,300.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C5c">c</A>)  Options
<dt><br>
              <dt>Your retirement plan provides many options for the payment of your retirement benefits.  You may wish to receive the maximum retirement allowance with no beneficiary payment.  There are also other options which provide reduced monthly payments in return for protection for a beneficiary.  For more information, read the Retirement System booklet entitled "YOUR OPTIONS AT RETIREMENT", available from the Office of Human Resources.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C5d">d</A>)  Vesting
<Dt><br>
              <dt>If you have 10 or more years of service credit upon leaving public employment (including 5 years as a Retirement System member), you have the right to a vested benefit.  This entitles you to a retirement allowance when you retire, related to your  previous years of government employment.  
<dt><br>
              <dt>You can begin to receive a full vested benefit when you reach age 62.  You may choose to receive a reduced benefit at any time between ages 55 and 62.
 <dt><br>
              <dt>The amount of your vested benefit is frozen when you leave public employment and will not be increased by a delay in filing to receive it.
<dt><br>
              <dt>It is up to you to notify ERS when you become eligible for and ready to receive your benefit.  In order to receive your vested benefits at the earliest possible time, a retirement application must be completed and submitted before the first of the month following your 55th birthday.  Otherwise, your retirement will become effective on the date your application is received by the Retirement System.
<dt><br>
              <dt>Vested benefits are payable throughout your retirement and you can select an optional method of payment to provide for possible income to your beneficiary.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C5e">e</A>)  Disability Benefits
<dt><br>
              <dt>You, the College, or anyone authorized by you, may file your application for disability benefits.  Application forms are available from the Retirement System or the Office of Human Resources.
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you think you are eligible, you may submit applications for both ordinary and accidental disability retirement benefits.  However, both must be submitted before your effective retirement date.
<dt><br>
              <dt>You are also eligible to select an option for the payment of  your disability benefits.  More information, is found in the Retirement System booklet entitled, "YOUR OPTIONS AT RETIREMENT."

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C5ei">i</A>)   Ordinary Disability Benefits
<dt><br>
                   <dt>If you become physically or mentally disabled on a permanent basis, you may be eligible for an ordinary disability retirement benefit.  In order to qualify, you must have at least 10 years of service credit.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>If you entered government service before age 40, your ordinary disability retirement benefit is 1/60th (1.66%) of your final average salary for each year of service credit.  Various factors (withdrawn contributions, periods out of service, and loans, among others) may reduce your benefit but, generally, the minimum allowance is one-third of your final average salary.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>If you entered government service after attaining age 40, your benefit is equal to 1/60th (1.66%) of your final average salary multiplied by the number of years of possible service before you reach age 60.  Remember that your retirement allowance may be reduced, due to withdrawn contributions, loans, and other factors.  However, the minimum allowance is generally one-third of your final average salary.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>An application for this benefit may be submitted either while you are actually in the service upon which your  membership is based or while on a medical leave of absence.  Should you be separated from service, you must file your  application with the Retirement System within 90 days after termination of service.

             </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C5eii">ii</A>)   Accidental Disability Benefits
<dt><br>
                   <dt>Regardless of your time in service, if you become physically or mentally unable to perform your job as the direct result of an on-the-job accident which was not due to your willful negligence, you may be eligible for an accidental disability retirement benefit.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>In order to qualify, written notice of your accident must be filed with the Retirement System within 90 days of the accident, detailing the time and place of the incident, the particulars thereof, the nature and extent of your injuries, and your alleged incapacity.  The notice must be signed by you or someone acting on your behalf.  Your application for benefits must be filed before you reach age 60.  Should you be separated from service, either voluntarily or involuntarily, your application may be submitted within 2 years of your date of separation.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>If approved, your accidental disability retirement benefit will be a pension equal to:
<dt><br>
                    <dd>*   60% of the first $15,300 of your final average salary,
<dt><br>
                    <dd>*   50% of your final average salary over $15,300, and
<dt><br>
                    <dd>*   40% of any final average salary over $27,300.
<dt><br>
                   <dt>This benefit will be reduced by the total amount of  Workers' Compensation benefits that you are or may become entitled to receive.  Members who are eligible for Workers' Compensation must apply for these benefits.  In addition to your pension, you will receive an annuity provided by any contributions you may have made during your working years.
</dl>
          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C5g">f</A>)  Contributions
<dt><br>
              <dt>As a Tier II member of the New Career Plan, you are not required to contribute towards your retirement benefits.  However, you may elect to make voluntary contributions to the Retirement System.  These contributions, plus interest, will provide additional annuity income for you when you retire.

          </dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6C5h">g</A>)  Loans
<dt><br>
              <dt>If you have made contributions towards your retirement benefits,  have at least one year of service credit, and are still on payroll, you may apply for a loan against your contributions.  Eligible members may obtain an application form from the Retirement System or Office of Human Resources.
</dl>
     </dl>
<br><br>
<B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="S6C6-9.html">Continue to next section</A></B>
