<BR>
<BR>
                            <center><strong>X.  STUDENT SERVICES</strong></center>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A"><b>A</a>.	STUDENT SERVICES PROGRAM</b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>The Office of the Vice President for Enrollment Student Services is responsible for the coordination of an effective student affairs program, the aim of which is to assist each student to achieve experience and growth toward his/her own personal goals and those which the College sets for him/her.  The Student Services  Division acts as a service agency for both students and faculty which serves best when both freely use its help for information, discussion, and common action on individual problems.

	<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A1"><i>1</a>.	COUNSELING CENTER</i>

		<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A1a">a</a>)	Services
<dt><br>
			<dt>The College Counseling Center exists to provide professional psychological services to students experiencing ongoing or situational difficulties.  Both individual and group counseling are offered to assist students to cope more effectively with personal problems that may interfere with their ability to function.  Typical concerns include childhood and adult abuse issues, relationship difficulties, eating disorders, drug and alcohol problems, self-esteem, study habits, crisis and loss situations, depression and anxiety, gender concerns, etc.  The Center's primary focus is on short-term counseling.   
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Center provides consultative services and training sessions to various groups on campus.  Peer educators, trained through this office, are available for outreach programming to increase student awareness on a number of relevant issues.
 <dt><br>
			<dt>Information shared in counseling is treated in strict confidence and receives full protection under the law.
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Employee Assistance Program (EAP) is the primary resource for counseling assistance and referral for faculty and staff.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A1b">b</a>)	Policy on Consultation, Confidentiality, and Referral
      
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A1bi">i</a>)	Consultation with Faculty and Staff
<dt><br>
				<dt>Counseling Center personnel are available to provide consultations to Deans, Residence Life staff, and other faculty and staff concerning approaches to and handling of particular cases, including recommendations on courses of action or referrals.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A1bii">ii</a>)	Confidentiality
<dt><br>
				<dt>Information shared by student clients in a counseling session will be treated with the strictest confidentiality, and will not be disclosed without written permission, except when in the judgment of the counselor such disclosure is necessary to protect the student client or someone else from imminent physical or psychological danger.  While information will not be released to an outside agency without written permission, as professionals Counseling Center staff may confer with each other in order to improve services to students.

			</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A1biii">iii</a>)	Referrals

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A1biiia">(a)</a>	Routine
         <dt><br>
					<dt>Students may be referred on an informal basis to the Counseling Center at any time for assistance in connection with personal, psychological and/or other mental health related problems.  Such a referral may be recommended or suggested by the faculty or staff member; but, if accepted by the student, it is on a voluntary, non-mandatory basis.
<dt><br>
					<dt>To protect the confidentiality of the student, notification of attendance cannot be made.  However, a request to the Counseling Center by the faculty or staff member at the time of the referral will result in notification if a referred student does not appear. Further information will not be released.
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A2"><i>2</a>.	THOMAS M. BARRINGTON STUDENT UNION</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Student Union is a large complex located between the residence halls and the academic quad.  It houses the offices of Student Government Association, College Union Board, The Racquette (student newspaper), The Pioneer (yearbook), the Gamma Sigma Sigma Lost & Found, and a number of smaller student organizations.  There is a large multi-purpose room which can accommodate a variety of activities and several meeting rooms of various sizes.  The Union also houses the College Store, two short-order cafeterias, an ice cream and cookie shop, and a pizza parlor.  College offices in the Student Union include the Director of the Student Union & Activities, the Assistant Vice President for Student Development, the Director of Multicultural Affairs, and the Director of Campus Life.
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Student Union is open seven days per week during the academic year (except for official college vacations) and weekdays during the summer.  Hours are posted at each entrance.
 <dt><br>
		<center><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="student absences">EXTENDED STUDENT ABSENCES</A></center>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Office of the Director of Student Union and Activities has, as a courtesy, continued the procedure of notifying faculty when a notice of extended student absence is received.  The guidelines under which the Office responds are as follows:
<dt><br>
		<dd>a)	Office of Student Union and Activities does not excuse students from classes.  It notifies the faculty when there are extended absences.
<dt><br>
		<dd>b)	Office of Student Union and Activities does not notify faculty for brief, common illnesses of short duration (generally, less than five days).
<dt><br>
		<dd>c)	A memorandum from the Office of Student Union and Activities is not required for faculty to excuse students from classes.
		<dt><br>
		<dd>d)	The guidelines used for extended absences are as follows:
<dt><br>
			<dd>--a death in the immediate faculty<br>
			<dd>--a serious accident involving a student or a member of his/her immediate faculty<br>
			<dd>--a serious illness, hospitalization or surgery involving a student or a member of his/her immediate family<br>
			<dd>--miscellaneous absences (maternity, paternity, situations involving a fiancee, etc.).
<dt><br>
		<dd>e)	All notices of extended student absences are provided to the Office of Academic Services at the end of each semester in the event that these absences have impacted academic success.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A3"><i>3</a>.	DINING SERVICES</i>
<Dt><br>
		<dt>Dining facilities are open from the first day of registration through the last day of exams each semester.  Specific schedules are available in the Dining Services office located in Thatcher Hall.  Residential dining facilities are not open over extended recess periods of more than three days.  Special arrangements can be made by contacting the Catering Office in Thatcher Hall.
<dt><br>
		<dt><!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="PACES">PACES</A> operates three major dining facilities; the Barrington Student Union, Lehman Hall and Thatcher Hall.  
<dt><br>
		<dt>A food court is located in the Barrington Student Union.  This area includes:  the Bears' Den (a pasta & pizza restaurant), Cookies, Cream & Company, The Grill, The Proud Pickle Deli, and a traditional-style diner.
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Gallery, a full service restaurant open for weekday lunches and Tuesday night dinner, is located in Thatcher Hall.  Snack Bars are located in Carson Hall and the Crane Commons.  The snack bar in Carson Hall, The Greenery, is open year round (Monday - Friday). 
<dt><br>
          		<dt>Lehman Dining Hall includes eight food concepts:  Traditional, Italian, Vegetarian, Grilled, Deli, Breakfast (continental) and a Wokery.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A4"><i>4</a>.	HEALTH SERVICES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Watkins Student Health Service offers comprehensive health care to all students.  The services include episodic illness/injury care; health/wellness counseling and education; gynecological exams and treatment, including contraception; STD screening, counseling, and treatment for men and women (including HIV testing); allergy injections and immunizations; and a full range of preventive and educational campus outreach programs.  The Health Service also provides most necessary laboratory services and distributes many commonly required medications.
<dt><br>
		<dt>The student health mission is to maintain an optimum environment for students to pursue their academic work with a minimum of health- related interferences.  Goals of the Health Service are to deliver efficient care to students with illness or injury, encourage optimal wellness through the promotion of healthy lifestyle practices, and to empower students to become well informed consumers of health care services.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A5"><i>5</a>.	SPECIAL PROGRAMS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Office of Special Programs coordinates the <!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="eop">Educational Opportunity Program (EOP)</A>.
<dt><br>
		<dt>EOP is a special admissions and retention program for students who are both educationally and economically disadvantaged, but who possess the potential for academic success.  Tutoring, counseling and financial assistance are provided to enrolled students.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A6"><i>6</a>.	ORIENTATION PROGRAMS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>SUNY Potsdam offers all new students a formal opportunity to become acquainted with its academic programs, facilities, faculty and staff.  Orientation occurs after admission and prior to matriculation.  All students (including freshmen, transfers and adult learners) who will be entering during the fall semester are invited to attend.  For mid-year matriculants, there is an additional session held just before classes begin in January.
<dt><br>
		<dt>The primary function of orientation is to assist students in their transition to the SUNY Potsdam environment.  A significant part of that process is working individually with an experienced academic adviser and selecting one's courses.  Other activities typically include discussions of graduation requirements, introductions to various academic and social policies, discussions of financial aid, meeting with the staff of such offices as Residence Life and developing familiarity with numerous College services.  In conjunction with the freshman sessions, there are also separate parallel parent orientation programs.  Orientation programs are coordinated by the Office of New Student Programs.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A7"><i>7</a>.	RESIDENCE LIFE</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A7a">a</a>)	Residence Halls 
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students have many options as to living arrangements, including single room, double, or suite in co-ed or all-male or all-female facilities.  Special interest housing options compliment the residential program. The residence halls are staffed with professionals, paraprofessionals and upper-class students  who serve as Resident Assistants helping students adjust to college life and deal with various contemporary problems.  There is one Resident Assistant for every 25 students.

<dt><br>
<A NAME="10A7b">b</a>)	College Housing Policy
<dt><br>
			<dt>All students are required to live on campus until they have accumulated 88 credits toward graduation.  Students transferring to Potsdam are required to live for at least one year on-campus. Transfer students should contact the Residence Life Office as to their status.  Exceptions may be made for students living at home, for married students, and veterans on a case by case basis decided by the Director of Residence Life. 

<dt><br>
<A NAME="10A7c">c)	Programming
<dt><br>
			<dt>SUNY Potsdam is able to house approximately two-thirds of its students in residence halls on the campus.  While the primary purpose of these residences is obviously to provide students with a place to reside while pursuing their studies at the College, their existence presents a great opportunity to promote  a living/learning environment.
<dt><br>
			<dt>The existence of these accommodations has allowed SUNY Potsdam to become primarily a residential college.  The College views residential life as a fundamental component of the Potsdam educational experience.  Residences are not simply a convenient place to live, but, in the Potsdam context, are units in which the intellectual, social, and cultural development of students is promoted.  The Residence Hall environment can promote student development and learning throughout the institution.
<dt><br>
			<dt>Given this perception of the role of student residences, educational, social, and cultural programming is far more than an agreeable supplement to residence life.  Educational programming, particularly that which is integrated with academic units, is a crucial part of the residential experience.  Such programming should be diverse and varied and implemented in conjunction with academic units.  It should provide students with a choice of living situations, and it should stress the integration of campus life, curricular and co-curricular.
<dt><br>
			<dt>Residence Hall programming is developed in numerous ways.  Some programming originates with, and is implemented, by students.  Other programming is developed by faculty and staff, with the expectation that students will find this programming of benefit. The Residence Life staff experiments and takes original approaches to programming.  They study successful programs at other institutions and replicate them where appropriate.
<dt><br>
			<dt>While sound management practices and fiscal responsibility are essential, Residence Life is not be construed as a business or as a profit making venture.  Its main purpose is to advance the academic, intellectual, and social development of students and to assist in the achievement of the academic goals of the College.  
<dt><br>
			<dt>Stress is placed on the comfort of students and on the creation of a congenial living environment, and students are treated at all times as participants in rather than involuntary residents of the system.  To the extent possible, students have a share in the governance of residences and in the development of policies. They are consulted not only on programming but also on budgetary matters, including the establishment of room rental rates.  It is important to note, however, that extensive consultation does not mean the yielding of control:  the Office of Residence Life remains accountable to the institution both for the management of residences and also for the furtherance of the institution's academic goals.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A8"><i>8</a>.	STUDENT SUPPORT SERVICES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Student Support Services is a federally funded program designed to assist participants with academic and other concerns during their college career.  Our goal is to provide the academic support necessary to help students remain in school and reach graduation. Services include:  peer tutoring, counseling (personal and financial), academic planning, study skills assistance, peer mentoring, and career and graduate school exploration. Student Support Services works in cooperation with other offices at SUNY Potsdam. 

<dt><br>
		<dt>Participants must be U.S. citizens, accepted for enrollment at Potsdam, have a need for academic support, and meet one or more of the following criteria:
<dt><br>
		<dd>-first generation college student (neither parent has a four year college degree)
<dt><br>
		<dd>-fall within income limits set by the U.S. Department of Education (verified by our office)		
		<dt><br>
		<dd>-physically and/or learning disabled (valid documentation is required) 

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9"><i>9</a>.	CAREER PLANNING</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Career Planning Office provides the following services to SUNY Potsdam students and alumni:

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9a">a</a>)	Career Identification
     <dt><br>
			<dt>Individual counseling, the Harrington O'Shea Test, and the SIGI and interactive computer program assist in selecting career options.  This service has proven to be of value whether or not students have already chosen their academic majors.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9b">b</a>)	Career Entry
<dt><br>
			<dt>Individual counseling and group workshops in job-search strategies, writing resumes and cover letters and developing interviewing skills are provided.  This service also includes employer recruiting and the maintenance of reference files (reference letters).

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9c">c</a>)	Career Management
<dt><br>
			<dt>This program is primarily an alumni service in career progression or career change.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9d">d</a>)	Library
<dt><br>
			<dt>A wide range of career descriptions and employer references are cataloged and housed in the Career Planning Library in Sisson Hall.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9e">e</a>)	Student Computer
<dt><br>
			<dt>We provide a computer and laser printer for student use in preparing resumes, and for quick access to the Internet.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9f">f</a>)	Internet
<dt><br>
			<dt>Through our page on the WEB, accessible from all campus computers, you have access to:  job postings, places to submit your resume electronically, information about office services, financial aid, employers, graduate schools, internships, and career information.  

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9g">g</a>)	Job Vacancy Lists
<dt><br>
			<dt>Job vacancy lists are also maintained year-round in the areas of education, business, social service, arts, environment, public affairs, music, writing/editing, and liberal arts.
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9h">h</a>)	Networking
<dt><br>
			<dt>Career Planning staff assists students with selecting and contacting employers of specific interest to them.  They also provide follow-up with the employers and students, working to develop a meaningful career experience while at SUNY Potsdam.  All majors are eligible.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9i">i</a>)	Summer and Part-time Jobs
<dt><br>
			<dt>The office monitors information on summer jobs and provides special guidelines pertaining to them.  Community part-time jobs are also posted.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9j">j</a>)	Major Affair
<dt><br>
			<dt>With Residence Life, we co-sponsor an evening program to help students select a major.  All academic departments are present, allowing students to ask questions and discuss ideas with faculty and upper class students in the major.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9k">k</a>)	Potsdam R.E.S.U.M.E. Program (Resume Employer Service Unique Matching Express Program)
<dt><br>

			<dt>The purpose is to supply employers with quick access to SUNY Potsdam students/alumni resumes.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9l">l</a>)	SUNYCDO Job Fair
<dt><br>

			<dt>In cooperation with other SUNY campuses, we co-sponsor a Spring state-wide job fair for Potsdam seniors and alumni.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9m">m</a>)	Presentations
<dt><br>

			<dt>We are glad to visit classes, residence halls, fraternities and sororities, academic organization meetings, campus organizations, and special interest groups to describe services, answer questions, or give workshops.  Just call to work out the details.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A9n">n</a>)	Extended Office Hours
<dt><br>

			<dt>We extend office hours to 6:30 p.m. two days each week, with these days varying per semester.
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<A NAME="10A10"><i>10</a>.	STUDENT CONDUCT</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Section 356 of the Education Law empowers the College Council to make regulations governing the conduct and behavior of students.  All programs for student welfare and conduct are entrusted to and administered by the President of the College.  The administration of student conduct regulations and the College Judicial System is  delegated by the President to the Vice President for Student Life and is specifically the responsibility of the Judicial Coordinator who is appointed by the Vice President.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A11"><i>11</a>.	STUDENT JUDICIAL SYSTEM</i>
<dt><br>
		<Dt>The Student Judicial System at Potsdam is under the direction of the Assistant Vice President for Student Life  who acts as the Judicial Coordinator.  Details of the Student Judicial System are found in the Code of Student Rights, Responsibilities and Conduct, copies of which are available from the Office of the Assistant Vice President for Student Life and are also included in the Residence Life Handbook and the Student Handbook.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A12"><i>12</a>.	STUDENT ORGANIZATIONS</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A12a">a</a>)	Deposit of Operating Funds
<dt><br>
			<dt>It has been the College's practice to require student organizations or student groups to deposit their operating funds with PACES.  The following policy is a codification of that practice.
<dt><br>
			<dt>All student organizations, clubs or groups, whether SGA- recognized or not, excluding certain off-campus organizations such as sororities or fraternities, shall be required to deposit their operating funds in a PACES agency account.  Such funds shall be disbursed by PACES in accordance with written instructions in the form of a check request from the student organization.  PACES shall not be required to pay interest on such accounts but shall provide bookkeeping and accounting services to the organizations or groups depositing such funds.
</dl>
	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A13"><i>13</a>.	VETERANS SERVICES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Veterans and active duty personnel seeking assistance in obtaining educational benefits under federal programs and should contact the Registrar's Office.  Those receiving benefits are required to file monthly attendance reports in that office. 

	</dl>
<dt><br><br>
<BR>
<B><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="S10.14-26.html">Continue to next section</A></B>
<BR>

