<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chapter 10 14-26</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#ff00ff">

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=87  SRC="../FACBOOK.GIF"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
                             <center><strong>X.  STUDENT SERVICES</strong></center>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A14"><i>14</a>.	OFFICE OF DISABLED STUDENT SERVICES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Office of Disabled Student Services (DSS) provides services for qualified students with documented physical, learning, and/or psychiatric disabilities who need academic accommodations in the classroom.  Accommodations are determined on an individualized basis, with consideration given to the student's documentation and opportunity for academic access and in light of the essential eligibility requirements of the service, activity, course or program of study.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Some of the services provided or coordinated include:  notetakers, text readers, exam readers and scribes, extended exam time, distraction-reduced exam location, relocation of classrooms, auxiliary equipment loan, academic advising, the ordering of taped texts, special orientation to campus, priority registration, personal growth and career counseling, as well as liaison with and referral to faculty, staff, and community agencies.  Students are encouraged to become self-advocates, to take increasing responsibility for speaking with faculty and community agencies.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A15"><i>15</a>.	THE STUDENT WORD PROCESSING LAB</i>
 <dt><br>
		<dt>The English Department operates the Student Word Processing Lab in Morey Hall.  Macintosh Plus computers with associated disk drives and printers are available for student word processing.  The facility is supervised by English Department faculty on weekdays from 8 a.m. to 4 p.m.  Priority for use is given to students required to use word processors in English courses, but the Lab is available to the general campus community.  Writing classes are occasionally conducted in the Lab.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A16"><i>16</a>.	THE LEVITT CENTER</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The James H. Levitt Memorial Computer Center, located in Crumb Library is managed by Distributed Computing/TeleMedia Department and provides public access to campus computing resources.  The Center is connected to the campus network (and to SUNYNet and the national Internet) and has access to standard campus applications as well as other instruction-related computing activities.  The Levitt Center has Macintosh and PC computers, dot-matrix printing and laser printing (free for students with a SUNY Potsdam ID card).  While SUNY Potsdam students and faculty have priority in the use of this facility, the public may use these facilities as available.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A17"><i>17</a>.	THE KELLAS HALL COMPUTER CLASSROOM</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Kellas Hall Computer Classroom is managed by the Distributed Computing/TeleMedia Department and is equipped with 25 Macintosh computers and a LCD-type projection system for large screen viewing.  Each computer is connected to the campus network (and to SUNYNet and the national Internet) and has access to an AppleShare file server and a variety of applications including word processing, spreadsheets and communication (Gopher, NetNews, FTP, TELNET, Mosaic, Email).  Use of this classroom for instructional purposes must be reserved.  Contact the Distributed Computing/TeleMedia Department (x2083) for more information.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A18"><I>18</a>.	THE DUNN HALL COMPUTER CLASSROOM</I>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Dunn Hall Computer Classroom is managed by the Computer and Information Sciences Department and is equipped with 15 Zenith 386 computers and a LCD-type projection system for large screen viewing.  Each computer is connected to the campus network (and to SUNYNet and the national Internet) and has access to an AppleShare file server and a variety of applications including word processing, spreadsheets and communications (Gopher, NetNews, FTP, TELNET, Mosaic, Email).  Use of this classroom for instructional purposes must be reserved.  Contact the Distributed Computing/TeleMedia Department (x2083) for more information.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A19"><I>19</a>.	THE FLAGG HALL COMPUTER CLASSROOM</I>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Flagg Hall Computer Classroom is managed by the Distributed Computing/TeleMedia Department and is equipped with 25 Zenith 486 computers and a LCD-type projection system for large screen viewing.  Each computer is connected to the campus network (and to SUNYNet and the national Internet) and has access to a Novell Netware server and a variety of applications including word processing, spreadsheets and communications (Gopher, NetNews, FTP, TELNET, Mosaic, Email).  Use of this classroom for instructional purposes must be reserved.  Contact the CIS Department (x2074) for more information.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A20"><I>20</a>.	RESIDENCE HALL COMPUTER CENTERS</I>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Residence Hall (Bowman, Draime, Knowles, Lehman, Van Housen) Computing Centers offer students access to Macintosh and PC computers and dot-matrix printing on a 24-hours, 7-day basis.  Student assistants are available from 6pm to 11pm, Sunday through Thursday, to manage laser-printing services and to provide assistance to the center's student users.  The centers are connected to the campus network (and to SUNYNet and the national Internet) and have access to standard campus applications.  These centers are also accessible to disabled persons.
</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A23"><I>21</a>.	POTSDAM/AKWESASNE TALENT SEARCH PROGRAM (PATS)</I>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The PATS Program provides a variety of support services to encourage postsecondary education among low income, potential first generation college students.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Participants must have completed the fifth grade and show potential for postsecondary education.  Adults as well as persons currently in school are served.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Services are provided through St. Lawrence County Schools, Salmon River Central School, Akwesasne Mohawk Schools and through community agencies serving these areas.  PATS provides a linkage between SUNY Potsdam and the North Country Communities that it serves.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A24"><I>22</a>.	SCIENCE AND TECHNOLOGY ENTRY PROGRAM (STEP)</I>
<dt><br>
		<dt>North Country STEP is an education enrichment program that provides academic support services and experiential career development activities to 7th through 12th grade students from minority and/or low income backgrounds.  The objectives of STEP are to encourage selection and persistence in high school math and science courses, and enrollment in scientific, technological, health or health- related two- or four-year college programs.  North Country STEP services are provided at no cost to eligible students at participating schools.
<dt><br>
		<dt>SUNY Potsdam students act as mentors and volunteer tutors at local junior and senior high schools.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A25"><I>23</a>.	NATIVE AMERICAN AFFAIRS</I>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Office of Native American Affairs serves as the principal resource for the Northern Consortium, SUNY Native American Initiative at SUNY Potsdam, a regional group of colleges working to increase the recruitment and retention of Native American students in higher education.  Operating within the college's Multicultural Affairs Division, the Office assists in maintaining involvement and input from college, regional, and state-wide Native American advisory councils.  SUNY Potsdam's proximity (35 miles) to the St. Regis Mohawk Reservation at Akwesasne has allowed for a variety of unique collaborations between the two communities.  This Office helps facilitate such activities, sponsors Native American cultural awareness events and serves as an information clearinghouse.

	</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="10A26"><I>24</a>.	HANDICAPPED ACCESS</I>
<dt><br>
		<dt>It is the policy and intent of SUNY Potsdam that no otherwise qualified disabled individual shall, solely by reason of his or her disability, be subject to discrimination, as required by Section 504 of the Rehabilitation Act of 1973 and the Americans with Disabilities Act.  In accordance with such requirements and with the College's own policies and programs, reasonable physical accommodations for disabled persons will be made when necessary and appropriate.  In compliance with the recommendation of the Office of Civil Rights, disabled persons may request that classes meeting in buildings that are not accessible, such as those in Carson Hall, be moved to other locations that are accessible to the physically disabled.
</dl>
</dl>
<BR>

<br>


