<BR>
<center>
<strong>XII.  CAMPUS POLICIES</strong>
</center>
<dt><br><BR>

<dd><dl>
<A NAME="12A"><b>A</a>.	CAMPUS POLICIES AND PROCEDURES</b>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="12A32"><i>32</A>.	LIBRARY LOAN POLICIES</i>
 <dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A32a">a</A>)	Frederick W. Crumb Memorial Library
 <dt><br>
			<dt>Students and faculty of SUNY Potsdam and the three other colleges in Potsdam and Canton, as well as the community at large, may borrow library materials and use  the services offered by the Crumb Library.  Students enrolled at any SUNY campus have library privileges throughout SUNY.
<dt><br>
			<dt>Library materials borrowed by students and community residents are due 28 days following the day that they are signed out or at the end of the semester, whichever comes first.  SUNY Potsdam faculty loans are due 120 days following the day that they are signed out.  For all borrowers, maps and videos are due 2 days after they are signed out.  All periodicals are library use only.
               <dt><br>
			<dt>Any library material may be recalled before the due date at the request of another borrower.  Failure to respond to a recall notice will result in a fine of five dollars plus one dollar for each additional day up to a maximum recall fine of fifty dollars per item.  
<dt><br>
			<dt>The overdue fine is $1.00 per day per item to a maximum of $50.00 per item.  There is a grace period of 14 days, during which there is no fine for material that is returned or renewed.  The fine that applies after the grace period expires is retroactive to the first day material is overdue.
               <dt><br>
			<dt>In addition, failure to respond to a recall or to return overdue material will result in a suspension of borrowing privileges.  In addition, SUNY Potsdam students who have not cleared their library records will be unable to register again and their transcripts will be withheld.
<dt><br>
			<dt>Library materials may be renewed in person or by phone (267-2485) unless a recall request is pending.
</dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A32b">b</A>)	Crane Library
<dt><br>
			<dt>Students, faculty and staff of SUNY Potsdam and the three other colleges in Potsdam and Canton, as well as the community at large and students at other SUNY campuses, may borrow library materials and use the services offered by the Crane Library.
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	Circulating Material
<dt><br>
				<dt>There are two categories of circulating materials in Crane Library.  The majority of these materials circulate for the same period of time as do materials from Crumb Library.  A second category of materials circulate for a limited time period.<br><BR>
<dt><B>Regular Circulating Materials</B>
<BR>
<dt>These include most books and scores, and the policies are similar to those established by Crumb Library.  Library materials borrowed by students and community residents are due 28 days following the day that they are signed out or at the end of the semester, whichever comes first.  SUNY Potsdam faculty loans are due 120 days following the day that they are first signed out.  All periodicals are library use only.
<BR>
<BR>

<dt>Any library material may be recalled before the due date at the request of another borrower.  Failure to respond to a recall notice will result in a fine of five dollars plus one dollar for each additional day up to a maximum recall fine of fifty dollars per item. 
<br><BR>
<dt>The overdue fine is $1.00 per day per item to a maximum of $50.00 per item.  There is a grace period of 14 days, during which there is no fine for material that is returned or renewed.  The fine that applies after the grace period expires is retroactive to the first day material is overdue.<BR>
<BR>
<dt>In addition, failure to respond to a recall or to return overdue material will result in a suspension of borrowing privileges.  Furthermore, SUNY Potsdam students who have not cleared their library records will be unable to register again and their transcripts will be withheld.<BR>
<BR>
<dt>Library materials may be renewed in person or by phone (267-2451) unless a recall request is pending.<BR>
<BR>

<dt><B>Materials Circulating For a Limited Time Period</B>
<BR>
<dt>These include historical sets of music and complete works of composers (scored classified in M2 and M3).  Materials in these categories borrowed by students and community residents must be returned by closing on the day they are borrowed.  Materials borrowed by faculty are due 5 days after they are first signed out.<BR>
<BR>
<dt>Procedures concerning recalls, overdues, and renewals are similar to those established for regular circulating materials.<BR>
<BR>

			<dt>ii)	Non-circulating Material
<dt><br>
				<dt>Non-circulating materials include records, compact discs, cassette and open-reel tapes, video recordings,
periodicals, reserve materials, restricted materials,
reference books, and graduate theses. Faculty may make special arrangements to borrow these materials for instructional or research purposes.
<dt><br>

<dt>A fine of five dollars plus one dollar per each additional day up to a maximum of $50.00 per item will be levied for failure to respond to a recall notice.
<dt><br>

<dt>Overdue notices are sent if materials are not returned by their due dates.  Failure to respond to a recall or to return overdue material will result in a suspension of borrowing privileges.
<dt><br>
<dt>Materials may be renewed in person or by phone (267-2451) unless a recall request is pending.
</dl><!-- 3 -->
</dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A32c">c</A>)	Appeal Process
<dt><br>
			<dt>An individual may appeal a fine or suspension of his/her borrowing privileges by appealing to the Director of Libraries in writing within ten calendar days of the receipt of notice of the fine and/or suspension of privileges.  The response of the Director of Libraries shall be issued within five calendar days of receipt of  the appeal by written notification to the appellant.
<dt><br>
<dt>If the Director of Libraries sustains the fine and/or suspension, the appellant may appeal to the Provost within five calendar days of receipt of the Director's response.  The response of the Vice Provost shall be issued within five calendar days of the receipt of the appeal by written notification to the appellant.
<dt><br>
<dt>If the Provost sustains the fine and/or suspension, the appellant may appeal to the President's Designee within five days of receipt of the Provost's response.  The response of the President's Designee shall be issued within five calendar days of receipt of the appeal by written notification to the appellant.  The decision of the President's Designee is final.
<dt><br>
<dt>A fine and/or suspension of borrowing privileges may be effected only after completion of the appeal process or if the appeal is not made in a timely manner.
</dl><!-- 2 -->
</dl><!--1 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A33"><i>33</A>.	MAINTENANCE AND PUBLIC ORDER</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>With respect to public assemblies, SUNY Potsdam will observe and implement the SUNY Board of Trustees' policy entitled "Rules and Regulations for Maintenance of Public Order on Premises of State-Operated Institutions of the State University of New York."  Copies of this document are on file in the Crumb Library and are available from the Office of the Assistant Vice President for Student Development, 105 Barrington Student Union.
<dt><br>
<dt>This policy specifies that each campus communicate these rules to the college community and adopt and promulgate procedures for giving reasonable notice and details of any planned assembly, picketing, or demonstration on the grounds or in buildings of the institution.  To this end, the following local procedures and guidelines are in effect at SUNY Potsdam.
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
<dt>a)	Definitions
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
	<dt>i)	The term SUNY Potsdam shall refer to facilities under the jurisdiction of SUNY Potsdam including buildings, grounds, parking lots, classrooms, and equipment in Potsdam and at the Star Lake Campus.
</dl><!-- 3 -->
<dt><br>
		<dt>b)	Guidelines for any planned assembly, picketing, or demonstration on grounds or in buildings at SUNY Potsdam.
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
<dt>i)	Any notification of such activities involving SUNY Potsdam facilities shall be made on the form provided by the College and must be on file at least three (3) working days in advance of the activity. The notification forms should be obtained from the Office of Public Safety, completed, and returned to that office.
<dt><br>
<dt>If unusual or unforeseen circumstances prevent observance of the three day notification period, it shall be the responsibility of the person(s) organizing the activity to notify the appropriate designee and to complete appropriate forms at least four (4) hours before any activity begins.  In addition, if the use of specific campus buildings, equipment, or other property will be used in connection with the planned activity, it is the responsibility of the sponsoring organization to obtain permission to use such campus facilities through the normal channels specified in existing College policies.  These policies require that use of a College facility by any College affiliated group must be obtained from the individual building administrator responsible for that facility.  All requests to use College facilities by any non-    College affiliated group must be submitted to the     Office of Continuing Education.
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	In addition to the conduct specified in the Board of     Trustees' policy section 535.3, no activity may:
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
<dt>(a)	amplify sound that interferes with class activity, College activities, or that is in violation of Village ordinances or other ordinances,
<dt><br>
				<dt>(b)	modify or alter College facilities without permission from the College.
</dl><!-- 4 -->
<dt><br>
			<dt>iii)	Revocation or withdrawal of permission to use a College facility may occur at any time due to unforeseen operational problems, or for violation of the above section ii).
<dt><br>
<dt>If, in the judgment of College officials, an activity is not consistent with the intended purposes as specified in the notification form, or the activity has been misrepresented, permission to use the College facility shall be withdrawn and the activity in progress shall be halted.  
<dt><br>
			<dt>iv)	The use of College facilities does not imply the College's endorsement of the purposes or views of the sponsors of the activity in question.
</dl><!-- 3 -->
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	</dl><!--1 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A34"><i>34</A>.	NEWS POLICY</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>All programs sponsored by the College, including workshops, conferences, non-credit courses, lectures, concerts, exhibitions, etc. are to be publicized only with the assistance of the College Relations Office.  Faculty and staff approached by the media to discuss personal or academic interests should feel free to respond, but are asked to inform the College Relations Office that the media contact has happened.  Any faculty or staff member approached by the media to discuss a College program or policy should refer the reporter to the College Relations Office.

	</dl><!--1 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A35"><i>35</A>.	NOTIFICATION OF RESIGNATION OR RETIREMENT</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Faculty planning on retiring or resigning are instructed to notify the College President in writing specifying the effective date.  A copy of the notification should also be sent to the appropriate Vice President and Dean/Director and the employee's immediate supervisor.
<dt><br>
<dt>Employees are encouraged to give such notification as far in advance of the effective date as is possible and feasible in order to allow sufficient time for planning and recruitment.
<dt><br>
<dt>The agreement calls for employees who intend to leave the employ of the University to give thirty (30) days notice to the President or designee.

	</dl><!--1 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A36"><i>36</A>.	OFFICE HOURS</i>

	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A36a">a</A>)	College Offices
<dt><br>
			<dt>Offices will open no later than 8:30 a.m.
<dt><br>
			<dt>Offices will not close before 4:30 p.m. during the academic year and will not close before 4:00 p.m. during the summer (i.e., between commencement day and the first day of the fall semester).
 <dt><br>
<dt>In unusual circumstances and only with the approval of the appropriate Vice President/Provost, specific services may be available only at certain times, so that the office can concentrate on the major priorities.  However, the office      must remain open and the hours during which the limited      services are offered must be posted.
 <dt><br>
<dt>In offices in which there is more than one clerical employee, work schedules are to be arranged to provide continuous coverage over the lunch hour.
 <dt><br>
<dt>Classified service employees are entitled to two fifteen minute coffee breaks per day, one in the morning and one in the afternoon.  This break time cannot be used to extend the lunch hour or to change arrival or departure time.
 <dt><br>
<dt>The scheduling of office coverage and the limiting of specific services within the above policies is the responsibility of the office supervisor in consultation with the immediate supervisor.

 		</dl><!--2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A36b">b</A>)	Teaching Faculty
 <dt><br>
			<dt>All teaching faculty are expected to maintain a regular schedule of office hours for consultation with students.  The number of hours and the particular schedule are determined by the faculty member with the condition that they are sufficient enough and convenient enough to assure accessibility to students.  The time of such hours should be distributed throughout the week as far as possible.  Special provision should be made through appointments for students unable to meet with instructors at announced times.  The schedule of office hours should be posted outside the instructor's office and announced in class.
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	</dl><!--1 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
<I>37.  OMNI<A NAME="12A37">BUS TRANSPORTATIO</A>N EMPLOYEE TESTING ACT OF 1991</I><BR>
<BR>
The Omnibus Transportation Employee Testing Act of 1991 requires the establishment of rules reguiring alcohol and drug testing programs for employees engaged in safety-sensitive functions in the aviation, motor carrier, rail, transit, and service industries.  This policy addresses the requirements and conditions of the drug and alcohol testing rules, focusing on the regulatory requirements, as they affect SUNY Potsdam.<BR>
<BR>
Effective  January 1, 1996, all employees who are considered "safety-sensitive" are covered by the Act.  A safety-sensitive employee is defined as one who has a commerical drivers license (CDL)  AND operates or may be called upon the College to operate a commerical motor vehicle (CMV).  A commerical motor vehicle is one that weighs over 26,000 pounds or; is designed to carry 16 or more people, including driver or; is used to transport hazardous materials which is required to be placarded or; requires a CDL to operate for other reasons.<BR>
<BR>



		<dt><A NAME="12A38"><i>38</A>.	PERSONAL PROPERTY</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Faculty are cautioned that neither the College or the State of New York are responsible for personal property brought on campus.  Individuals should assure themselves that their personal insurance covers such property while on campus.

	</dl><!--1 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A39"><i>39</A>.	POLITICAL ACTIVITIES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The State University encourages you to exercise your constitutional right to vote and support the political party and candidate of your choice.  You should be aware, however, that if your position is one which is funded by federal monies, any political activities you pursue may be subject to the provisions of the Federal Hatch Act.  Also, please remember that if you participate in any political activities, you must not participate in them during your work hours and they must never involve the use of State equipment, supplies,      or services of any kind.  Refer to Section 107 of the Civil Service Law, federal Hatch Act, or contact the Office of Human Resources.

	</dl><!--1 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A40"><i>40</A>.	PRINTING AND PUBLICATIONS POLICY</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Office of College Relations is charged with producing the SUNY Potsdam Publications that are destined for an external audience.  The publications staff is responsible for maintaining quality and consistency in College publications, while projecting an accurate and favorable image of the institution.
<dt><br>
<dt>Those members of the college community who wish to produce      publications for an external audience by any means, including      the use of desk-top publishing, are required to seek review of      content and design from the College Relations Office.  The      staff is always ready to offer assistance in creating a design      for such publications.
 <dt><br>
<dt>Your cooperation in observing the various aspects of the Publications Policy will greatly enhance the efforts of the Office of College Relations as it seeks to present a consistent and positive image of the College.

	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A40a">a</A>)	Name of the College
 <dt><br>
	<dt>The name of the College shall be "State University of New York College at Potsdam", "SUNY Potsdam" is the short form.

		</dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A40b">b</A>)	College Logo and Stationery
 <dt><br>
			<dt>The College's logo and stationery are designed to project a unified and up-to-date image of the College.  The design standards for both the logo and stationery are to be strictly followed.  If in doubt as to the appropriate use of either, consult with the Office of College Relations.  Copies of the logo, both on paper and on computer disk, are available through the Office of College Relations.(the logo is also available in a variety of formats in temporary storage on the campus network)
 <dt><br>
<dt>Official College stationery may now be ordered directly through Duplicating.  Do not call the Office of College Relations or receiving and Stores to order stationery, unless you need a change in the name of your office or your phone number.  Please allow two weeks for delivery.

		</dl><!--2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A40c">c</A>)	College Seal
<dt><br>
			<Dt>The College seal is not to be used for publications.  The College seal is to be reserved for formal documents and occasions (i.e., Presidential proclamations, diplomas, etc.).  The College logo is the mark to be used when it is desirable to represent the College in a concise graphic manner.

		</dl><!--2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A40d">d</A>)	Printing Services
<dt><br>
			<dt>There are three primary printing options for reproducing publications at SUNY Potsdam.  Those options and their respective capabilities follow:
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	Duplicating
<dt><br>
				<dt>Duplicating<br>
				<dt>Sizes to 11" x 17" <br>
				<dt>Bond, offset, and card stock<br>
				<dt>Colored paper is available and NCR<br>
				<dt>Black ink only<br>
				<dt>Folding, collating, stitching, and plastic binding      
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	Central Print Shop (SUNY Canton)
<dt><br>
				<dt>Duplicating and offset printing<br>
				<dt>Over 200 copies<br>
				<dt>Sizes to 11 x 17"<br>
				<dt>Bond, offset, cover and card stock and fine papers available in a variety of colors<br>
<dt>Single and multi-color printing <br>
<dt><br>
				<dt>Printing halftones and screen tints<br>
<dt>Folding, collating, stitching, and plastic binding<br>
<dt>Colored ink
<dt><br>
			<Dt>iii)	Outside Vendors
<dt><br>
				<dt>For jobs which exceed the capacities of the above operations including:
<dt><br>
<dt>Printing on coated stocks<br>
<dt>Printing large areas of solid color<br>
<dt>Four-color process (color photos)<br>
<dt>Large quantities<br>
<dt>Large format
<dt.<br>
			<dt>In most instances, the nature, the budget, and the intended audience of the publication will determine how it is to be designed and printed.  The staff in the Office of College Relations will choose how best to get the job done.
<dt><br>
<dt>If it is a job which requires simple duplicating, the timeliness of delivery and the quantity required will affect the decision as to where the job is printed.  This decision is to be made by the Duplicating staff.
</dl><!-- 3 -->
</dl><!--2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A40e">e</A>) Publication Requests
<dt><br>
<Dt>To initiate an external publication to be produced by the Office of College Relations, you must file a Publication Request Form.  This form provides the basic information necessary to begin production planning.  It will also allow for prioritizing the publication in order to schedule the annual workload.
<dt><br>
<dt>Publication Request Forms are sent to all departments in April.  At this time, you are asked to project your publications needs for the following year (July 1 - June 30).
<dt><br>
<dt>If for some reason, the office is unable to handle your request, the staff will suggest alternative methods for having the publication produced.
<dt><br>
<dt>Of course, there are always unanticipated needs; the office will try to accommodate these needs on a time-available basis.  Publication Request Forms for these unscheduled publications are available throughout the year in the Office of College Relations.  You should file one as soon as you know your need.

		</dl><!--2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A40f">f</A>)	Funding For Publication
<dt><br>
			<dt>The Publications budget in the Office of College Relations provides for only the major recruitment and development publications of the College.  All other publications are funded through the originating departments.  Please be sure to include the amount you have budgeted for your publication and the account number to which it will be charged when you complete the Printing Publication Request Form.

		</dl><!--2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A40g">g</A>)	Recruiting Publications (Admissions)
<dt><br>
			<dt>All publications intended to be used for admissions recruiting must first be reviewed and approved by the Director of Admissions and the Director of College Relations.

		</dl><!--2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A40h">h</A>)	Production Services
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	Planning and Advising
<dt><br>
				<dt>The staff of the Office of College Relations is involved in planning printing on a daily basis.  Consulting with the office as soon as you know that you will be producing a publication will save you time, energy and money.
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	Time and Cost Estimates
<dt><br>
				<dt>The staff will evaluate your proposed publication, determine the printing option that best suits your needs, and provide time and cost estimates. 
<dt><br>
			<dt>iii)	Editing
<dt><br>
				<dt>The staff provides editorial support.  However, you are responsible for preparing original copy.  Guidelines for the preparation of copy are available in the Office of College Relations.  Following these guidelines will expedite the production of your publication.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iv)	Typesetting
<dt><br>
				<dt>Computerized typesetting for most publications is done in-house.  Copy submitted for publication should be on disk in Microsoft Word or Word Star with an attached hard copy.  
<dt><br>
			<dt>v)	Proofreading
<dt><br>
<dt>While due caution is exercised in typesetting, typographical errors do occur.  Ultimately, it is the client's responsibility to ensure that the typeset matter is free from errors.  You will be asked to proofread your copy and to sign off on corrections throughout the production process. 
<dt><br>
			<dt><br>vi)	Design
<dt><br>
				<dt>Do not try to design your publication in advance.  Experienced graphic designers will design a publication that will effectively communicate the intended message while maintaining the College's publication standards.
<dt><br>
			<dt>viii)	Expediting
<dt><br>
				<dt>If your publication is to be printed in Duplicating, it is your responsibility to see that the Duplicating Job Request is properly filled out and that the job is taken to Duplicating.  If the job is to be printed at the Central Print Shop (SUNY Canton), the designer assigned to the job will fill out the Duplicating Job Request and expedite production.  If the job is to be printed by an outside vendor, your designer will coordinate (through Purchasing) production of the publication.
</dl><!-- 3 -->
		</dl><!--2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt><A NAME="12A40i">i</A>)	State Printing Regulations
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	Bidding
<dt><br>
				<dt>All printing purchased from outside vendors is closely regulated by statute and monitored by the Office of General Services and the Office of the State Comptroller.  Most of the printing performed by outside vendors requires competitive bidding.  Printing orders in excess of $2,500 require sealed bids.  The bidding process can take from thirty to sixty days, depending on the estimated dollar amount of the order.
<dt><br>
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
