<TITLE>Chapter 12 64-65</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#ff00ff">

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=87  SRC="../FACBOOK.GIF"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>

<center>
<strong>XII.  CAMPUS POLICIES</strong><BR>
<BR>

</center>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<A NAME="12A"><b>A</a>.	CAMPUS POLICIES AND PROCEDURES</b>

<dt><br>
	<BLOCKQUOTE><dt><A NAME="12A64">64</A>.<i>	WORK ORDER REQUESTS</i>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt><A NAME="12A64a">a</A>)	Maintenance of Campus Physical Facilities
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	Scope
<dt><br>
				<dt>Maintenance of campus physical facilities is the responsibility of the Physical Plant Department.  Work done by the department may be classified as either routine or non-routine.
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
<dt>(a)	Routine Work
<dt><br>
	<dt>The primary function of the Physical Plant Department is the routine maintenance and operation of campus physical facilities.  This function is defined as upkeep, repair, replacement and preventative maintenance of buildings, systems, components and non-academic equipment as originally configured, installed and operated.  Routine maintenance and operation work is given priority.  This is necessary because facility malfunctions tend to affect the campus community as a whole, rather than one or a few individuals.  The cost of routine maintenance is the responsibility of the Physical Plant Department and is paid from the department's operating budget.
<dt><br>
<dt>(b)	Non-Routine Work
<dt><br>
<dt>Non-routine work is considered any job that is not maintenance and operation oriented, such as requests for partitions, shelves, space alterations, utility enlargements, academic equipment construction and/or repair.  The cost of non-routine work is not a part of the Physical Plant Department's operating budget.  The funding source will have to be identified and the project may require approval of the Building Administrator, Department Chairperson/Director, Dean, Provost and/or President.
</dl><!-- 4 -->
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	Procedures
<dt><br>
				<dt>A request to have work (routine or non-routine) performed is processed using a Work Request form.  This form is available from the Office of Physical Plant.
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
<dt>(a)	Three copies of the completed work request form (including Department Chairperson/Director and Building Administrator approval) is submitted to the Physical Plant Office.  One copy (pink) is retained for department files.
<dt><br>
<dt>(b)	Physical Plant personnel will review the work request to determine the feasibility of the request, as well as the capability of the Physical Plant Department to complete the project, and budget and personnel requirements.
<dt><br>
				<dt>(c)	For non-routine work, the Physical Plant Office will estimate the project cost, recommend a funding source(s) (e.g. department budget, campus OTPS pool, capital construction), and discuss with the requester before proceeding.  Where the funding source identified is the campus OTPS pool, it is the requester's responsibility to request the funds.  If capital construction funds are required, the Assistant Vice President for Facilities is responsible for submitting the request as required after approval by the President (or designee).
<dt><br>
<dt>(d)Authorized work requests will be assigned to the appropriate supervisor for action.  The requester will be notified that this has been done.  Unauthorized requests are returned to the requester with explanation.
<dt><br>
<dt>(e)A monthly status review of Work Requests will be completed by the Physical Plant Office.  Incomplete work orders will be discussed with appropriate supervisor and analyzed for resolution.
<dt><br>
				<dt>(f)	The requester may, at any time, ask for a status report pertaining to his/her work order by contacting the Physical Plant Office personnel.
<dt><br>
				<dt>It is to be noted that because of the large number of work orders submitted it may not always be possible to complete requests within time limits desired due to available personnel, funding requirements, the availability of materials and other commitments.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl><!-- 4 -->
</dl><!-- 3 -->
		<dt>
	<BLOCKQUOTE><dt><A NAME="12A64b">b</A>)	SUNY Potsdam Telecommunications Network
<dt><br>
			<dt>The SUNY Potsdam Telecommunications Network supports voice, video and data services.  Voice services are provided through a cable plant of twisted-pair wiring connecting each campus telephone set (digital and analog) to a campus AT&T switch.  Voice services include AUDIX voice mail and auto-attendant features.    
<dt><br>
<dt>Video (TV) services are provided via coaxial cable from a campus-managed SMATV distribution system.  Programming consists of 22 channels of television and a campus information channel and is delivered to every student room and many classrooms.   
<dt><br>
<dt>Data services are provided by standard Ethernet networking via fiber and thinwire cable to nearly every office, classroom, computer center and laboratory on campus.  Data communication protocols currently supported include AppleTalk, DECnet, LAT, Novell IPX, TCP/IP.  Remote access to the data network supporting ARA, SLIP, PPP and standard RS232 is provided via a bank of 1200/2400/9600/14000 modems.
<dt><br>
<dt>Services relating to the SUNY Potsdam Telecommunications Network (repair, maintenance or installation) must be requested from the Distributed Computing/TeleMedia department on a Network Add/Change/Repair form.  Forms are available from the telephone office of Distributed Computing/TeleMedia in Kellas Hall (x3000).  The form must not only include a description of the work to be performed, but also an account for billing if parts and materials must be purchased.  If assistance from the Physical Plant is needed, that office will be notified using the standard Physical Plant work-request form.  Usually, requests will be handled on a first-come, first-served basis.  Exceptions will be made for emergency requests if they are within reason.

		<dt><br>
	<dt><A NAME="12A64c">c</A>)	Audio-Visual/Electronic Repairs
<dt><br>
			<dt>All repairs of departmentally-managed audio-visual or elec- tronic equipment are to be requested by memorandum to the Director of Distributed Computing/TeleMedia.  If the repairs require an extraordinary expensive part or component, the department may be asked to find funding to share in the cost.  When necessary, and if available, temporary replacement will be supplied.</BLOCKQUOTE>


</dl><!-- 2 -->
</dl><!-- 1 -->
</dl><!-- 0 -->

<I><BLOCKQUOTE>65.<!-- Anchor Point Tag --><A NAME="65">SUNY POTSDAM PERSONAL TELEPHONE CALL PAYMENT POLICY</I></A>


	<BLOCKQUOTE>a)	All faculty and staff requesting personal authorization codes will do so by completing a 			Telephone/Network Services request form.
<BR>
<BR>

		b)	This form requires the signature of the employee's department head or their designee 				(telephone coordinator).
<BR>
<BR>

		c)	Forward all requests to the Telecommunications System Administrator.
<BR>
<BR>

		d)	The Telephone Office will issue a personal authorization code to the faculty and/or 				staff member in writing.  Allow five business days for processing.
<BR>
<BR>

		e)	The letter received by the user will inform the user that they have sole responsibility for 			all calls placed with their personal authorization code.  If by mistake the user places 				business calls using their personal authorization code, they must return a copy of their 				bill with the calls they are requesting credit for circled.  The credit will show on the 				customer's next bill.
<BR>
<BR>

		f)	All parties are to understand that personal authorization codes are at the discretion of 			their supervisor.  A supervisor has the right to revoke their code at any time for misuse.
<BR>
<BR>

		g)	Any user whose authorization code is deactivated for nonpayment will have to pay a 				five dollar reactivation fee.  Past due balances must be paid in full prior to a user 				requesting that their code be reactivated.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>



	<BLOCKQUOTE>PAYMENT POLICY</BLOCKQUOTE>



	<BLOCKQUOTE>1)	All bills are due thirty days from the date of the invoice.
<BR>
<BR>

	2)	Anyone not making payment before receiving their sixty day notification will have their account 		closed and their supervisor notified.
<BR>
<BR>

	PAYMENT METHODS AND OPTIONS ARE AS FOLLOWS:
<BR>
<BR>

	1)	Payments are due thirty days from the receipt of the invoice.
<BR>
<BR>

	2)	All personal account holders with a monthly bill of five dollars or less will now have the 			following options:
</BLOCKQUOTE>


		<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>a)	If user's wish to hold their bill until they reach a five dollar minimum, this will now be 			acceptable.  User's will continue to receive monthly invoices.  Payment is due thirty days 			after your account reaches the five dollar minimum.  You will not receive statements.
<BR>
<BR>
		b)	Personal account users will now have the option to pay in advance.  The Telephone 				Office will credit the user's account for the prepaid amount.  Users will continue to 				receive monthly invoices that will show their current telephone charges as well as the 			amount of credit remaining on their account.</BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
	<BLOCKQUOTE>Anyone with questions and/or suggestions regarding this policy may contact the telephone office at x3000.</BLOCKQUOTE>
</dl>
</dl>
</dl>
<BR>
<BR>


