<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>Chapter 13 AFFIRMATIVE ACTION</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#ff00ff">

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=87  SRC="../FACBOOK.GIF"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<center>
<strong>XIII.  AFFIRMATIVE ACTION</strong></center>
<dt><br><BR>

<dd><dl>
<A NAME="13A">A</A>.	<b>EQUAL OPPORTUNITY AND AFFIRMATIVE ACTION POLICY OF THE STATE UNIVERSITY OF NEW YORK (SUNY)</b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>The State University of New York Board of Trustees adopted an Equal Opportunity policy in 1971 calling for the development of a University-wide Affirmative Action Program to "detail actions designed to realize our University's commitment to equal employment; analyze employment patterns within the University; set forth plans to rectify any deficiencies; identify and remove impediments to equal opportunity;...provide for internal and external dissemination of University policy; pursue the commitment to equal opportunity throughout the institution; and provide for the review, assessment, evaluation, and improvement of University action in carrying out...Affirmative Action Programs.  The SUNY Office for Affirmative Action, a part of the Chancellor's Office has responsibility for implementation of this policy.  In addition to the matters listed above, the Office also has responsibility for administering the SUNY Discrimination Grievance Procedure, programs for the handicapped, and programs to encourage minority business development.
    <dt><br> 
	<dt>Today, every SUNY campus has a designated Affirmative Action Officer, and Affirmative Action Committee, which is advisory to the campus President, and a written Affirmative Action Plan and Program.  There is also a system-wide SUNY Task Force on Affirmative Action, which is advisory to the Chancellor.
<dt><br>
	<dt>Employees of the State University of New York are assured equal opportunity without regard to race, sex, age, national origin, religion, marital status, pregnancy, disability, ex-offender status, or sexual orientation.  In addition Vietnam Era Veterans and disabled veterans are ensured equal opportunity under the Vietnam Era Veterans Readjustment Act of 1974.
<dt><br>
	<dt>Any employee of the State University of New York who believes that he or she has been discriminated against in any personnel decision or condition of employment may file a complaint with his or her campus Affirmative Action Officer using the University's Internal Discrimination Grievance Procedures.  A copy of the procedures is available from the campus Office for Affirmative Action.  Externally, complaints may be filed with the local office of the Equal Employment for Human Rights.  Complaints of discrimination on the basis of sexual orientation may be filed with the Governor's Office for Employee Relations in Albany.  The campus Affirmative Action Officer will provide addresses, phone numbers, and filing procedures to any employee requesting such information.

<dt><br>
<A NAME="13B">B</A>.	<b>EQUAL OPPORTUNITY AND AFFIRMATIVE ACTION POLICY OF THE STATE UNIVERSITY OF NEW YORK, AT POTSDAM</b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>SUNY POTSDAM is committed to the principles of non- discrimination and equality of opportunity in all of its personnel procedures and practices.  The College recruits, selects, hires,  trains and promotes staff and provides benefits without regard to race, color, religion, national origin, sex, age or handicap except where sex, age or handicap are bona fide occupational qualifications.
<dt><br>
	<dt>It is the policy of the SUNY Potsdam to provide equal opportunity in employment and upward mobility for all qualified persons, to prohibit discrimination in employment because of age, color, handicap, marital status, national origin, race, religion, sex, sexual preference, and Vietnam Era Veteran status.
<dt><br>
	<dt>This policy of equal employment opportunity:
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
	<dt>1.	Applies to all persons without regard to race, creed, color, national origin, age or sex, except where sex is a bona fide occupational qualification.
<dt><br>
	<dt>2.	Applies equally to all job classifications and titles at SUNY Potsdam and to all types of appointment, whether full-time or part-time.
<dt><br>
	<dt>3.	Governs all college employment policies, practices and actions including but not necessarily limited to recruitment, employment, rate of pay or other compensation, advancement, upgrading, promotion, demotion, renewal, non-renewal, termination, transfer, layoff, leave, training and employee benefits of whatever nature.
<dt><br>
	<dt>4.	Applies to all college employees wherever physically located.
<dt><br>
	<dt>5.	Expects each contractor, supplier, union, public agency or other cooperative agent to support this policy by complying with all applicable State and Federal equal employment opportunity laws and regulations.
<dt><br>
	<dt>In addition to providing equal employment opportunities for all qualified persons, the College has a special commitment to the principle of Affirmative Action, which entails a positive, ongoing effort to seek qualified members of two under-represented groups:  women and minorities.  It is the goal of this College to achieve equitable representation of women and minorities in all academic, administrative, and service units of the College.
</dl><!-- 1 -->
<dt><br>
<A NAME="13C">C</A>.	<b>COMMITMENT TO QUALITY</b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>The standing of SUNY Potsdam as a leading liberal arts college in the State of New York and in the nation requires that it recruit staff of the highest possible caliber.  Its faculty and staff should be highly qualified for their positions and they should show promise of achievement in the future.  They should exhibit breadth as well as depth of talent and they should be drawn from a diversity of backgrounds.
<dt><br>
	<dt>The search for new talent should, under normal circumstances, be national in scope.  It should include advertising in leading professional journals, contact with major centers of excellence and a systematic attempt to bring to the campus the most talented and promising candidates.  The College should avoid settling for less than the best.

<dt><br>
<A NAME="13D">D</A>.	<b>RECRUITMENT PROCEDURES</b>
<dt><br>
	<dt>From the Office of the President of the College:
<dt><br>
	<dt>"The search for candidates to fill faculty and staff positions is perhaps the most important activity in which we as a College engage.  Through such searches, we announce not only our philosophy of hiring but also, in effect, the quality and nature of our institution.  On a more subtle level, we also signal the kind of curricula we offer - and whether or not we are current in this area.  Most importantly, searches constitute the principal means for creating the SUNY Potsdam of tomorrow, since the faculty and staff members hired as a result of the search process today will be the core of the institution in years to come.  We must settle for nothing less than the very best in candidates and must act assertively to locate and attract them to our campus, even if doing so requires more than traditional methods of advertising positions and examining applications.
<dt><br>
	<dt>The search process, while primarily the means for acquiring new and needed colleagues, also comes to represent the College in the forum of public and social concern.  For this reason, the search procedure carries with it great social responsibility.  Over the past several decades, we as a people have recognized the need to represent more accurately in the workplace the diversity of cultures and the differences based on gender that are expressed in our society at large.  In response to this imperative, policies have evolved to rectify the imbalances that resulted, seemingly automatically though often perhaps unconsciously, in previous hiring practices in all sectors.  As a public institution, we particularly embrace these policies as our own.
<dt><br>
	<dt>In so doing, we subscribe to the egalitarian principles that lie at the heart of our society.  We must guarantee to all members of society equal access to real opportunities for development and growth.  But our dedication to such a philosophy benefits those of us who offer such opportunities, as well as those to whom they are offered.  It is by now a truism that faculty members who are women or members of minorities provide role models to those of our students who share either their gender or their ethnic origins.  Less acknowledged but equally important is the kind of model these members represent to traditional, non-minority students as well, who can learn new and different approaches to academic subjects than those traditional faculty members might be able to offer.  The presence of women and minority faculty members also provides all of our students with a real sense of the multicultural society they are about to enter as adults, and the options in thought and manner that a pluralistic society encourages, and on which it depends.
<dt><br>
	<dt>Likewise, the entire faculty gains from the variety in perspective and opinion that often follows from differences in gender, race, or ethnicity among its members.  The scholarly activity stimulated by these differences also fosters growth in the general body of academic knowledge, often charting new areas of scholarship and research, and teaching us new ways to know.  Thus the pursuit of affirmative action  policies benefits us all." 
<dt><br>
	<dt>A summary of the College's recruitment procedures follows.  Complete details are found in the manual - SEARCH COMMITTEE PROCEDURES available from the Offices of Human Resources or Affirmative Action.

	<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 1 -->
<dt><A NAME="13D1">1.</A>	<i>INITIATING THE SEARCH</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>In identifying vacant positions that will be advertised as tenure-track, the dean/director will meet with department chairs to prioritize and define the proposed positions.  Positions that have been filled after having been advertised as temporary must be readvertised if the positions are converted to permanent or tenure-track.  It should not be assumed that all vacancies from retirements, resignations, terminations will be filled and that positions that have previously been "temporary" will be converted to tenure-track.

		<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
<dt><A NAME="13D1a">a</A>)	Recruitment Request
<dt><br>
			<dt>To formally initiate the search, approval must be obtained by securing the signature and approval of the Dean and others indicated on the recruitment request form.  All Recruitment Requests will be reviewed by Priorities Council to determine whether the search can go forward.  Upon receipt of the signed form, Human Resources is authorized to begin the search.

		<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13D1b">b</A>)	Advertising
<dt><br>
			<dt>Departments will prepare the ad as they recommend it be sent.  Rank, title, salary range, job description and application procedures will be determined by the Provost.  This information is to be forwarded to Human Resources via e-mail with a hard copy of the ad or placed in a shared folder/drop box.  General information pertaining to SUNY Potsdam will be prepared by Human Resources.  Advertising should be broad and open to attract the largest number of applicants.  The position describes the essential qualifications and duties.  The final ad copy will be prepared as a result of consultation with the department, Dean, Provost, and Vice President.  Before going to print, each advertisement must be reviewed and approved by the department chair (or dean after conversation with the department chair).

			<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
<dt><A NAME="13D1bi">i</A>)	Faculty Searches
<dt><br>
				<dt>In order to advertise a position as tenure-track, the ad must normally be placed by November 1.  Human Resources will place one master ad in the Chronicle of Higher Education, Black Issues in Higher Education, and the Hispanic Outlook early in the fall semester after consultation and approval by the Provost.  To the extent possible, all anticipated openings should be listed in this combined job announcement.

			<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13D1bii">ii</A>)	Professional and Management Searches
<dt><br>
				<dt>The campus has established a policy in which these positions are advertised either internally first or simultaneously internally/externally.  This process will allow internal candidates to be considered prior to extending the position to external candidates.  
<dt><br>
			<dt>In addition, departments should for all positions:<br>
			<dt>--	identify and provide the advertising copy for other publications, such as disciplinary publications, specialized journals, publications geared to women or minorities, etc.  As with the Chronicle ad, these ads must also be reviewed, and approved by the Deans.<br>
			<dt>--	Contact historically black institutions and ask for recommendations<br>
			<dt>--	Contact professional organizations to determine if there are minority or women's caucuses, committees, or employment registers<br>
			<dt>--	Make personal contacts with colleagues who might be interested in a move or might nominate others<br>
			<dt>--	Make telephone calls to colleagues and schools to seek out underrepresented applicants<br>
			<dt>--	Use source lists of minority candidates available through the dean's offices<br>
			<Dt>--	Utilize employment services at conventions
</dl><!-- 3 -->
		<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13D1c">c</A>)	Composition of the Search Committee
<dt><br>
			<dt>The chair of the search committee may or may not be the department chair or director.  In the case of a search for a department chair, at least one member of the search committee shall come from outside the affected department.  The committee should have a minimum of three members, and may be as large as deemed appropriate.  In the spirit of a student-centered campus, serious consideration should be given to having one or more students serve as committee members.  Even if students do not serve on the search committee, student involvement should be sought in the search process.
<dt><br>
			<dt>The search committee should reflect the interests and characteristics of various constituencies, taking into consideration ethnicity, gender, age, different areas of specialization within the department.  Search committees should be balanced.  If there is not sufficient diversity within a hiring department, serious consideration should be given to including a member from outside the department.  In general, if search committees themselves are diverse, we may be more successful in attracting multicultural candidates.
<dt><br>
			<dt>Other considerations:<br>
			<dt>--	Are the interests of non-tenured faculty and staff included?<br>
			<dt>--	Is someone with prior search committee experience on the committee?<br>
			<dt>--	Are the search committee nominees aware of the time commitment their participation will involve?<br>
			<dt>--	Should any members from outside the department be involved in the search?  (This may be appropriate in the absence of women and/or minorities in the department).<br>
			<dt>--	Is there anyone with access to special networks of talent that the search committee might tap for nominees?<br>
<dt><br>
			<dt>The final composition of a faculty search committee and selection of the chair will be determined in consultation with the appropriate dean/director who may add committee members from outside the hiring department.
<dt><br>
			<dt>If the position to be searched for is Vice President or President, the Faculty Assembly By-Laws require a process different from the one identified above.

		<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13D1d">d</A>)	Search Committee Charge
<dt><br>
			<dt>The dean/director/provost/vice president/president should specify the role of the committee.  It may be to identify and recommend for appointment qualified applicants not to make job offers or engage in discussions with candidates on term and conditions of employment.
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13D2">2</A>.	<i>FOLLOW-UP ON APPLICATIONS</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>A letter of acknowledgement and affirmative action card should be sent immediately upon receipt of an application.  Applicants should be informed as to the timetable of decision-making.  As vitae are received, they are to be available for review by the dean/director and appropriate vice president/provost.  Vitae of women and applicants from protected classes may be requested for special review.
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt>a)	Develop Written Criteria for Screening
<dt><br>
			<dt>Prior to the receipt of applications, the committee should decide upon the criteria to be used for preliminary and final screening stages.  The preliminary screening should be limited to information contained in the advertisement.  For example, if the ad specified a Ph.D., all applicants without a doctorate should be rejected.  If no minimum amount of experience was stated in the ad, candidates should not be eliminated on the basis of a lack of experience at this early stage.
<dt><br>
			<dt>The search committee identifies those applicants who do not meet the qualifications for the position and so informs them.  Remaining applicants may be asked to send additional material by a specific date.
<dt><br>
		<dt>b)	The following MUST take place PRIOR to inviting candidates to campus:
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	It is a good idea to send candidates information about SUNY Potsdam.  This could include the catalog, recent class schedule, the brochure SUNY Potsdam: A Profile, and any departmental documents that would help the candidate understand the nature of the vacant position and the college.  Information on the town of Potsdam may also be sent to the candidate and is available in Human Resources.
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	Telephone referencing:  The search committee should discuss in advance the questions to be asked.  These questions should be in writing to ensure that consistent questions are asked about each candidate.  Contact only persons who have been listed as references by the candidate.  With the candidate's permission you can contact references other than those listed by the candidate.  Arrangements may be made for a conference call through the Office of Human Resources.  Conference calls also can be set up via tele-media box.  Long-distance calls will be charged to the Office of Human Resources.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iii)	Telephone interview of finalists:  Before a campus interview is scheduled, a telephone interview of finalists may be conducted.  A written interview protocol should be prepared by the committee for use during the interviews and retained in the committee's files as part of the search record.  Each candidate should be asked the same questions for purposes of comparison and fairness.  Information is also provided  on resources available in Human Resources to improve the interviewing skills of committee members.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iv)	Consultation with the Dean/Director:  The Dean/Director should be informed as to the characteristics of the applicant pool and of the qualifications of the finalists who may be invited to campus.  The Dean/Director/Vice President/Provost/President may choose to examine the pool of candidates.  The number of candidates to invite for campus interviews will be decided in consultation with the Dean/Director (but normally will be limited to two).  The Dean/Director will consult with the appropriate Provost/ Vice President before giving verbal approval to invite candidates to campus.
<dt><br>
			<dt>v)	Filing of the "Request to Invite Candidate to Campus" Form (one for each candidate who will be invited to visit the campus).  Candidates may not be invited until the request has been approved by the Dean/Director and Provost/Vice President (or designee).  Travel arrangements will be made by a local travel agent in consultation with the candidate and the department chair.  IMPORTANT:  This form must be filed BEFORE a candidate can be brought to campus!
</dl><!-- 3 -->
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13D3">3</A>.	<i>THE ON-CAMPUS INTERVIEW</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>In order to hire from the strongest possible pool, it is important to invite candidates to campus as soon as possible.  For faculty searches, this may mean that candidates can be brought to campus during the first semester.
<dt><br>
		<dt>The Office of Human Resources' memorandum on "Recruitment Guidelines," deals with how to finance a search, what expenses can be paid, etc.  Recruitment costs have risen significantly in recent years and departments are expected to follow guidelines to help reduce recruitment-related expenses.
<dt><br>
		<dt>In addition to appropriate department personnel and committees, all candidates invited to campus must be scheduled to meet with:<br>
		<dt>a.	the appropriate dean/director<br>
		<dt>b.	a member of the Office of Human Resources<br>
		<dt>c.	students and others as determined by the department responsible for the position recruitment
<dt><br>
		<dt>If the candidate is a person of color, search chairs should contact the Assistant Vice President for Multicultural Affairs, who is eager to assist in the hiring process.  Her involvement can make candidates more aware of the support groups, services, and opportunities available, and improve the College's chances of hiring these candidates.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Please check with the Dean/Director's offices before inviting a candidate for specific days.  A copy of the candidate's vita and interview schedule must be made available to each interviewer prior to the interview.  Those persons conducting interviews should also be given an evaluation form.
<dt><br>
		<dt>An interview schedule should also be given to the candidate in advance of that person's arrival on campus.  The schedule often makes a lasting impression on the candidate.  Some suggested guidelines (which may appear all-too-obvious to most search committee chairs): schedules should be typed; schedules should be checked for accuracy in spelling, individuals' titles, etc.; proof schedules with an eye to how an outsider will view the professionalism of the hiring department (e.g. do not say "lunch with whoever (sic) in the Gallery"), allow time for a break during the interview.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Be sure to have written questions prepared ahead of time.  The department should have prepared a core set of questions to be asked of all candidates.  Care should be taken to avoid asking inappropriate questions.
<dt><br>
		<dt>As part of the interview process, all candidates interviewed for faculty positions on campus are expected to be placed in a 'teaching situation' involving faculty and students and appropriate to the discipline.  Generally, candidates should teach a scheduled class (except where not appropriate for some library positions).  This includes internal candidates, who should be asked to teach a class not in a course they are currently teaching.  If this is not possible, consider scheduling a "teaching simulation".  You can create a "class" of faculty and staff.  Search committee and faculty members should attend, their schedules permitting.  Interviews may give few clues as to teaching effectiveness, but a good (or bad!) teacher frequently can be identified in a teaching simulation.
<dt><br>
		<dt>Keep records as your search proceeds.  It is a good idea to keep minutes of search committee meetings.  Above all, retain candidate evaluation forms and all written comments.  This is particularly important when an internal candidate is a finalist for a tenure-track position.  All candidates must be afforded as equal as possible interview opportunities.

	<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13D4">4</A>.	<I>CONCLUDING THE SEARCH</I>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt>a)	Request to Hire Form:  Once the decision has been made as to whom to hire, a Request to Hire form must be completed including the information regarding the gender/racial/protected class composition of the applicant pool.  In some cases, the President or designee may request further information about the search process from the search committee before approving this form.  All the appropriate signatures must appear before the President or designee approves the final hiring.
 <dt><br>
		<dt>b)	Affirmative Action Cards:  The affirmative action cards are used to gather data for use in preparing the College's affirmative action plan.  To identify more clearly which affirmative action card goes with what vacancy, labels identifying the search will be prepared by Human Resources affixed to the affirmative action cards prior to their mailing to the search committee chair.  The cards will be mailed from the candidates directly to Human Resources.  Human Resources will forward the cards to the search committee chair upon receipt of the Request to Invite Candidates to Campus form.  The search committee chair will complete the affirmative action reporting on the back of the Request to Hire form.
<dt><br>
		<dt>c)	Search Records:  Each search committee chair should keep records and notes of evaluations of each candidate's credentials, reference checks, rating forms and interview results.  Upon the culmination of the search, all records and files should be completed and maintained for three years after the completion of the fiscal year in which the search was conducted.  These records will be used by the College in the event of a review by an outside agency (affirmative action, Department of Labor, etc.).  Such records must be retained in either the department office or returned to Human Resources.
<dt><br>
		<dt>d)	Every unsuccessful candidate who participated in an on-campus visit should be personally conducted by telephone, not just by letter.  If search committee chair does not do so, deans/directors should be informed so that they may do it.
<dt><br>
		<dt>e)	Hiring:  Search committee chairs should not discuss salaries with candidates or make offers of employment.  Assuming the department recommendation is accepted, the Dean/Director/Vice President/Provost/President will explore with the candidate his/her continuing interest in the position and salary expectations.  The Vice President/Provost or designee shall make the final salary offer.
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13D5">5</A>.	<i>REIMBURSEMENT OF CANDIDATE EXPENSES</i>

		<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
<dt><A NAME="13D5a">a</A>)	Payment of Travel Expenses
<dt><br>
			<dt>Within available funds and within local and State of New York guidelines, candidates invited to campus for a position interview requiring travel in excess of 100 miles (one-way) may be reimbursed in full for expenses (transportation, meals, lodging, etc.).
<dt><br>
			<dt>Exceptions to these policies, where appropriate, must have prior approval of the President of the College.
<dt><br>
			<dt>Search Committees are requested to exercise careful management of recruitment monies for departments and divisions under their supervision.  This should include consultation with Chairperson/Directors and search committees as to specific recruitment costs and available resources.  Heads of search committees should meet with the Director of Human Resources at the start of every search to verify expected recruitment costs.  Chairpersons/Directors and heads of search committees are expected to exercise all possible economies, without damaging the effectiveness of their searches.

		<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="135b">b</A>)	Payment of Moving Expenses
<dt><br>
			<dt>The College, in general, does not reimburse new appointees for moving expenses.
</dl><!-- 2 -->
</dl><!-- 1 -->
</dl><!-- 0 -->
<BR>
<BR>
