</DOCHDR>
<HTML> 
<HEAD><TITLE>S13 E 4-6</TITLE></HEAD> 
<BODY BGCOLOR="#FFFFFF" LINK="#0000FF" VLINK="#FF1FFF">

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=87  SRC="../FACBOOK.GIF"></CENTER>
<BR>
<BR>
<center><strong>XIII.  AFFIRMATIVE ACTION</strong></center>
<BR>

<BR>
<dt><A NAME="13E4">4</A>.	<i>GRIEVANCE PROCEDURES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>Any student or employee who feels she or he may have been sexually harassed by another employee is strongly encouraged to report any episode(s) to the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action.
<dt><br>
		<dt>There are three established procedures for processing a sexual harassment complaint:<br>
		<dt>--	Informal Grievance Procedures;<br>
		<dt>--	Formal Procedures;<br>
		<dt>--	External Administrative or Judicial Proceedings (bypassing SUNY Potsdam's internal procedures).
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 2 -->
		<dt>a)	Informal Grievance Procedure
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	The primary objective of all informal procedures is to discover and identify whether sexual harassment has in fact occurred.  To that end, a student or employee who feels she or he has been harassed by an employee is encouraged to consult with the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action.  Careful consideration of the definition of sexual harassment and a detailed review of the student's or employee's experience will take place.  Discussions at this informal level are treated as confidential.  No formal records are maintained, and the student or employee will be assured as much anonymity as possible.
<dt><br>
			<dt>ii)	A second goal is to explore with the student or employee the various alternatives available to her or him in response to the situation.  The ultimate goal is to support and assist the student or employee in implementing the approach chosen in order to reach a satisfactory resolution.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iii)	Both parties -- the complainant and the respondent (alleged harasser) -- have the right to appear with an advisor during any stage of the proceedings.  Advisors may accompany the parties for support and consultation but may not actively participate, i.e., speak in the proceedings.
<dt><br>
			<dt>iv)	Recommended actions include, but are not limited to:  a) a direct conversation between the student or employee and the alleged harasser, b) a letter written by the student or employee to the alleged harasser, and c) a conversation between the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action and the alleged harasser on behalf of the student or employee.
<dt><br>
			<dt>v)	Time frame
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
				<dt>(a)	Employees must file a grievance within 45 calendar days following an alleged case of sexual harassment.
<dt><br>
				<dt>(b)	Students must file a grievance within 45 calendar days following an alleged case of sexual harassment; or, if accused is an instructor, 45 calendar days after a final grade is received if that date is later.
<dt><br>
				<dt>(c)	If resolution satisfactory to both parties is reached within 14 calendar days, the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action shall close the case and send a written notice to complainant and respondent.
<dt><br>
				<dt>(d)	If satisfactory resolution is not possible within 14 calendar days, the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action shall so notify grievant advising her/him of the right to proceed to next step internally or with appropriate agencies.
</dl><!-- 4 -->
</dl><!-- 3 -->
<dt><br>
		<dt>b)	Formal Grievance Procedure
<dt><br>
			<dt>The SUNY Grievance Procedure for Reviewing Allegations of Illegal Discrimination will be employed in cases of sexual harassment.  This procedure, which may be used by a SUNY student or an employee, provides an additional mechanism through which the University may identify and initiate procedures to eliminate incidents of illegal discrimination.
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 3 -->
			<dt>i)	Written Statement
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
				<dt>(a)	A formal complaint of sexual harassment must include a written statement signed by the complainant specifying the incident(s) of sexual harassment.  The statement may be prepared by the complainant as a record of the complaint with assistance from the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action.  
<dt><br>
				<dt>(b)	Grievances must be filed with the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action.  The College will prevent retaliation against the complainant for filing a complaint.
</dl><!-- 4 --><BR>

			<dt>ii)	Time frame for Filing a Formal Grievance
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
				<dt>(a)	Employees must file a grievance within 45 calendar days following an alleged case of sexual harassment.
<dt><br>
				<dt>(b)	Students must file a grievance within 45 calendar days following an alleged case of sexual harassment; or, if accused is an instructor, 45 calendar days after a final grade is received if that date is later.
<dt><br>
				<dt>(c)	Grievant must notify the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action within 10 calendar days from the date of notification by the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action that the issue cannot be resolved informally.
</dl><!-- 4 -->
<dt><br>
			<dt>iii)	Procedural Options
<dt><br>
				<dt>The grievant's statement, together with a statement from the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action, indicating that informal resolution was not possible, will be forwarded to the Chair of the Affirmative Action Committee within 5 days.  Within 7 calendar days of receipt, the Grievance Chair shall notify the grievant and President that a review of the matter will take place by an ad hoc tripartite committee.
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 4 -->
				<dt>(a)	Ad Hoc Tripartite Committee
<dt><br>
<dd><dl><!-- 5 -->
					<dt>(1)	The ad hoc tripartite committee shall consist of one member chosen by the President, one member chosen by the grievant and a third, who shall chair the Committee, chosen by the two designees.  If the respondent is other than the President, that respondent shall be consulted and the President or designee and the respondent together shall select a panel member.  Selection must be completed and written notification of designees submitted to the appropriate Grievance Chairperson within seven calendar days.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(2)	The tripartite committee shall review the matter, as appropriate and shall have the right to all relevant information and to interview witnesses, including the right to bring together complainant and respondent, if desirable.  Both complainant and respondent shall be permitted rebuttal to the written record compiled by the committee.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(3)	Within 21 calendar days from the formation of the committee, the chairperson of the tripartite committee shall submit an opinion to the campus president as to whether or not discrimination has occurred.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(4)	If a tripartite committee cannot be selected within 7 days, either because the grievant cannot agree on a third member, the grievance chairperson (and, in the latter case, grievant) shall be so notified within the period.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(5)	The grievant may, in such cases, request an outside hearing officer review the charge.  Such request must be made in writing by the grievant to the grievant chairperson within five days from notification that a campus tripartite committee cannot be formed.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(6)	The request for an outside hearing officer shall be made in writing by the grievant to the appropriate grievance chairperson.  The chairperson shall submit a written statement within 5 days to the Executive Assistant to the Chancellor for Affirmative Action requesting that an outside hearing officer be appointed.  The written request shall include a copy of the original grievance statement and the reason an outside hearing officer is being requested.  An affirmative action officer from another SUNY campus shall be assigned as hearing officer.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(7)	The Executive Assistant to the Chancellor for Affirmative Action shall designate a hearing officer within 7 calendar days of receipt of the written request.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(8)	The hearing officer shall conduct a review and shall submit an opinion to the President within 21 calendar days from the date of appointment.  The hearing officer shall have the right to all relevant information and to interview witnesses, including the right to bring together complainant and respondent, if desirable.
<dt><br>
					<dt>(9)	The President or designee shall communicate the opinion of the  tripartite committee or of the hearing officer verbatim and in writing to the grievant and to the Assistant to the President for Affirmative Action within 7 calendar days together with a statement indicating his/her acceptance or rejection of the committee's recommendation.  The President will indicate his/her decision either to dismiss the charge for lack of evidence that unlawful discrimination has occurred or to discuss appropriate redress with the grievant if unlawful discrimination has been found.
</dl><!-- 5 -->
<dt><br>
				<dt>(b)	Off-campus Resolution of Grievances:  (External Administrative or Judicial Proceedings).
<dt><br>
					<dt>If the grievant is dissatisfied with the President's response, the grievant may file a formal complaint with:  a) New York State division of Human Rights, b) the Equal Employment Opportunity Commission, c) the Office of Federal Contract Compliance of the Department of Labor.     
<dt><br>
				<dt>(c)	Student Judicial Process: (See student conduct code)
</dl><!-- 4 -->
</dl><!-- 3 -->
</dl><!-- 2 -->
	<dt>
<dt><A NAME="13E5">5</A>.	<i>RECOMMENDED CORRECTIVE ACTION</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>The purpose of any action to resolve a complaint will be to correct or to remedy the injury, if any, to the complainant and to prevent further harassment.  Recommended action may include written or verbal reprimand of the harasser; suspension, dismissal, or transfer of the harasser; a change of grade or other academic record for a student who has been the victim of harassment; a change in personnel action (such as a promotion) for an employee who has been victimized; or other appropriate action with the understanding that the imposition of sanctions against an employee can occur only after completion of contractual disciplinary procedures.

	<dt><br>
<dt><A NAME="13E6">6</A>.	<i>FALSE CHARGES</i>
<dt><br>
		<dt>If it has been determined that a complaint was made by a student with the knowledge that the facts were false, the President or designee shall so notify the Vice President for Enrollment and Student Services.  In the case of a false complaint made knowingly by an employee, this finding shall be stated in the recommendation to the President for possible disciplinary action.           
</dl><!-- 1 --><BR>
<BR>
