<DT><!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DT><DT><HTML>
<DT><DT><HEAD>
<DT><DT><TITLE>lespone</TITLE>
<DT><DT></HEAD>
<DD>     <DT><!-- Body Tag --><BODY BACKGROUND="back2.gif">
<DD>     <DT></BODY>
<DD>     <DT><BR>
<DD>     <DT><BR>
<DD>     <DT>
<DD>     <DD>     <H3><EM><CENTER><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#199161"><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5>Prelesson :History of the Oswegatchie River</FONT></FONT></CENTER></EM></H3>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <B><I><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#199161">Pedagogy:</FONT></I></B>  This lesson is directed towards being an introduction to the Oswegatchie River Project.  The MST students, during the summer of 1996, spent two weeks designing a framework of short-term (four months long) goals for the Gouverneur Jr. High students.   Science concepts were selected and modified to be deemed appropriate.  Also, the method(s) of teaching have been determined to allow for a solid base in understanding and learning, and to maintain this base throughout the semester.  Because as many as four of us may be teaching simultaneously, we are serving to model the importance of cooperative learning, both academically and socially.<BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <STRONG><EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#199161">Phase 1</FONT></B>:</EM></STRONG>
<DD>     <DD>       As teachers, we would like the students to begin this project with 15-20 minutes of talking about ourselves and getting to know each student.  After this, we would like to establish a set of rules and consequences, which the students will be responsible for, and if they are unrealistic, the teacher will modify them ( this may take 10-15 minutes).  An introduction to the content area will begin with the students asking themselves, "What role does this river play in my life?".   They will then write their answer in a required journal (5 minutes allotted for this activity).  The ultimate goal of this project is to perform multiple experiments and develop "higher" knowledge which provides the students with the experience and ability to change their preconceptions concerning the significance of the river to them.  To end the class, a brief discussion will entail a brainstorming session concerning  certain aspects which the students believe is important in a town's location and the components which allow a town to function, adding details related to their town, Gouverneur.     <BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <STRONG><EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#199161">Phase 2:</FONT></B></EM></STRONG>
<DD>     <DD>      The students will continue the lesson, in groups of two,  looking at maps of the Oswegatchie River.  They will be taken to the library and given approximately 30 minutes to study the map.  In doing this, the students should be looking for a recognizable pattern, which would help to explain why Gouverneur is located exactly where it is on the river.  The teacher will know this has been accomplished by walking around and listening to the students talk together.  To allow the teacher to view the actual coherency of the students, they will be given another 15 minutes to complete a concept map, linking each aspect of the Oswegatchie River to another.  The concept maps will be put in their journals and handed in for overnight evaluation.  This provides the students with greater organization and prepares them for the Experiment, Making My City (<CITE>Outlook: The Earth </CITE> by McCalley. p.73).  At the end of the period, the students will be given a homework assignment.  The assignment will require the student to conduct an interview with an elderly person of the community.  Questions to ask may include: <BR>
<DD>     <DD>      <!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     "How significant do you believe this river is to the town?" or "Has the river changed in regards to the amount of pollution, or the number of fish permitted to eat?"
</DL>  
<DD>     <DD>     This enables the student to get a personal outlook on the river and to make them realize that the river really is important to everyone, themselves included.<BR><P>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <STRONG><EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#199161">Phase 3:</FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>      </STRONG>
<DD>     <DD>      The final class is allotted to the completion of Experiment, Making My City (<CITE>Outlook: The Earth  </CITE>by McCalley p.73).  The students will create a map of a town (to be as similar to Gouverneur as possible).  Still in their groups of two, a large piece of paper will be given to each group- to draw their maps on (35 minutes). This map will incorporate patterns found in the Oswegatchie River map and include components vital to a towns survival.  For example; farming provides food, the river provides power and recreation, and there must be a sewage/water treatment plant.  After the map is finished, the students will explain their reasons and compare their map to other students, possibly even explaining differences in specific locations.  The idea that there is no <STRONG>wrong</STRONG><STRONG>answer</STRONG> will be stressed. The teacher will ask certain questions to stimulate greater conversation within the class:<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     What is a town?<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     What is needed to make a town?<BR>
<DD>     <DD>       Now, the students will write about the importance of interaction in their journals (5 minutes).   The last 5 minutes of class, a questionnaire will be administered to assist in the determination of which students belong in what group; water quality or aquatic plants and animals.  It asks inquiring questions to find where the main interests of each student lies.  When the students are put in their appropriate group, the teaching will be directed toward a class consisting of 7/8 students, to provide a more personal atmosphere and to allow for more individual attention. <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     After the MST students meet at Gouverneur on Thursday, the following day the students will talk between each group; the water quality and the aquatic plants and animals.  This is the time to teach what they have learned and make it even more concrete in their minds.  Journals are also a required MUST!  Each student will write in their journals daily.  A topic will be given at the beginning of class, or at the end,  and they will write for 5 minutes. If we are in the field,  the students will comment on the weather and any other observations they make. <BR>
<DD>     <DD>       <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     </BODY>
<DD>     <DD>     </HTML>
