<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DT><!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DT><DT><HTML>
<DT><DT><HEAD>
<DT><DT><TITLE>lesptwo</TITLE>
<DT><DT></HEAD>
<DT><DT><!-- Body Tag --><BODY BACKGROUND="back2.gif">
<DT><DT></BODY>
<DT><DT><BR>
<DT><DT>
<DD>     <DD>     <H3><EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF659D">Lesson #1:  Ecosystems and Ecotones</FONT></FONT></B></EM></H3>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><I><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF659D">Pedagogy:</FONT></I></FONT></B>  
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <P>The Ecosystem and Ecotones will be introduced to the class at this time. 
<DD>     <DD>      A vital concept we would like the student to realize is that all components of an 
<DD>     <DD>     ecosystem are different, yet they interact to live peacefully.  This is absolutely 
<DD>     <DD>     necessary to maintain an established equilibrium.</P>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF659D">Phase 1:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>        

<P>Journal Entry-  Write what you think of when you hear the word system (5 minutes).  The activity "Edge of Home" (<CITE>Project Aquatic</CITE>p. 68) will be finished before the students go into the field.  They will brainstorm to develop an idea about ecosystems (5-10 minutes), then paint 2 circles, each a different color.  The idea being that the students will see the interaction that occurs when the two circles intercept/overlap (20 minutes).  This will instill the fact that even though it is a segregated world, the two still meet.  When they enter the field, this concept will be present throughout the ecosystem, and will be able to recognize it.  This activity will also familiarize the students with the terms mentioned above.</P>

<BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF659D">Phase 2:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>      

<P> The students will be in the field.  Upon arriving at the particular site, they will initiate their quadrants.  A quadrant will be chosen by each individual, and may be 1 meter by 1 meter.  There is only one requirement:  each student must pick the location that is unique in its characteristics. Possibly one is in the water, half in the water, close to the bank, farther away from the bank, etc...  Next, the students will chart and illustrate their quadrant in their journals(15 minutes).  They will also make any observations and record the necessary data ( weather, high or low life activity, fast or slow moving water, high or low water levels, etc...), including gathering and identifying species (10 minutes). The students have previously learned how to read a field guide, so only a brief review is needed (5 minutes).  A discussion about how each of these affects the other will occur after all is finished (15 minutes).</P>

<BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF659D">Phase 3:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       

<P>This is a classroom activity in which the students will compose ID cards for the Department of Environmental Conservation.  The information on the cards is obtained from the site work completed the day before, and includes the type of species, classified correctly, and the population of that species (20 minutes).   Finally, they will be asked to give a definition of what they think an ecosystem is.  The teacher will employ higher order questioning to direct the student toward a generative answer.  The students will also perform a group brainstorming session with the teacher constantly asking clarifying questions to aid them in the process (10 minutes).  The experiment "My Own Little World" will be started (it is found on the World Wide Web at the URL 
<DD>     <DD>     address:  http://207.22.231.50:80/nsta_scripts/List_SSC_byGrade.idc).<BR>
 The students will be given clean 1 liter Pepsi bottles and told to go outside and collect the following items: soil, 2-3 plants, small insects, dead leaves, 2-3 earthworms, and land snails(10 minutes).  Charcoal, thermometer, rainwater, clear tape and scissors will be provided.  The students will cut off the top of the bottle and add the above items to it.  The bottles will be dated and named on the bottom (5 minutes), and put away for use in a later lesson.</P>

<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     </BODY>
<DD>     <DD>     </HTML>
<DD>     </DL>
</DL>
