<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>pedseven.html - Converted</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BACKGROUND="greyone.gif">
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=6 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>PROJECT OSWEGATCHIE RIVER</CENTER></FONT><P>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#290A64"><CENTER>Water Quality Unit<BR>
Lesson Plan 7<BR>
Pedagogy</CENTER></FONT><P>

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 1</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 2</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior<BR>
Student Behavior<P>

<!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#290A64">Phase 3</FONT><BR>
Lesson Activity<BR>
Teacher Behavior <BR>
Student Behavior<P>

<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5><P>


This section is being revised into the above displayed task analysis format.  Please bear with us during this change.  Feel free to look over our thoughts listed below for a full description of our pedagogy according to the New Science Education <!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nap.edu/nap/online/nses/html/3.html">Teaching</A> and<!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="http://www.nap.edu/nap/online/nses/html/5.html#as"> Assessment</A> Standards.  Thank you.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=5><P>

The topic we want to cover, in detail, is pollution.  A very brief introduction will 
be done for this activity, the students will be performing most of the investigating 
themselves to aid in their learning and retaining the information.  We have been 
continuously reviewing different aspects of the water cycle throughout our investigations. 
<P>


 We now turn to an investigation of pollution, the different types of pollution, 
and the cause and effect of pollution.  There are four definitions of pollution: 
chemical, thermal, organic, and ecological.<P>


<!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Chemical pollution</FONT> - the introduction of toxic substances into an ecosystem.   
 Have
the students brainstorm for examples such as:
acid rain and
contamination of water by pesticides<BR>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Thermal pollution</FONT> - varying temperatures above or below the normal condition.
Brainstorm about 
power plant turbine heated water<BR>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Organic pollution</FONT> - oversupplying an ecosystem with nutrients.
Brainstorm about
fertilizer inflow<BR>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Ecological pollution </FONT>-stresses ordinarily created by natural processes
Brainstorm about
extreme tides pour saltwater into habitats ordinarily protected from seawater; 
abnormal increases in sediments in runoff water to produce silt and the 
introduction of aquatic plants via bird droppings<P>


The best procedure for the presentation of this data would be to introduce all four 
definitions for pollution, list each type of pollution on the bird and have the students 
brainstorm together to list examples of each type of pollution.  The students should 
specify which definition their example fits under and the example should be written 
on the board.  Upon completion of this segment, we will have a type of concept map 
visually available for the continuation of the activity. <P>


The next step is to consider these four types of pollution and determine the cause 
of each - are they human caused or naturally occurring pollution?  Can they be both? 
 Chemical, thermal, and organic pollution can occur without human intervention, and 
they can be caused directly by humans.  Give the students a chance to make this connection 
themselves, if they do not, lead them through an evaluation of the examples listed 
and help them make the connection.
The students should now be able to easily determine how pollution enters an ecosystem 
(there are two different types - point source and non-point source).  Give the students 
a chance to determine the definitions on their own:<P>


<!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Point source</FONT> - a localized source through which pollutants can enter the water 
  system<BR>
<!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Non-point source</FONT> - a variety of less identifiable sources, i.e. rain washing motor 
  oil from the pavement into the water supply<P>
Have the students identify at least three examples of each type of source.<P>


The activity to be performed is detailed on the accompanying handouts.  The students 
should be broken into two groups, assigned jobs, and let loose.  After the appropriate 
student from each group has come forward to receive the handout, go over the expectations 
briefly and allow them to begin work.  We should be consistently examining 
our notebooks and making sure that the job positions held by each student is varying 

during these activities.  <P>


To wind up for the day, close with the following questions:<P>
<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">What five things can each of us do - starting today - to reduce the number of 
pollutants being added to the environment.  Each student should list these five 
ideas in their journal.<BR>
<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">Investigate the United States Clean Air Act.<BR>
<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=8 HEIGHT=8  SRC="earth.gif">Investigate if DDT is still being used, in what states it is still legal, and why? 
<BR>
<P>
As time permits they may be given class time to answer these questions or they may 
be assigned as homework.

</BODY>
