<DT><EM><BR>
<DT></EM>
<DT>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>     <H3><EM><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#4E238A">Lesson #9: Human Interaction</FONT></EM></H3>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#4E238A">Pedagogy:</FONT></EM>  It has now been established that the ecosystem is an operation within itself. 
The role that each component plays can, and will be, upset by the actions of humans. 
This lesson focuses on the importance of the river to humans, whether it is for enjoyment or employment, and to convey the feeling that it is not always a beneficial act.<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#4E238A">Phase 1:</FONT></EM>
<DD>     <DD>        Journal Entry- What do humans use the river for?  Do they intend to harm the environment?<BR>
<DD>     <DD>      A role play will be performed in which a student picks a specific interest group (farmer, resident, factory owner/worker, fisherman, etc...) .  That student will be put on trial in front of advocates of the natural environment.  The advocates will ask opposing questions, requiring the special interest student to defend his/her position, giving concise explanations supporting his/her answers.  This will serve as a discussion about the effects (both positive and negative) this group has on the environment, mainly the river.  This procedure should be repeated for several students (45 minutes).<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#4E238A">Phase 2 & 3:</FONT></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Journal Entry- What is necessary for an ideal habitat for a deer?<BR>
<DD>     <DD>      The activity "Dragonfly Pond" from <CITE>Project Aquatic </CITE> p.154, will be completed.  This activity is actually a simulation of the habitat around a pond.  The students will be given a 18 x 24 inch cut out representing the pond.  Included, will be various land uses (i.e. farmland, parks, factory base). 
After the students cut out all the land uses, a class discussion will be held, discussing more of the pros and cons to each land use.  These may be written on the board for class reference.  The students will be told that they must use each land use to create a habitat. Although they may be separated, they must not overlap, only touch. Yet at the same time, the wildlife habitat must be preserved.  Throughout the time the students are working, they will be periodically interrupted to explain, demonstrate, and discuss their dragonfly pond (30-35 minutes).  When they are finished, positive and negative aspects of human interaction will be identified, and possible solutions to these actions will be proposed and discussed.  The students will identify land uses in   Gouverneur and propose various ways to improve land use there (10 minutes).
<DD>     </DL>
<DD>     </BODY>
<DD>     </HTML>
</DL>
