<DT><!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DT><DT><HTML>
<DT><DT><HEAD>
<DT><DT><TITLE>lespeig</TITLE>
<DT><DT></HEAD>
<DT><DT><BODY BACKGROUND="back2.gif">
<DT><DT><BR>
<DT><DT>
<DD>     <DD>     <H3><EM><B><CENTER><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">Lesson #7: Animals</FONT></FONT></CENTER></B></EM></H3>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><I><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">Pedagogy:</FONT></I></FONT> </B> The students have already learned and understand the role of plants in an ecosystem; and how to classify the plants according to the 5 Kingdom, hierarchical classification system.  In this lesson, the close relationship which exists between plants and animals will be stressed.  They will also learn how to classify animals according to the same system. <BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">Phase 1:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Journal Entry- If a fish requires an aqueous environment for survival, will it live if the water is taken away? In this sense, is water a limiting factor? Why?<BR>
<DD>     <DD>      Limiting factors will be introduced by demonstration.  The demonstration will consist of a water barrel.  The boards of the water barrel will each be a different length, and when filled with water, can only be filled as high as the shortest board. The shortest one poses a limit for the water level.  The students will be asked to hypothesize why this is demonstrative of limiting factors.  It must be explained that without 
this factor, that species cannot exist (30 minutes).  The remainder of the class will be spent discussing adaptation through evolution.  The teacher will pose hypothetical questions to the class concerning man:<BR>
<DD>     <DD>      " Supposing man really is a result of advances in the monkey, can you name similarities and differences between the two?" <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     Present the poster of man's evolution, ask if they can think of any other animals which may have undergone the same/similar processes.  Finally, tell the students of one specific animal, the fish, ask them: <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     " Did the fish have lungs?" <BR>
<DD>     <DD>         Tell them:  An amphibian is actually an advanced fish.  <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     Ask the students to share ideas for possible adaptations required to allow the fish to go  from water to land,  and possible reasons why the fish would want to leave the water (15 minutes). <BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">Phase 2:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Journal Entry- Make a rough sketch of the deer track, and make predictions about the animals.<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     Is it heavy?<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     Is it big?  <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     In the field, students will find an animal track, the most common track would be of a deer, and make a plaster casting of the track, using premade plaster.  A piece of  one foot diameter cardboard by 2 inch made into a ring will be placed over the track, and filled with plaster.  Allow it to dry for about half an hour.  Then remove the casting, and any debris that may have accumulated with a brush.  Compare the casting to other tracks to determine the classification of the animal.  When looking for its classification, provide an explanation of the characteristics in the journal which are used in the field guide for determination (10 minutes).  Students will take a soil sample from this site for future use (2-3 minutes).<BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#00FF00">Phase 3:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Cranial Creation #23 from <CITE>Cranial Creations in Life Science </CITE> by Downing and Miller p.101 will be performed and put in their journals. The student is given a list of conditions,  for example; little rain, and they must give an adaptation which would allow the animal to live there.  After an adaptation is given for each condition, the student must draw a picture of what they think that animal looks like, with an accompanying description (25-30 minutes).  Each reason should show a logical thinking progression.  If the students want to, they can share their creation  with the class.  At this time, the journals will be handed in for evaluation (10-15 minutes).
<DD>     <DD>     </BODY>
<DD>     <DD>     </HTML>
<DD>     </DL>
</DL>
