<DT><DT><HEAD>
<DT><DT><TITLE>lespthr</TITLE>
<DT><DT></HEAD>
<DT><DT><!-- Body Tag --><BODY BACKGROUND="back2.gif">
<DT><DT></BODY>
<DT><DT><BR>
<DT><DT>
<DD>     <DD>     <H3><EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Lesson #2:  Energy and the Nutrient Cycles</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>      </H3>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><I><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Pedagogy:</FONT></I></FONT></B>  
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <P>The students must be made aware of the extreme dependence that biotic factors have on abiotic factors.  The energy exchange occurs every minute of every day.  In this lesson, the students will study the water cycle, the sun, and three nutrient cycles.  This demonstrates the connectedness of the individual constituents of the 
<DD>     <DD>     life cycle.</P>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Phase 1:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <P>Journal Entry- Free write anything about the sun.<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     A brainstorming session with the entire class about the energy from the sun will take place.  <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     "What does it do?"
</DL> 
<DD>     <DD>     Additional directive questions from the teacher serve to achieve a clear cycle.  For example:<BR>
<DD>     <DD>      <!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     "Are plants dependent upon the sun? How? "
</DL> 
<DD>     <DD>    <!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     "Are animals dependent      on the sun?  How?"
</DL> 
<DD>     <DD>      This will take approximately 15 minutes.  The remainder of the class period will be filled by completing the experiment "Water Wings" from <CITE> Project Aquatic </CITE> p.4.  This experiment will stress the significance and necessity of water to all living things.  The students will also learn the water cycle and reiterate it by drawing a poster.  For this, the students will break into four groups of two.  Each poster will be hung in the room for the remainder of the lesson.  A homework activity given to them will require the pupil to make an energy list of each electrical appliance in their house.  (Reference: <CITE>Outlook: The Earth</CITE> by McCalley p.131). The cost per kilowatt hour will be given to them and they must determine how much energy they use (the information on the back of the appliance gives the usage) and how much it costs them.  When this is accomplished, they must devise various ways to "save" energy.  The list will be due the next day, or a penalty imposed.</P>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Phase 2:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>      
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <P> The homework will be discussed and a different form of energy will be introduced; the energy of nutrients (10 minutes).  After the students have each explained their findings and solutions, handouts of the carbon and nitrogen cycle will be given to each student.  They will then be divided into two groups of four students.  It will take  about twenty minutes to give an example, or a means of energy transfer between each variable in the cycle.  For example; between the sun and plants, they may add sunlight in the daytime.  The cycle will be put on chart paper, with each example included. 
<DD>     <DD>      There will be a designated spokesperson from each group who will then explain the groups supporting reasons concerning why they answered in that way (10 minutes).  The last 5 minutes will be spent writing in the journals.  Journal Entry- Does everybody and everything utilize the same energy sources?</P>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64">Phase 3:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <P>The experiment "Tracking Down Carbon in Nonliving Systems", found on the World Wide Web at the URL address:       http://207.22.231.50:80/nsta_scripts/List_SSC_byGrade.idc, is an activity which will be performed to demonstrate the carbon cycle (30-35 minutes).  A beaker of lime water is present with a candle burning in it.  When the candle burns out, shake the beaker.  The students must then blow into it until it turns very milky white.  This beaker will sit overnight.  Throughout the experiment, students will note any observational changes in their journals, comparing this beaker to the plain lime water beaker.  After the experiment, students will draw the carbon cycle as they have viewed it.  They will also write about what they have learned, and how it is important to humans.</P>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>       
<DD>     <DD>     </BODY>
<DD>     <DD>     </HTML>
