<DT><DT><TITLE>lespsev</TITLE>
<DT><DT></HEAD>
<DT><DT><BODY BACKGROUND="back2.gif">
<DT><DT><BR>
<DT><DT>
<DD>     <DD>     <H3><EM><!-- Font Tag --><I><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#A27314"><CENTER>Lesson #6:  Photosynthesis</CENTER></FONT></I></EM></H3>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <!-- Font Tag --><I><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#A27314">Pedagogy:</FONT></I>  The importance of plants to all life was established the last lesson.  The most vital aspect, Photosynthesis, will be studied in detail now.  Although a new topic is commencing, it is still related to plants and the inter-relationships among the species of the ecosystem.<BR><P>


<DD>     <DD>     <EM><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#A27314">Phase 1:</FONT></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Journal Entry- Make a list of organisms dependent on plants.<BR>
<DD>     <DD>      A movie will be shown to the pupils, which pertains to photosynthesis.  The movie will teach them about energy from the sun and its conversion in photosynthesis; this includes respiration in plants and animals, and the role of oxygen and carbon dioxide.  Before the movie is started, a list of concepts to look for in the movie will be presented to the students.  This can be done by putting it on a handout, or by writing it on the board.  This list must include: chlorophyll, pigmentation, respiration, carbon dioxide, oxygen, and light energy.  When the movie is finished, all concepts will be discussed as to their role in photosynthesis and the degree of importance, in a group discussion (one 45 minute class period).  <BR><P>


<DD>     <DD>     <EM><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#A27314">Phase 2 & 3:</FONT></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Both days will be used to perform the experiment "Photosynthesis Dry Lab"  from <CITE>Cranial Creations in Life Science  </CITE> by Downing and Miller p.162.  This lab will challenge the students to analyze specific reactions and predict what will happen if a certain test is implemented.  All observations and comments are to be put in their journals.  The students must give reasons for the obtained results, based on their knowledge of photosynthesis.  <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     The scientific method will need to be utilized when students  work backwards from the results to derive the hypothesis (two 45 minute class periods).  
<DD>     <DD>     </BODY>
<DD>     <DD>     </HTML>
<DD>     </DL>
</DL>
