<BODY bgcolor="#ffffff" text="#000000" link="#0000ff" vlink="#ff00ff">

<CENTER><IMG WIDTH=462 HEIGHT=87  SRC="../FACBOOK.GIF"></CENTER><BR>
<BR>

<A NAME="VI.  RETIREMENT, DISABILITY AND DEATH BENEFITS"><CENTER><B>VI.  RETIREMENT, DISABILITY AND DEATH BENEFITS</B></CENTER></A>
<dt><br>
<BR>

<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B6"><BLOCKQUOTE><I>6</A>.	RETIREMENT PLANS FOR TIER III AND TIER IV MEMBERS - GENERAL STATEMENT</I>
<dt><br>
<dt>Tier III members are entitled to receive either the benefits under  the Coordinated Escalator Plan (CO-ESC) or the benefits under the Coordinated Retirement Plan.  Members may not mix the provisions of the two laws to change the eligibility requirements for a benefit under either plan.  Once a Tier III member selects and begins to receive a retirement benefit, whether it be under CO-ESC or the Coordinated Retirement Plan, (s)he cannot change plans.  For example, if a Tier III member credited with less than 30 years of service retires at age 55 under the provisions of the CO-ESC Plan with its 30% reduction and its offset of Social Security beginning at age 62, the member is "locked in" to that benefit--(s)he cannot change to Coordinated Retirement Plan benefits at a later date.  (See below for further discussion of these benefits.)
<dt><br>
<dt>Tier IV members are only entitled to the benefits of the Coordinated Retirement Plan.</BLOCKQUOTE>

	</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B7"><BLOCKQUOTE><I>7</A>.	RETIREMENT PLAN FOR TIER III MEMBERS (7/27/76 - 8/31/83) THE COORDINATED ESCALATOR PLAN (CO-ESC)</I>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B7a">a</A>)	Funding (Contributions)
<dt><br>
	<dt>CO-ESC members must contribute 3% of their annual salary toward their retirement benefits during the period for which they accrue service credit.  Employers also contribute to the Retirement System on behalf of members.  These two sources together with investment income provide the money to pay retirement benefits.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B7b">b</A>)	Borrowing
<dt><br>
			<dt>CO-ESC members may borrow from their contributions.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B7c">c</A>)	Refunds
<dt><br>
			<dt>CO-ESC members cannot withdraw while they are employed as teachers.  If they stop teaching in a New York State public school or college they can only withdraw if credited with less than 10 years of service.  Upon withdrawal, they are entitled to a refund of their contributions with interest.
		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B7d">d</A>)	Service Retirement Eligibility
<dt><br>
			<dt>If prior to your present membership in the System you never were a member of any public retirement system in New York State, you will be eligible to retire at age 55 with a minimum of 10 years of service after July 1, 1973, or
<dt><br>
<dt>If you held a previous membership in a NYS public retirement system, you will be eligible to retire at age 55 with a total of 10 years of service, or
<dt><br>
<dt>If you attain age 70, you will be eligible to retire if you are credited with a minimum of five years of service.
<Dt><br>
		</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B7e">e</A>)	Benefit Calculation
<dt><br>
			<dt>For each year of credited service up to 20, you receive 1 2/3% of your final average salary.  If you are credited with 20 or more years of service, your allowance is computed at the rate of 2% per year, not in excess of 30 years, of your final average salary.  Final average salary is defined as the average of your highest three consecutive annual salaries (with certain limitations).
<dt><br>
<dt>The law requires a reduction based on age, as follows:
<br>
<center>
<table width=90%>
<tr><th align=left>RETIREMENT AT AGE</th>  <th align=left>% OF REDUCTION</th>  </tr>

<tr><td>61</td>                 <td>6.7%</td>               
<tr><td>60</td>                <td>13.3%</td>               
<tr><td>59</td>                <td>16.7%</td>               
<tr><td>58</td>                <td>20.0%</td>               
<tr><td>57</td>                <td>23.3%</td>               
<tr><td>56</td>                <td>26.7%</td>               
<tr><td>55</td>                <td>30.0%</td>               
</table>
</center>
<dt><br>
<dt>At age 62, your benefit will be diminished by 50% of your Social Security benefit accrued while in NYS public employment.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B7f">f</A>)	Deferred Retirement (Vesting)
<dt><br>
			<dt>If you have at least 10 years of credited service and you cease to teach in a New York State public school, you have vested rights.  Vesting enables you to receive a retirement benefit at age 55 or later.  Your benefit will be calculated the same as above.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B7g">g</A>)	Ordinary Disability Retirement
<dt><br>
			<dt>If you are credited with at least five years of service and are not eligible for a normal retirement benefit but are eligible for a primary Social Security disability benefit, you may be eligible for an ordinary disability benefit from the Retirement System.
<dt><br>
<dt>The ordinary disability benefit is computed at the rate of 2% per year of service up to 30 years.  It cannot be less than 33 1/3% of final average salary, minus 50% of any primary Social Security disability benefit and 100% of any workers' compensation payments.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B7h">h</A>)	Accidental Disability Retirement
<dt><br>
			<Dt>If you become disabled as the natural and proximate result of an accident on the job, not caused by your own willful negligence, and you are not eligible for a normal service retirement benefit but are eligible for primary Social Security disability benefits, you may be eligible for an accidental benefit from the Retirement System.
<dt><br>
<dt>The accidental disability payment is computed at the rate of 2% per year of service you would have been credited with had your employment continued until age 65, not in excess of 30 years, multiplied by your final average salary, minus 50% of any primary Social Security disability benefit and 100% of any workers' compensation payments.</BLOCKQUOTE>

		</dl>
<dt>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B8"><i>8</A>.	RETIREMENT PLAN FOR TIER III (7/27/76 - 8/31/83) AND TIER IV (ON OR AFTER 9/1/83) MEMBERS--THE COORDINATED RETIREMENT PLAN</i>

<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B8a">a</A>)	Funding (Contributions)
<dt><br>
			<dt>Coordinated Retirement Plan members must contribute 3% of their annual salary toward their retirement benefits.  Employers also contribute to the Retirement System on behalf of members.  These two sources together with investment income provide the money to pay retirement benefits.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B8b">b</A>)	Borrowing
<dt><br>
			<dt>Coordinated Retirement Plan members may borrow from their contributions.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B8c">c</A>)	Refunds
<dt><br>
			<dt>Coordinated Retirement Plan members cannot withdraw while they are employed as teachers.  If they stop teaching in a New York State public school, they can apply for a refund of their contributions, with interest, at age 62 if credited with less than 10 years of service.  Upon death, where an individual has not retired or where a death benefit is not payable, the contributions shall be refunded to the designated beneficiary.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B8d">d</A>)	Service Retirement Eligibility
<dt><br>

			<BLOCKQUOTE><BLOCKQUOTE>Coordinated Retirement Plan members may retire:<br>
<br>
at age 55, if credited with 30 years of service, or<br>
at age 62, if credited with 10 years of service, or<br>
at age 70, if credited with 5 years of service.<br></BLOCKQUOTE></BLOCKQUOTE>
<br>

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B8e">e</A>)	Benefit Calculation
<dt><br>
			<dd>i)	If credited with less than 25 years of service, your allowance is computed at the rate of 1 2/3% of final average salary for each year of service.
<dt><br>
			<dd>ii)	If credited with 25 to 30 years of service, you receive 2% of final average salary for each year of service.
<dt><br>
			<dd>iii)	If credited with more than 30 years of service, you receive 60% of final average salary for the first 30 years (2% for each year) and 1 1/2% of final average for each additional year.
<dt><br>
<dt>Final average salary is defined as the average of your highest three consecutive regular annual salaries (with certain limitations).

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B8f">f</A>)	Deferred Retirement (Vesting)
<dt><br>
			<dt>If you have at least 10 years of credited service and cease to teach in a New York State public school, you have vested rights. Vesting enables you to receive a retirement benefit at age 62.  Your benefit will be calculated the same as above, but in no event can it be less than the actuarial equivalent of your contributions plus interest.

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
<dt><A NAME="6B8g">g</A>)	Disability Retirement
<dt><br>
			<dt>If you are credited with a least 10 years of service and are determined by the Retirement System to be physically or mentally incapacitated for performance of gainful employment, you would be eligible for a disability benefit.
<dt><br>
<dt>If the Retirement System determines that you are disabled from the performance of gainful employment as the natural and proximate result of an accident not caused by your own willful negligence sustained in performance of your duties in active service while actually a member of the Retirement System, the requirement that you must have 10 years' credited service is waived.
<dt><br>
<dt>Coordinated Retirement Plan members under age 60 retiring for disability will receive a retirement allowance equal to 1/60 of final average salary multiplied by the number of years of credited service.  However, such members shall receive a minimum pension of the lesser of 33 1/3% of final average salary or 1/60 of final average salary multiplied by the total service the member would have rendered had (s)he continued in service to age 60.
<dt><br>
<dt>Members age 60 and older who meet the eligibility requirements for disability retirement will have their allowances computed on the same basis as a service retirement allowance.  However, in no event can such members receive more than they would under the disability calculation.
<dt><br>
<dt>The Application for Disability Retirement must be filed with the System within three months from the last date the member was being paid on the payroll, or within 12 months of the last date the member was being paid on the payroll if the member was on a leave of absence for medical reasons without pay during such 12- month period and was disabled at the time the salary ceased being paid.</BLOCKQUOTE>

		</dl>
<dt><br>
<dd><dl>
</dl>
	</dl><BR>
<BR>

