<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>     <H3><EM><B><CENTER><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#66081E">Lesson # 10: Human Interaction</FONT></FONT></CENTER></B></EM></H3>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <B><I><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><EM><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#66081E">Pedagogy:</FONT></EM></FONT></I> </B> We will further investigate the impact that human interaction has on the river, and the impact the river has on humans.  For example, factory wastes are dumped into the river, which poisons the fish.  When we go to eat the fish, they are filled with high levels of mercury, dangerous for human consumption.   Indeed, a reciprocal relationship exists; it begins with humans, enters the food chain, and returns to us with adverse consequences.<BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#66081E">Phase 1:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       The students will propose various impacts humans have on the environment, and how it negatively impacts us in the end.  The quality of the food obtained from the river will be discussed. It will be found by writing a letter, requesting specific information, to the DEC, and by contacting a community health building in Gouverneur.  Each student will choose what they want to do, but four have to write a letter and four have to contact the health building (10 minutes).  The letter is a homework assignment, as is contacting the community health building.  The demonstration "Cleaning Water: 
Heat, Cold, and Vapor" from 474<CITE> Science Activities for Young Children</CITE> by Green p.89 will be done (35 minutes).  Throughout this demonstration, the students will record any observable changes in their journals. This will show each student that nature has an intrinsic method of cleaning water.  Cling wrap, two bowls, boiling   and cold water will be required for this activity.  Because it is such a simple experiment, only the teacher will do it.  After the demonstration, the students will give possible reasons for the changes that were observed and they will discuss the way it occurs in nature (10 minutes).<BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#66081E">Phase 2:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Journal Entry- How do you feel about people who knowingly harm the environment, yet refuse to remedy the problem?<BR>
<DD>     <DD>      The health problems associated with pollution which resulted from negative human impact will also be discussed.  These pollution problems need to be realized by the students; sometimes it is not even known that they exist.  The remainder of the class period will be filled by completing the experiment "Deadly Links" from <CITE>Project Wild</CITE> p.270.  The activity is to demonstrate the impact pesticides have had on the environment. 
They enter the food chain and continue through, affecting every level. The students will be divided into grasshoppers, shrews and hawks.  Each one will carry a bag which represents their stomach.  Multi-colored pieces for dog food, or poker chips will be distributed either within the classroom, or in an open space.  The grasshoppers     will be given 60 seconds to collect food, then the shrews can hunt the grasshoppers for 30-60 seconds.  Each captured grasshopper surrenders his/her stomach and sits out of the game.  Then the hawks, who have been watching, hunt the shrews for 30-60 seconds (30 minutes- includes set-up and organization time).  The teacher will explain that pesticides were used to spray the crop the grasshoppers ate.  Any multicolored food is contaminated with pesticides.  Therefore, any grasshoppers not eaten by the shrews will be dead if they contaminated food in their stomachs.  This is to stress pesticides in the environment and its passage through the food chain.  The students will offer other examples of this phenomenon (15 minutes).<BR><BR>
<DD>     <DD>     
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#66081E">Phase 3:</FONT></FONT></B></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       At the site, along a highway, or on school grounds, the students will write in their journals any evidence they have found of human interaction there.  To make the students realize that they can help the environment, they will be asked to pick up garbage, litter, or waste found (30 minutes).  Finally, as  a conclusion to pollution, the      students will devise various ways in which pollution can be eliminated or minimized to allow for a much cleaner environment (10 minutes).
<DD>     <DD>     </BODY>
<DD>     <DD>     </HTML>
<DD>     </DL>
</DL>
