<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<!-- List Tag --><DL>
<DD>     <DD>     <H3><EM><!-- Font Tag --><I><FONT SIZE=5 COLOR="#FF0000">Lesson #8:  Food Chains and Trophic Pyramids</FONT></I></EM>
<DD>     <DD>      </H3>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#FF0000"><I>Pedagogy:</I></FONT>  This lesson is a perfect denouement of the constituents of an ecosystem. 
<DD>     <DD>      Everything previously covered will be reviewed and a definite dependence will be made obvious.  Particular emphasis will be placed on food chains and trophic pyramids.<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#FF0000">Phase 1:</FONT></EM>
<DD>     <DD>      Students will be asked to complete the activity "Colors that Stand out In Nature" found off the World Wide Web at the URL address:   <BR>
    http://207.22.231.50:80/nsta_scripts/List_SSC_byGrade.idc. 
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     One hundred toothpicks will be scattered around the schoolyard.  All the toothpicks will be five different colors ,green must be one, representing food.  In this activity, the students are the predators hunting for the food.  There will be a specified amount of time for the predators to capture their food (15-20 minutes).  After the time is up, count the number of prey and chart a data table for the entire class.  The data will then be entered into a computer and graphed for the whole class.  A discussion will follow about how it represents competition and why it may be a food chain (20-25 minutes).<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#FF0000">Phase 2:</FONT></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Complete the activity "Food Chains" found off the World Wide Web at the URL address: 
<DD>     <DD>      http://207.22.231.50:80/nsta_scripts/List_SSC_byGrade.idc,<BR>
  to further cover the concept of food webs and trophic levels.  The students will demonstrate their knowledge of this subject matter by completing a "flow-diagram"  of energy through the various levels.  Interactions between the different chains can be exhibited by having a student hold multi-colored string and set up around the room.  It is a great idea to have the teacher participate as a positive role model (45 minutes).<BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <EM><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=4 COLOR="#FF0000">Phase 3:</FONT></EM>
<DD>     <DD>       Direct, hands-on, experience will be implemented to culminate our topic on food chains.  The students will make a human food pyramid.  The set up is similar to this one:                                                 
<DD>     <DD>                                                         <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <IMG SRC="lespnin1.gif">  <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     <BR>
<DD>     <DD>     Each level will be labeled with a colored construction paper.  One person, not actively participating, will take a picture of the pyramid.  This picture will be analyzed and the students can view the mass distribution and determine the order of importance.  It is critical for the students to realize that the farther up the food chain energy moves, the less there is.  Therefore, the lowest level is most important, decreasing in importance as you climb the levels (45 minutes).
<DD>     </DL>
</DL>
