<BODY>
<B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5>Lesson Plan #11 - St. Lawrence River Effect</FONT></B><BR><BR>
<CENTER><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64"><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="lespten">Task Analysis</A></A></FONT></CENTER><BR>
<CENTER><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64"><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="assmnt">Assessment</A></FONT></CENTER><BR>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=3 NOSHADE>

<BR>
Lesson Target   <BR>
          Effect of one river <BR>
         on another      <BR>
Science Concept:<BR>
Erosion, hydromixing, adaptation, introduction of non-indigenous   species<BR>
<BR>
Science Skills:<BR>
Analyzing and predicting<BR>
Observation<BR>
Communicating and discussing<BR>
Interpretation<BR>
<BR>
Interdisciplinary Connection:<BR>
Geography, physics<BR>
<BR>
Duration: 1 week<BR>
<BR>
Lesson outcomes:<BR>

<H3> </H3>
Students will:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>Predict characteristics of river dynamics at the mouth of a river.<BR>
<LI>Create rivers in sand table activity using two different river    scenarios.<BR>
<LI>Compare and discuss the differences for the two rivers produced.<BR>
<LI>Predict and discuss similarities with the Oswegatchie/St.     Lawrence rivers.<BR>
<LI>At the river site, observe actual river dynamics.<BR>
<LI>Compare observed with predicted.<BR>
<LI>Compare species at different sites with species at mouth of river.<BR>
<LI>Search for evidence of erosion.<BR>
<LI>Collect evidence of human uses and pollution.<BR>
<LI>Chart differences observed in journals. <BR>
<BR>
</OL>
Overview:<BR>
The students will create rivers to compare river dynamics, erosion and water flow 
at the mouth of the Oswegatchie/St. Lawrence River connection.  The lesson with start 
with prediction and will compare hypothesized notions with actual data at the Oswegatchie sites.  Species adaptation, invasion and human factors will also be discussed.
</BODY>
</HTML>
