<BODY>
<B><!-- Font Tag --><FONT SIZE=5>Lesson Plan #13 - Migration</FONT></B><BR><BR>
<CENTER><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64"><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="lespfrt">Task Analysis</A></FONT></CENTER><BR>
<CENTER><!-- Font Tag --><FONT COLOR="#290A64"><!-- Link Tag --><A HREF="assmnt">Assessment</A></FONT></CENTER><BR>
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR WIDTH=100% SIZE=3 NOSHADE>

<BR>
Lesson Target   <BR>
       Migration:<BR>
 reasons for and how?      <BR>
<BR>
Science Concept:<BR>
Limiting factors<BR>
Predator-prey relationships<BR>
Weather changes<BR>
<BR>
Science Skills:<BR>
Observation  analyzing and predicting<BR>
data taking   planning<BR>
pattern recognition<BR>
<BR>
Interdisciplinary Connection:<BR>
Earth Science, Social Sciences<BR>
Students will state, through a series of processes which include;    note taking, 
observing, pattern finding and prediction, why a    particular event has occurred, 
and what caused it.<BR>
<BR>
Duration: 1 week<BR>
<BR>
Lesson outcomes:<BR>

<H3> </H3>
Students will:<BR>
<OL>
<LI>Observe their own quadrant; noting any changes - pertaining to    plant and animal 
signs.<BR>
<LI>Brainstorm, as a class, and determine reasons for a migration,    also a means.<BR>
<LI>Break into groups of 2 and plan a trip for a certain animal (the    choice is solely 
students: retain diversity)  The trip must take    into account the following factors: 
 Time of year, weather,    season, method, and for what purpose (ie. to obtain a 
greater    food source)<BR>
<LI>Using the "trip", state  a cause and effect relationship (ie. Cold    weather caused 
the animals to move underground.) <BR>
<LI>Determine population changes.<BR>
<LI>Determine the limiting factors by completing Migration Headache    Experiment (Aquatic 
Book p.94-98). <BR>
<BR>
</OL>
Overview:<BR>
In this lesson on the migration of species, students will recognize the relationships 
between weather and species habitat/niche.
</BODY>
