<BODY>
<BR>

<H3><EM>Lesson #13:  Invasive Species</EM></H3>
<BR>
<BR>
Pedagogy:  Our final lesson concentrates on the introduction of new species into a 
previously uninhabited area.  They proliferate to such an extent that they upset 
the naturally maintained balance and virtually chokes out other indigenous species. 
 This occurs because of the increased competition the invasive species creates for the habitat, 
and because the native species originally there is unable to adapt so quickly,   
they die.  The two main invasive species we will be devoting the most study to, is 
the zebra mussel and purple loosestrife.  There are others, such as the carp, eel, trout, 
and the alewife, but the zebra mussel and the purple loosestrife are the most recent, 
with a the greatest impact, causing much debate in this area.  We are expecting to 
find the presence of these species in the Oswegatchie River.<BR>
<EM>Phase 1:</EM>
  The journals will be submitted for a final grading.  <BR>
The students will be asked what words they would associate with exotic and native. 
 From the words they provide, a definition for them will be constructed.  Then, they 
will be asked if any exotic species were found at the sites along the Oswegatchie 
River.  If so, field guides will be used in classifying them.  Research will entail, in 
which the students use an encyclopedia to determine the origin of that species.  
Finally, the students will chart and illustrate possible migration routes on unlined 
paper.  These will be submitted to the teacher for evaluation (45 minutes).  <BR>
Homework:  The students must do research to devise a list of exotic species in the 
Oswegatchie River.<BR>
<EM>Phase 2:</EM>
  The activity "Aquatic Roots" from <CITE>Project Aquatic </CITE>
 p.100 will be completed.  The information gathered will include the origin, and its 
impacts on the area.  They will list the benefits and liabilities provided for the 
environment (40 minutes).  An oral report to the class will be required, reporting 
upon their findings.  The oral will be very informal, 2-3 minutes in length.    Homework: 
 The students will write a reflective experience, in which they comment on the amount 
of learned material, the enjoyment out of it, methods of teaching, and whether they 
liked the class or not.<BR>
<EM>Phase 3:</EM>
  Finally,  the exotic species impact will end with a class discussion of the economic 
costs of them, and possible solutions on how to terminate, or control them (15-20 
minutes).  Teacher evaluations will be handed out and the students are welcome to 
comment upon the class outline and content (20 minutes).
</BODY>
</HTML>
