<HEAD>
<TITLE>lesptwl</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<BR>

<H3><EM>Lesson #12: Seasonal Changes</EM></H3>
<BR>
<BR>
Pedagogy:  The four seasons affect the ecosystem through physical property changes, 
such as water erosion, soil content, amount of precipitation, and the degree of temperature 
fluctuation. <BR>
<EM>Phase 1:</EM>
  In two groups of four, the students will complete "The Frozen Water Experiment" 
from the <CITE>474 Science Activities for Young Children</CITE>
  by Green p.87.  This will allow the students to observe, on a smaller scale, the 
physical changes, and scientific concepts (density) which result from freezing.  
After the experiment is completed, within their groups, they must hypothesize about 
the changes which occur in the river, with the change in seasons (35 minutes).  They must 
write these in their journals, and share their results with the class.  A recorder 
and a spokesperson will be designated before the experiment starts (15 minutes).<BR>
<EM>Phase 2:</EM>
  (Note: The students have already had a lesson on succession, prior to commencing 
this one.)  At the field site, preferably below Gouverneur, the students must look 
for the changes of succession.  In groups of two, the students will complete the 
activity "Nothing Succeeds Like Succession" from <CITE>Outlook: The Earth</CITE>
  by McCalley p.203.  They will choose two different places at the site and observe 
differences and similarities in the successional stage.  They will then formulate 
a hypothesis to explain the differences in the two areas.  A soil sample will be 
taken from the river bed and analyzed, using the soil testing kits provided by the Gouverneur 
school district (40 minutes).  Finally, the students will write a scenario, in their 
journals, predicting  what the area will look like if it is left undisturbed for 
five years (10 minutes).<BR>
<EM>Phase 3:</EM>
  The experiment "Soil Samples" from <CITE>474 Science Activities for Young Children  </CITE>
by Green p.358 will be performed.  A soil sample will have been taken from each site 
several weeks in advance.  Each student was given a container and a label.  They 
were instructed to take a small sample from the site and to label it correctly: Name,Date, Weather, and Site.  Part Two will require the students to analyze the soil taken 
from each spot, noting any differences.  Last, they will compare soil type to the 
conditions described in their journals for that day, time of year, and weather conditions. 
 The students will record these comparisons in their journals  Several students will 
be asked to share their findings.  The class will be asked to draw any conclusions 
from the data found (45 minutes).
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
