<HEAD>
<TITLE>Assessments</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<EM>Assessment<BR>
</EM>
<EM><BR>
</EM>
  Two "Student Self Assessments" and one "Summative Assessment Checklist"  will be 
will be developed for each unit plan.  The "Student Self Assessment" 
should assess understanding of the science concept, the science process skill being practiced, and the social skill 
being practiced. <BR>
Below are copies of two student self assessment activities that were used for the Engage Lesson of this unit.  These "worksheets" become self assessment tools when pupils are provided a chance to check their answers with one another, and to check their answers with a standard copy of the worksheet, without the teacher providing input or using results for grading.  Based on results of the student self assessments, the teacher will modify follow up activities until pupils have constructed the concepts necessary for other activities.
<!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>
 <BR>
 <CENTER><!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=165  SRC="selftest.gif">	<!-- Graphic Tag --><IMG WIDTH=200 HEIGHT=165  SRC="selfttwo.gif"></CENTER>
</BODY>
</HTML><!-- Horizontal Line Tag --><HR>

In addition to these, the college student / teacher used a "Summative Assessment Checklist" she  maintained for each student.  The checklist lists 
all concepts and skills in the lesson plan objectives, and provides opportunity to record 
performance in five categories (<STRONG>O</STRONG>
utstanding, <STRONG>M</STRONG>
astery, <STRONG>D</STRONG>
eveloping, <STRONG>I</STRONG>
nadequate, <STRONG>N</STRONG>
ot yet).    The checklist would be used during all five lessons of the unit, which allows the pupils to demonstrate higher levels of performance as the unit progresses.
</DOC>
