<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>UnitCooperativeLearningPlan [v4</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY>
<STRONG>Johnson &amp; Johnson's Cooperative Learning Model<BR>
</STRONG>
Effective hands on science requires that students work in groups. Six standards established by Johnson and Johnson for 
 group work are given below.  The BSCS "Science For Life and Living" program uses these standards and identifies specific social and communication skills which may be developed in grades K - 6.  At grade levels K and 1 group size should not be greater than 2.  At grade 2 group size may be increased to 3, and at grade 4 group size may be increased to 4.  Groups should stay intact for the duration of a unit, and pupils should work together as they progress through the 5 E's.  Larger group size allows pupils to develop enhanced social and communication skills, and to engage in more complex investigations. Success in developing those skills depends upon structuring group jobs effectively and having students assess themselves on their developing social and communication skills.  A cooperative education plan for your unit should cover all of these factors.<BR>
1. 
<H6>Positive interdependence:</H6>
 the goals or tasks are structured so that students must concern themselves with the 
performance of all team members, not just their own performance. What will you do 
to cause this to occur in groups doing your lesson? ______________________________<BR>
<HR>
<HR>
2. 
<H6>Heterogeneity: </H6>
cooperative teams should be heterogeneous in terms of ability, gender, ethnicity, 
and other personal characteristics. What special provisions will you make to assure 
that heterogeneous groups which you form will work well? (What possible difficulties 
do you anticipate? What are you going to do to make sure that those difficulties do not 
inhibit good work?) _______________________________________________________________________<BR>
<HR>
<HR>
3.
<H6> Leadership:</H6>
 All members of teams share leadership responsibilities. Each member has a job to 
do, and the team has no formal leader.   What instructions will you give to your 
pupils to bring about this situation during your lesson(s)?    ___________________________________________________<BR>
<HR>
<HR>
4. 
<H6>Partnership:</H6>
 In their teams, students focus on both the academic assignment and the skills they 
need for working together. They review the success of their assignment and how well 
they cooperated and they try to improve both. What will you do with your pupils to 
make sure that this occurs? _______________________________________________________________________<BR>
<HR>
<HR>

<H6>5. Social Skills:</H6>
 (See table 2 for suggestions on social skills development at each grade level) Students 
learn their social skills the same way they learn academic material. Proficiency 
at sharing leadership, communicating, building trust, and managing conflict cannot 
be assumed, it must be taught. What specific instructions will you provide your grouped 
pupils? _________________________________<BR>
<HR>
<HR>

<H6>6. Teacher as consultant: </H6>
Questions are given back to groups for solution. 
</BODY>
</HTML>
</DOC>
